WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.760
- The following is a conversation
with Joel David Hamkins, a

00:00:03.820 --> 00:00:07.780
mathematician and philosopher
specializing in set theory,

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:10.420
the foundation of mathematics
and the nature of

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:14.100
infinity. He is the number one highest

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:17.360
rated user on MathOverflow,
which I think is a legendary

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.140
accomplishment. MathOverflow, by
the way, is like StackOverflow

00:00:21.260 --> 00:00:24.880
but for research mathematicians. He is

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.880
also the author of several
books, including Proof

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:32.650
in the Art of Mathematics
and Lectures on the

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:37.240
Philosophy of Mathematics.
And he has a great blog,

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:43.720
infinitelymore.xyz. This
is a super technical and

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:47.940
super fun conversation about the
foundation of modern mathematics

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.080
and some mind-bending
ideas about infinity,

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:55.630
nature of reality, truth,
and the mathematical

00:00:55.740 --> 00:01:00.880
paradoxes that challenged some of the
greatest minds of the 20th century.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:10.460
I have been hiding from the world a bit,
reading, thinking, writing, soul-searching,

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:14.360
as we all do every once in a while.
But mostly, just deeply focused

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:18.240
on work and preparing mentally
for some challenging travel I

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:25.810
plan to take on in the new year. Through
all of it, a recurring thought comes to me,

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:29.040
how damn lucky I am to
be alive and to get to

00:01:29.060 --> 00:01:32.570
experience so much love
from folks across the

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:36.960
world. I want to take this
moment to say thank you

00:01:37.780 --> 00:01:40.870
from the bottom of my heart
for everything, for your

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:44.840
support, for the many amazing
conversations I've had

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:49.300
with people across the world.
I got a little bit of hate

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:54.230
and a whole lot of love,
and I wouldn't have it

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:58.120
any other way. I'm grateful for all of it.

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:01.700
This is the Lex Fridman Podcast. To
support it, please check out our

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:05.520
sponsors in the description,
where you can also

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:13.200
find ways to contact me, ask questions,
give feedback, and so on. And now, dear

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:16.590
friends, here's Joel David Hamkins.

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:21.300
Some infinities are bigger
than others. This idea from

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:25.120
Cantor at the end of the 19th
century, I think it's fair to

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:29.090
say, broke mathematics
before rebuilding it. And

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:32.800
I also read that this was a devastating
and transformative discovery for

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:36.360
several reasons. So one,
it created a theological

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:40.200
crisis. Because infinity is associated
with God, how could there be multiple

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:43.420
infinities? And also,
Cantor was deeply religious

00:02:43.460 --> 00:02:47.180
himself. Second, there's a
kind of mathematical civil

00:02:47.260 --> 00:02:53.760
war. The leading German mathematician
Kronecker called Cantor a corrupter of youth

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:58.570
and tried to block his career. Third, many

00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:02.520
fascinating paradoxes emerged
from this, like Russell's

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:06.420
paradox, about the set of all sets
that don't contain themselves,

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:09.020
and those threatened to
make all of mathematics

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:13.060
inconsistent. And finally, on the
psychological side and the personal

00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:16.920
side, Cantor's own breakdown.
He literally went mad,

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:20.760
spending his final years in and
out of sanatoriums, obsessed with

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:24.420
proving the continuum hypothesis.
So, laying that all out on the

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:30.920
table, can you explain the idea of
infinity, that some infinities are

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:35.780
larger than others, and why was this
so transformative to mathematics?

00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:39.800
- Well, that's a really great
question. I would want to start

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:43.540
talking about infinity and
telling the story much

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:47.280
earlier than Cantor, actually, because,
I mean, you can go all the way

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:50.380
back to Ancient Greek times when Aristotle

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:55.020
emphasized the potential
aspect of infinity as opposed

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:59.060
to the impossibility, according
to him, of achieving an actual

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:02.640
infinity. And Archimedes'
method of exhaustion where

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:06.500
he is trying to understand
the area of a region

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:10.480
by carving it into more and
more triangles, say, and

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:14.440
sort of exhausting the area and thereby
understanding the total area in terms

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:17.519
of the sum of the areas of the
pieces that he put into it.

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:22.270
And it proceeded on this kind of potential
understanding of infinity for hundreds of years,

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:25.909
thousands of years. Almost
all mathematicians were

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:29.969
almost all mathematicians
were potentialists only and

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.600
thought that it was incoherent
to speak of an actual

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:41.120
infinity at all. Galileo is an extremely
prominent exception to this, though he

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:44.840
argued against this sort
of potentialist orthodoxy

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.140
in The Dialogue of Two New
Sciences. Really lovely

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:56.740
account there that he gave. And that the...
In many ways, Galileo was anticipating

00:04:56.780 --> 00:05:00.220
Cantor's developments, except he
couldn't quite push it all the way

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:05.920
through and ended up throwing
up his hands in confusion

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:10.320
in a sense. I mean, the Galileo
paradox is the idea or the

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:14.280
observation that if you think
about the natural numbers,

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:18.160
I would start with zero but I think maybe
he would start with one. The numbers one,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:22.000
two, three, four, and so on, and
you think about which of those

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:25.840
numbers are perfect
squares. So zero squared is

00:05:25.860 --> 00:05:29.560
zero and one squared is one
and two squared is four, three

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:33.520
squared is nine, 16, 25,
and so on. And Galileo

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:37.130
observed that, that the
perfect squares can be

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:41.000
put into a one-to-one
correspondence with all of the

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:44.730
numbers. I mean, we just did
it. I associated every number

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:48.360
with its square. And so it seems

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:52.290
like on the basis of this
one-to-one correspondence that

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:55.980
there should be exactly the same number of

00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:59.520
squares, perfect squares
as there are numbers, and

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:03.300
yet there's all the gaps in
between the perfect squares,

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:10.092
right? And, and this suggests that there
should be fewer perfect squares, more

00:06:10.132 --> 00:06:14.092
numbers than squares because the numbers
include all the squares plus a lot more in

00:06:14.132 --> 00:06:20.352
between them, right? And Galileo was quite
troubled by this observation because

00:06:21.152 --> 00:06:24.611
he took it to cause a kind
of incoherence in the

00:06:24.672 --> 00:06:28.412
comparison of infinite quantities,
right? And another example

00:06:28.472 --> 00:06:32.272
is, if you take two line
segments of different lengths,

00:06:33.172 --> 00:06:37.111
and you can imagine drawing
a kind of foliation,

00:06:37.152 --> 00:06:41.032
a fan of lines that connect
them. So the endpoints are

00:06:41.072 --> 00:06:45.062
matched from the shorter to the longer
segment, and the midpoints are matched and

00:06:45.072 --> 00:06:48.521
so on. So spreading out the
lines as you go. And so every

00:06:48.572 --> 00:06:52.252
point on the shorter line
would be associated with

00:06:52.292 --> 00:06:55.852
a, a unique distinct point
on the longer line in a

00:06:55.892 --> 00:06:59.672
one-to-one way. And so
it seems like the two

00:06:59.682 --> 00:07:03.472
line segments have the same number of
points on them because of that, even

00:07:03.512 --> 00:07:07.322
though the longer one is longer. And so it

00:07:07.352 --> 00:07:11.271
makes, again, a kind of confusion
over our ideas about infinity. And

00:07:11.312 --> 00:07:13.772
also with two circles,
if you just place them

00:07:13.912 --> 00:07:17.632
concentrically and draw
the rays from the center,

00:07:17.692 --> 00:07:20.991
then every point on the
smaller circle is associated

00:07:21.032 --> 00:07:24.991
with a corresponding point on the
larger circle, you know, in a

00:07:25.072 --> 00:07:28.972
one-to-one way. And, and again,
that seems to show that the

00:07:28.991 --> 00:07:32.912
smaller circle has the same number of
points on it as the larger one, precisely

00:07:32.972 --> 00:07:36.932
precisely because they can be put
into this one-to-one correspondence.

00:07:36.991 --> 00:07:40.712
Of course, the contemporary attitude
about this situation is that those two

00:07:40.752 --> 00:07:44.072
infinities are exactly the same,
and that Galileo was right in those

00:07:44.111 --> 00:07:47.592
observations about the equinumerosity.
We would talk about it now

00:07:47.632 --> 00:07:51.592
by appealing to what I call the
Cantor-Hume principle, or some people

00:07:51.652 --> 00:07:55.432
just call it Hume's principle, which
is the idea that if you have two

00:07:55.491 --> 00:07:59.232
collections, whether they're finite
or infinite, then we want to

00:07:59.312 --> 00:08:02.982
say that those two collections
have the same size. They're

00:08:03.012 --> 00:08:06.732
equinumerous if and only
if there's a one-to-one

00:08:06.792 --> 00:08:10.292
correspondence between those
collections. Galileo was

00:08:10.352 --> 00:08:14.272
observing that line segments of
different lengths are equinumerous,

00:08:14.332 --> 00:08:18.292
and the perfect squares are
equinumerous with all of the

00:08:18.312 --> 00:08:22.232
natural numbers, and any two
circles are equinumerous, and so

00:08:22.292 --> 00:08:25.881
on. The tension between the Cantor-Hume

00:08:25.952 --> 00:08:29.902
principle and what could be called
Euclid's principle, which is that the

00:08:30.012 --> 00:08:34.011
whole is always greater than the
part, is a principle that Euclid

00:08:34.031 --> 00:08:37.952
appealed to in the Elements many
times when he's calculating

00:08:38.052 --> 00:08:41.962
area and so on. It's a basic idea

00:08:42.011 --> 00:08:45.852
that if something is just a
part of another thing, then the

00:08:45.892 --> 00:08:49.812
whole is greater than the
part. So what Galileo

00:08:50.352 --> 00:08:53.732
was troubled by was this tension between

00:08:54.492 --> 00:08:57.312
what we call the Cantor-Hume
principle and Euclid's

00:08:57.692 --> 00:09:01.462
principle. It wasn't fully resolved, I

00:09:01.492 --> 00:09:05.392
think, until Cantor. He's
the one who really explained

00:09:05.452 --> 00:09:09.412
so clearly about these different
sizes of infinity and so on

00:09:09.472 --> 00:09:12.992
in a way that was so compelling. He

00:09:13.052 --> 00:09:16.792
exhibited two different
infinite sets and proved that

00:09:17.192 --> 00:09:20.052
they're not equinumerous; they
can't be put into one-to-one

00:09:20.312 --> 00:09:23.952
correspondence. It's
traditional to talk about the

00:09:23.972 --> 00:09:27.922
uncountability of the real numbers.
Cantor's big result was that the

00:09:27.972 --> 00:09:31.752
set of all real numbers is an
uncountable set. Maybe if we're

00:09:31.792 --> 00:09:35.572
going to talk about countable sets,
then I would suggest that we talk

00:09:35.632 --> 00:09:39.771
about Hilbert's Hotel, which really
makes that idea perfectly clear.

00:09:39.812 --> 00:09:41.352
- Yeah, let's talk about Hilbert's Hotel.

00:09:41.932 --> 00:09:45.912
- Hilbert's Hotel is a hotel with
infinitely many rooms. Each

00:09:45.972 --> 00:09:49.872
room is a full floor suite. So
there's floor zero... I always

00:09:49.912 --> 00:09:53.592
start with zero because for me, the natural
numbers start with zero, although that's

00:09:54.052 --> 00:09:57.552
maybe a point of contention for
some mathematicians. The other

00:09:57.592 --> 00:09:58.482
mathematicians are wrong.

00:09:58.482 --> 00:10:01.882
- Like I mentioned, I'm a programmer, so starting
at zero is a wonderful place to start.

00:10:01.892 --> 00:10:05.732
- Exactly. So there's floor zero,
floor one, floor two, or room zero,

00:10:05.792 --> 00:10:09.372
one, two, three, and so on, just like the
natural numbers. So Hilbert's Hotel has a

00:10:09.432 --> 00:10:11.652
room for every natural number,

00:10:13.172 --> 00:10:16.992
and it's completely full. There's
a person occupying room N for

00:10:17.052 --> 00:10:20.792
every N. But meanwhile, a
new guest comes up to the

00:10:20.812 --> 00:10:24.471
desk and wants a room. "Can I have
a room, please?" The manager says,

00:10:24.712 --> 00:10:26.902
"Hang on a second, just give me a moment."

00:10:27.752 --> 00:10:31.031
You see, when the other guests had
checked in, they had to sign an

00:10:31.092 --> 00:10:35.072
agreement with the hotel that maybe

00:10:35.112 --> 00:10:38.712
there would be some changing
of the rooms during this stay.

00:10:39.552 --> 00:10:43.512
So the manager sent a message
up to all the current

00:10:43.572 --> 00:10:47.372
occupants and told every
person, "Hey, can you

00:10:47.672 --> 00:10:51.452
move up one room, please?" So the
person in room five would move to

00:10:51.492 --> 00:10:54.932
room six, and the person in room six would
move to room seven and so on. And everyone

00:10:55.012 --> 00:10:58.752
moved at the same time. And of course, we
never want to be placing two different

00:10:58.791 --> 00:11:02.072
guests in the same room, and we want
everyone to have their own private room

00:11:02.232 --> 00:11:06.152
and... But when you move everyone
up one room, then the bottom

00:11:06.212 --> 00:11:10.172
room, room zero, becomes available, of
course. And so he can put the new guest in

00:11:10.192 --> 00:11:13.652
that room. So even when
you have infinitely many

00:11:13.692 --> 00:11:17.652
things, then the new guest can be
accommodated. And that's a way of

00:11:17.812 --> 00:11:21.791
showing how the particular
infinity of the occupants of

00:11:21.812 --> 00:11:25.712
Hilbert's Hotel, it violates
Euclid's principle. I

00:11:25.752 --> 00:11:28.012
mean, it exactly illustrates
this idea because

00:11:28.992 --> 00:11:32.771
adding one more element to a set
didn't make it larger, because we

00:11:32.812 --> 00:11:36.291
can still have a one-to-one
correspondence between the total new

00:11:36.412 --> 00:11:40.472
guests and the old guests
by the room number, right?

00:11:40.531 --> 00:11:44.972
- So, to just say one more
time, the hotel is full.

00:11:45.052 --> 00:11:45.972
- The hotel is full.

00:11:46.312 --> 00:11:49.952
- And then you could still squeeze
in one more, and that breaks

00:11:50.952 --> 00:11:54.652
the traditional notion of
mathematics and breaks

00:11:54.732 --> 00:11:58.692
people's brains when they try to think
about infinity, I suppose. This is

00:11:58.791 --> 00:11:59.852
a property of infinity.

00:11:59.892 --> 00:12:03.632
- It's a property of infinity
that sometimes when you add an

00:12:03.712 --> 00:12:07.692
element to a set, it doesn't
get larger. That's what this

00:12:07.732 --> 00:12:11.599
example shows. But one
can go on with Hilbert's

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:15.010
Hotel, for example. I mean,
maybe the next day, you know,

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:19.260
20 people show up all at once. We can
easily do the same trick again, just move

00:12:19.339 --> 00:12:23.219
everybody up 20 rooms.
And then we would have 20

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:26.439
empty rooms at the bottom, and
those new 20 guests could go

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:33.339
in. But on the following weekend,
a giant bus pulled up, Hilbert's

00:12:33.459 --> 00:12:37.079
bus. And Hilbert's bus has, of course,

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:40.500
infinitely many seats. There's Seat Zero,
Seat One, Seat Two, Seat Three, and so

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:45.219
on. And so one wants to... You know,
all the people on the bus want

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:49.219
to check into the hotel, but the hotel is
completely full. So what is the manager going to

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:53.250
do? And when I talk about Hilbert's Hotel,

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:56.920
when I teach Hilbert's Hotel in
class, I always demand that the

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:00.579
students provide, you know, the
explanation of- of how to do it.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:02.270
So maybe I'll ask you.

00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:06.280
Can you tell me, yeah, what is your idea about
how to fit them all in the hotel, everyone

00:13:06.339 --> 00:13:08.579
on the bus, and also
the current occupants?

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:14.760
- You separate the hotel into even and
odd rooms, and you squeeze in the new

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:19.020
Hilbert bus people into the odd
rooms and the previous occupants

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:20.089
go into the even rooms.

00:13:20.089 --> 00:13:23.920
- That's exactly right. That's a
very easy way to do it. If you

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:27.939
just tell all the current guests
to double their room number, so in

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:31.680
Room N, you move to Room 2 times N.
So they're all going to get their own

00:13:31.839 --> 00:13:35.720
private room, the new room, and it will always be
an even number 'cause 2 times N is always an even

00:13:35.780 --> 00:13:39.640
number. And so all the odd rooms
become empty that way. And now we can

00:13:39.699 --> 00:13:42.880
put the bus occupants into
the odd-numbered rooms.

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:47.420
- And by doing so, you have now shoved
an infinity into another infinity.

00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:51.079
- That's right. So what it really shows...
I mean, another way of thinking

00:13:51.180 --> 00:13:54.930
about it is that, well, we
can define that a set is

00:13:54.939 --> 00:13:58.220
countable if it is equinumerous
with a set of natural

00:13:58.260 --> 00:14:02.199
numbers. And a kind of easy
way to understand what that's

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:04.000
saying in terms of Hilbert's Hotel is that

00:14:04.939 --> 00:14:08.780
a set is countable if it fits into
Hilbert's Hotel, 'cause Hilbert's Hotel

00:14:08.819 --> 00:14:12.660
basically is the set of natural numbers
in terms of the room numbers. So to be

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:16.319
equinumerous with a set of natural numbers is
just the same thing as to fit into Hilbert's

00:14:16.359 --> 00:14:18.920
Hotel. And so what we've shown is that

00:14:20.439 --> 00:14:24.140
if you have two countably
infinite sets, then their

00:14:24.260 --> 00:14:28.079
union is also countably infinite. If you
put them together and form a new set

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:32.400
with all of the elements of either of
them, then that union set is still

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:35.760
only countably infinite.
It didn't get bigger.

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:40.589
And that's a remarkable
property for a notion

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:43.890
of infinity to have, I suppose. But
if you thought that there was only

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:47.970
one kind of infinity, then it wouldn't be
surprising at all, because if you take

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.640
two infinite sets and put them together, then it's
still infinite. And so if there were only one kind of

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:53.270
infinity, then it
shouldn't be surprising...

00:14:53.270 --> 00:14:57.160
that the union of two countable sets
is countable. So there's another way

00:14:57.199 --> 00:15:01.560
to push this a bit harder, and
that is when Hilbert's train

00:15:02.420 --> 00:15:08.260
arrives, and Hilbert's train has
infinitely many train cars...

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:13.560
...and each train car has
infinitely many seats.

00:15:13.599 --> 00:15:16.819
And so we have an infinity
of infinities of the train

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:20.050
passengers together with the
current occupants of the

00:15:20.079 --> 00:15:24.770
hotel, and everybody on the train
wants to check in to Hilbert's Hotel.

00:15:26.459 --> 00:15:29.980
So the manager can, again, of
course, send a message up to all the

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:33.900
rooms telling every person to double

00:15:33.959 --> 00:15:37.459
their room number again. And
so that will occupy all the

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:40.959
even-numbered rooms again,
and but free up again the

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:44.980
odd-numbered rooms. So somehow, we
want to put the train passengers

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:49.099
into the odd-numbered rooms. And so while

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:54.760
every train passenger is on some
car, let's say Car C and Seat S,

00:15:55.880 --> 00:15:59.069
so somehow, we have to take these
two coordinates, you know, C,

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:03.480
S, the car number and the
seat number, and produce from

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:06.640
it an odd number in a one-to-one way, you

00:16:06.699 --> 00:16:10.520
know? And that's actually
not very difficult. In

00:16:10.579 --> 00:16:16.579
fact, one can just use, say... An easy
way to do it is to just use the number

00:16:18.060 --> 00:16:25.260
3 to the C times 5 to the S. 3 to the
C, 3 to the car number, so 3 x 3 x

00:16:25.480 --> 00:16:29.420
3, you know, the number of the
car. You multiply 3 by itself, the

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:33.280
number of the train car, and
then you multiply 5 by itself

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:37.099
the seat number of times, and then you
multiply those two numbers together. So

00:16:37.319 --> 00:16:41.089
3 to the C times 5 to the S. That's

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:44.900
always an odd number, 'cause the
prime factorization has only 3s and

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.509
5s in it. There's no 2
there. So therefore, it's

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:52.420
definitely an odd number, and
it's always different because

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:56.960
of the uniqueness of prime
factorization. So every number

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.700
can be factored uniquely into primes.
So if you have a number of that form,

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:04.599
then you can just factor it, and that
tells you the exponent on 3 and the

00:17:04.659 --> 00:17:08.619
exponent on 5. And so you know exactly
which person it was, which car

00:17:08.639 --> 00:17:10.520
they came from, and which
seat they came from.

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:14.869
- And prime factorization is
every single number can be

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:19.569
decomposed into the atoms of
mathematics, which is the prime

00:17:19.639 --> 00:17:23.230
numbers. You can multiply them
together to achieve that number.

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:27.940
And that's prime factorization. You're
showing 3 and 5 are both prime numbers,

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:33.879
odd. So through this magical
formula, you can deal with this

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:41.320
train, infinite number of cars, with each
car having infinite number of seats.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:45.139
- Exactly right. We've proved
that if you have countably many

00:17:45.200 --> 00:17:48.090
countable sets, then the union of those

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:52.110
sets, putting all those sets
together into one giant set,

00:17:52.159 --> 00:17:55.889
is still countable. You know, because the train
cars are each countable, plus the current

00:17:55.900 --> 00:17:59.850
hotel. It's sort of like another train car, if
you want to think about it that way. The current

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:03.690
occupants of the hotel could, you
know, have the same number as

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:07.659
any of the train cars. So
putting countably many

00:18:07.679 --> 00:18:11.150
countable sets together to
make one big union set is

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:15.252
still countable. It's quite
remarkable, I think. I mean when

00:18:15.312 --> 00:18:19.161
I first learned this many, many years
ago, I was completely shocked by it and

00:18:19.232 --> 00:18:23.072
transfixed by it. It was quite
amazing to me that this notion

00:18:23.111 --> 00:18:26.911
of countable infinity could be
closed under this process of

00:18:26.992 --> 00:18:30.532
infinitely many infinities
adding up still to the very same

00:18:30.572 --> 00:18:34.502
infinity, which is a strong instance, a

00:18:34.631 --> 00:18:38.591
strong violation of Euclid's principle
once again, right? So, the new

00:18:38.732 --> 00:18:42.552
set that we built is... has
many more elements than the old

00:18:42.611 --> 00:18:46.420
set in the sense that there are additional
elements, but it doesn't have many

00:18:46.512 --> 00:18:50.171
more elements in terms of its size
because it's still just a countable

00:18:50.232 --> 00:18:53.171
infinity and it fits into Hilbert's Hotel.

00:18:53.272 --> 00:18:57.192
- Have you been able to sort of
internalize a good intuition about

00:18:58.012 --> 00:19:04.732
countable infinity? Because that is a pretty
weird thing. You can have a countably

00:19:04.812 --> 00:19:08.611
infinite set of countably infinite
sets, and you can shove it

00:19:08.671 --> 00:19:11.492
all in and it still is a
countable infinite set.

00:19:11.552 --> 00:19:15.411
- Yeah, that's exactly
right. I mean, I guess,

00:19:15.752 --> 00:19:19.651
of course, when you work with
these notions, the argument of

00:19:19.752 --> 00:19:23.631
of Hilbert's Hotel becomes kind of
clear. There are many other ways to

00:19:23.672 --> 00:19:27.371
talk about it too. For example,
let's think about, say,

00:19:27.411 --> 00:19:31.391
the integer lattice, the
grid of points that you

00:19:31.452 --> 00:19:35.371
get by taking pairs of natural
numbers, say, so the upper

00:19:35.512 --> 00:19:37.911
right quadrant of the
integer lattice, yeah?

00:19:38.812 --> 00:19:42.792
So there's the, you know, row zero, row one, row two and
so on, column zero, column one, column two and so on,

00:19:42.851 --> 00:19:49.371
and each row and column has a countable
infinity of points on it, right?

00:19:50.272 --> 00:19:53.692
So those dots, if you
think about them as dots,

00:19:54.252 --> 00:19:57.391
are really the same as the train
cars if you think about each column

00:19:58.052 --> 00:20:01.952
of... in that integer lattice, it's
a countable infinity. It's like one

00:20:02.052 --> 00:20:05.871
train car and then there's the next train
car next to it, and then the next column

00:20:05.891 --> 00:20:07.282
next to that, the next train car.

00:20:08.472 --> 00:20:12.012
And so, but if we think about it in
this grid manner, then I can imagine

00:20:12.072 --> 00:20:16.052
a kind of winding path
winding through these grid

00:20:16.091 --> 00:20:19.702
points, like up and down the diagonals.

00:20:19.702 --> 00:20:23.660
Winding back and forth. So I start at
the corner point and then I go down,

00:20:23.712 --> 00:20:27.411
up and to the left, and then down and to the right,
up and to the left, down and to the right, and so on,

00:20:28.351 --> 00:20:34.022
in such a way that I'm going to
hit every grid point on this path.

00:20:34.091 --> 00:20:38.380
So, this gives me a way of assigning
room numbers to the points.

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:42.052
Because every grid point
is going to be the

00:20:42.232 --> 00:20:46.121
Nth point on that path
for some N. And that

00:20:46.172 --> 00:20:49.911
that gives a correspondence between the
grid points and the natural numbers

00:20:49.952 --> 00:20:53.831
themselves. So it's a kind of different
picture. Before, we used this 3

00:20:53.911 --> 00:20:57.232
to the C, 5 times 5 to the
S, which is a kind of, you

00:20:57.272 --> 00:21:01.252
know, overly arithmetic way to
think about it. But there's a kind

00:21:01.292 --> 00:21:05.032
of direct way to understand
that it's still a

00:21:05.052 --> 00:21:08.692
countable infinity when you have countably
many countable sets, because you can just

00:21:09.292 --> 00:21:13.272
start putting them on this list. And as long
as you give each of the infinite collections a

00:21:13.351 --> 00:21:17.222
chance to add one more
person to the list, then

00:21:17.252 --> 00:21:20.911
you're going to accommodate everyone
in any of the sets in one list.

00:21:20.952 --> 00:21:24.772
- Yeah, it's a really nice visual way to think about
it. You just zigzag your way across the grid

00:21:25.732 --> 00:21:29.572
to make sure everybody's included. That
gives you an algorithm for including

00:21:29.611 --> 00:21:33.591
everybody. So, can you speak
to the uncountable infinities?

00:21:33.611 --> 00:21:33.812
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:21:33.831 --> 00:21:35.611
- What are the integers
and the real numbers-

00:21:35.651 --> 00:21:35.982
- Correct

00:21:36.172 --> 00:21:38.411
- and what is the line that
Cantor was able to find?

00:21:38.431 --> 00:21:43.081
- Maybe there's one more step I
want to insert before doing that.

00:21:43.081 --> 00:21:50.131
Which is the rational numbers. So
we did pairs of natural numbers.

00:21:50.172 --> 00:21:54.111
Right? That's the train car,
basically. But maybe it's a little

00:21:54.131 --> 00:21:57.572
bit informative to think about the
rational, the fractions, the set of

00:21:57.651 --> 00:21:59.812
fractions, or rational numbers,

00:22:00.732 --> 00:22:04.452
because a lot of people maybe have an
expectation that maybe this is a bigger

00:22:04.472 --> 00:22:08.192
infinity because the rational
numbers are densely ordered.

00:22:08.232 --> 00:22:12.052
Between any two fractions, you
can find another fraction, right?

00:22:12.172 --> 00:22:17.922
The average of two fractions is another
fraction. And so, sometimes people,

00:22:18.812 --> 00:22:22.472
it seems to be a different
character than the

00:22:22.532 --> 00:22:26.452
integers, which are discretely ordered, right?
From any integer, there's a next one and a

00:22:26.492 --> 00:22:29.081
previous one, and so on. But
that's not true in the rational

00:22:29.111 --> 00:22:33.011
numbers. And yet, the rational numbers are

00:22:33.071 --> 00:22:39.111
also still only a countable infinity.
And the way to see that is actually

00:22:40.012 --> 00:22:43.931
it's just exactly the same as Hilbert's
train again, because every fraction

00:22:43.972 --> 00:22:47.192
consists of two integers:
the numerator and the

00:22:47.252 --> 00:22:51.052
denominator. And so if
I tell you two natural

00:22:51.111 --> 00:22:54.992
numbers, then you know what fraction
I'm talking about. I mean, plus the

00:22:55.032 --> 00:22:58.931
sign issue, I mean if it's positive or
negative. But if you just think about the

00:22:58.972 --> 00:23:02.812
positive fractions, then, you know,
you have the numbers of the form

00:23:02.871 --> 00:23:06.512
P over Q, where Q is not
zero. So you can still do

00:23:06.712 --> 00:23:10.591
3 to the P times 5 to the
Q. The same idea works.

00:23:11.111 --> 00:23:14.431
with the rational numbers.
So this is still a countable

00:23:14.552 --> 00:23:17.692
set. And you might think, "Well, every set

00:23:18.652 --> 00:23:22.552
is going to be countable because there's only
one infinity." I mean, if that's a kind of

00:23:22.572 --> 00:23:26.451
perspective maybe that you're
adopting, but it's not

00:23:26.512 --> 00:23:30.431
true, and that's the profound achievement
that Cantor made is proving that the set of

00:23:30.472 --> 00:23:33.822
real numbers is not a countable
infinity. It's a strictly larger

00:23:33.831 --> 00:23:37.472
infinity, and therefore
there's more than one

00:23:37.532 --> 00:23:40.792
concept of infinity, more
than one size of infinity.

00:23:40.812 --> 00:23:44.302
- So let's talk about the real numbers. What are
the real numbers? Why do they break infinity?

00:23:44.312 --> 00:23:49.871
The countable infinity. Looking
it up on Perplexity, real numbers

00:23:49.911 --> 00:23:53.732
include all the numbers that can be represented
on the number line, encompassing both

00:23:53.851 --> 00:23:57.552
rational and irrational numbers. We've
spoken about the rational numbers, and the

00:23:57.591 --> 00:24:01.552
rational numbers, by the way, are by
definition, the numbers that can be represented

00:24:01.611 --> 00:24:05.391
as a fraction of two integers.

00:24:05.431 --> 00:24:09.201
- That's right. So with the real numbers,
we have the algebraic numbers. We

00:24:09.351 --> 00:24:13.252
have, of course, all the rational numbers. The
integers and the rationals are all part of the

00:24:13.272 --> 00:24:16.532
real number system. But then also, we have
the algebraic numbers like the square root of

00:24:16.851 --> 00:24:20.752
2 or the cube root of 5 and
so on. Numbers that solve an

00:24:20.792 --> 00:24:24.271
algebraic equation over the integers,
those are known as algebraic

00:24:24.351 --> 00:24:27.852
numbers. It was an open question
for a long time whether that was

00:24:27.964 --> 00:24:31.664
all of the real numbers
or whether there would

00:24:31.704 --> 00:24:35.484
exist numbers that are the
transcendental numbers. The

00:24:35.533 --> 00:24:38.724
transcendental numbers are real
numbers that are not algebraic.

00:24:38.744 --> 00:24:42.343
- And we won't even go to the surreal numbers
about which you have a wonderful blog post.

00:24:42.384 --> 00:24:43.823
We'll talk about that a little bit later.

00:24:43.884 --> 00:24:47.863
- Oh, great. So it was Liouville
who first proved that

00:24:47.924 --> 00:24:51.853
there are transcendental numbers, and
he exhibited a very specific number

00:24:51.924 --> 00:24:55.764
that's now known as the Liouville
constant, which is a transcendental

00:24:55.884 --> 00:24:59.303
number. Cantor also famously
proved that there are many,

00:24:59.363 --> 00:25:03.123
many transcendental numbers.
In fact, it follows from his

00:25:03.224 --> 00:25:07.132
argument on the uncountability of
the real numbers that there are

00:25:07.184 --> 00:25:12.214
uncountably many transcendental numbers.
So most real numbers are transcendental.

00:25:12.244 --> 00:25:15.394
- And again, going to Perplexity, "Transcendental
numbers are 'real' or 'complex'

00:25:15.424 --> 00:25:19.244
numbers; they are not the root
of any nonzero polynomial with

00:25:19.283 --> 00:25:23.224
integer or rational coefficients.
This means they cannot

00:25:23.244 --> 00:25:27.204
be expressed as solutions to algebraic
equations with integer coefficients,

00:25:27.283 --> 00:25:30.234
setting them apart from
algebraic numbers."

00:25:31.144 --> 00:25:35.083
- So some of the famous transcendental
numbers would include the number pi,

00:25:35.204 --> 00:25:40.103
you know, the 3.14159265 and so on.

00:25:41.063 --> 00:25:44.303
So that's a transcendental number.
Also, Euler's constant, the

00:25:44.444 --> 00:25:47.664
e, like e to the x, the
exponential function.

00:25:47.744 --> 00:25:51.684
- So you could say that some of the sexiest numbers
in mathematics are all transcendental numbers?

00:25:51.783 --> 00:25:55.603
- Absolutely. That's true. Yeah, yeah. Although,
you know, I don't know, square root of two is

00:25:55.644 --> 00:25:55.904
pretty

00:25:56.283 --> 00:26:00.593
- Square root. All right. So it depends.
Let's not... Beauty can be found in

00:26:00.593 --> 00:26:02.404
in all the different
kinds of sets, but yeah.

00:26:02.414 --> 00:26:06.363
- That's right. And if you have a kind of simplicity
attitude, then zero and one are looking pretty good too,

00:26:06.424 --> 00:26:07.533
so... And they're definitely not

00:26:07.823 --> 00:26:10.803
- Sorry to take that tangent, but what is
your favorite number? Do you have one?

00:26:10.924 --> 00:26:12.593
- Oh, gosh. You know-

00:26:12.593 --> 00:26:13.363
- Is it zero?

00:26:13.404 --> 00:26:17.164
- Did you know there's a
proof that every number is

00:26:17.224 --> 00:26:22.004
interesting? You can prove it, because...

00:26:22.083 --> 00:26:23.484
- Yeah? What's that proof look like?

00:26:23.504 --> 00:26:23.823
- Yeah, okay.

00:26:23.843 --> 00:26:24.504
- How do you even begin?

00:26:24.543 --> 00:26:25.684
- I'm gonna prove to you-

00:26:25.803 --> 00:26:25.974
- Okay

00:26:26.004 --> 00:26:28.464
- ...that every natural
number is interesting.

00:26:28.484 --> 00:26:28.974
- Okay.

00:26:29.004 --> 00:26:32.764
- Yeah. I mean, zero's interesting because
it's the additive identity, right?

00:26:32.783 --> 00:26:36.263
That's pretty interesting. And one is
the multiplicative identity, so when you

00:26:36.364 --> 00:26:40.283
multiply it by any other number, you
just get that number back, right? And

00:26:40.404 --> 00:26:46.053
two is, you know, the first prime number.
That's super interesting, right? And-

00:26:46.103 --> 00:26:50.744
Okay. So one can go on this way and
give specific reasons, but I wanna

00:26:50.764 --> 00:26:54.684
prove as a general principle that every
number is interesting. And this is

00:26:54.724 --> 00:27:02.224
the proof. Suppose, toward contradiction,
that there were some boring numbers.

00:27:02.343 --> 00:27:03.843
Okay?

00:27:03.964 --> 00:27:04.194
- Oh, okay.

00:27:04.204 --> 00:27:06.583
- But if there was an uninteresting number-

00:27:06.664 --> 00:27:06.884
- Yes

00:27:07.404 --> 00:27:11.024
- ...then there would have to be a
smallest uninteresting number.

00:27:11.063 --> 00:27:13.444
- Mm-hmm. Yes.

00:27:13.504 --> 00:27:17.343
- But that's a contradiction, because the
smallest uninteresting number is a super

00:27:17.404 --> 00:27:23.043
interesting property
to have. So therefore-

00:27:23.063 --> 00:27:24.184
- Ah, that's good.

00:27:24.323 --> 00:27:26.643
- ...there cannot be any boring numbers.

00:27:26.724 --> 00:27:30.543
- I'm gonna have to try to find a hole in
that proof- because there's a lot of

00:27:30.583 --> 00:27:33.434
baked in in the word interesting,
but yeah, that's a beautiful.

00:27:33.484 --> 00:27:34.103
- Right.

00:27:34.143 --> 00:27:38.043
- That doesn't say anything about the transcendental
numbers, about the real numbers that you

00:27:38.103 --> 00:27:39.004
just proved from just-

00:27:39.024 --> 00:27:39.033
- That's right

00:27:39.033 --> 00:27:39.984
- ...four natural numbers.

00:27:40.004 --> 00:27:42.543
- Yeah. Okay, should we get back
to Cantor's argument, or-

00:27:42.583 --> 00:27:43.204
- Sure.

00:27:43.244 --> 00:27:46.843
You've masterfully avoided the question.
Well, you basically said, "I love all

00:27:46.924 --> 00:27:47.364
numbers."

00:27:47.424 --> 00:27:48.174
- Yeah, basically.

00:27:48.303 --> 00:27:49.343
- Is that what you said?

00:27:49.364 --> 00:27:49.813
- Yeah. That was my intention.

00:27:49.823 --> 00:27:51.643
- Back to Cantor's argument. Let's go.

00:27:51.704 --> 00:27:55.444
- Okay, so Cantor wants to prove that

00:27:55.524 --> 00:27:59.393
the infinity of the real
numbers is different and

00:27:59.444 --> 00:28:03.364
strictly larger than the infinity of
the natural numbers. So the natural

00:28:03.404 --> 00:28:06.764
numbers are the numbers that
start with zero and add one

00:28:06.864 --> 00:28:10.803
successively, so zero, one, two, three,
and so on. And the real numbers, as

00:28:10.843 --> 00:28:14.083
we said, are the numbers
that come from the number

00:28:14.143 --> 00:28:18.063
line, including all the integers and the
rationals and the algebraic numbers and

00:28:18.083 --> 00:28:21.464
the transcendental numbers and all
of those numbers altogether. Now,

00:28:21.583 --> 00:28:25.464
obviously, since the natural numbers
are included in the real numbers,

00:28:25.524 --> 00:28:29.484
we know that the real numbers
are at least as large as

00:28:29.543 --> 00:28:33.204
the natural numbers. And so the
claim that we want to prove is that

00:28:34.004 --> 00:28:39.944
it's strictly larger. So suppose
that it wasn't strictly larger. So

00:28:40.404 --> 00:28:44.373
then they would have the same size.
But to have the same size, remember,

00:28:44.643 --> 00:28:48.524
means by definition that
there's a one-to-one

00:28:48.563 --> 00:28:52.504
correspondence between them.
So we suppose that the real

00:28:52.543 --> 00:28:56.444
numbers can be put into one-to-one
correspondence with the natural numbers.

00:28:57.603 --> 00:29:01.323
So therefore, for every natural number N, we
have a real number, let's call it R sub N.

00:29:01.643 --> 00:29:05.623
R sub N is the Nth real number on the

00:29:05.684 --> 00:29:09.484
list. Basically, our assumption allows
us to think of the real numbers as

00:29:09.543 --> 00:29:13.103
having been placed on a
list, R1, R2, and so on.

00:29:13.164 --> 00:29:16.244
Okay, and now I'm going to define
the number Z, and it's going to

00:29:16.283 --> 00:29:20.004
be... The integer part is going to
be a zero, and then I'm going to

00:29:20.424 --> 00:29:24.283
put a decimal place, and then I'm going to
start specifying the digits of this number

00:29:24.404 --> 00:29:28.373
Z. D1, D2, D3, and so on. And what

00:29:28.384 --> 00:29:32.323
I'm going to make sure is
that the Nth digit after the

00:29:32.343 --> 00:29:40.024
decimal point of Z is different from the
Nth digit of the Nth number on the list.

00:29:40.103 --> 00:29:43.924
Okay? So, to specify the Nth digit of Z, I

00:29:44.004 --> 00:29:47.843
go to the Nth number on the list,
R sub N, and I look at its Nth

00:29:47.944 --> 00:29:51.603
digit after the decimal point.
And whatever that digit

00:29:51.643 --> 00:29:56.404
is, I make sure that my digit
is different from it. Okay?

00:29:57.484 --> 00:30:01.424
And then I want to do something
a little bit more, and that is

00:30:01.464 --> 00:30:05.444
I'm going to make it different in
a way that I'm never using the

00:30:05.484 --> 00:30:10.164
digits zero or nine. I'm just always
using the other digits and not zero

00:30:10.174 --> 00:30:40.984
and it would form a kind of diagonal
going down and to the right, and that,

00:30:41.043 --> 00:30:44.904
for that reason, this argument is called the
diagonal argument because we're looking at the

00:30:44.984 --> 00:30:48.803
Nth digit of the Nth number, and those
exist on a kind of diagonal going

00:30:48.843 --> 00:30:51.724
down. And we've made our number Z

00:30:52.664 --> 00:30:57.063
so that the Nth digit of Z is different
from the Nth digit of the Nth number.

00:30:58.404 --> 00:31:03.583
But now it follows that Z
is not on the list because

00:31:04.464 --> 00:31:08.444
Z is different from R1 because, well,

00:31:08.524 --> 00:31:12.144
the first digit after the decimal
point of Z is different from the first

00:31:12.224 --> 00:31:15.424
digit of R1 after the decimal
point. That's exactly how we built

00:31:15.464 --> 00:31:19.283
it. And the second digit of Z is
different from the second digit

00:31:19.383 --> 00:31:23.123
of R2 and so on. The Nth
digit of Z is different

00:31:23.204 --> 00:31:26.883
from the Nth digit of R
sub N for every N. So

00:31:26.924 --> 00:31:30.964
therefore, Z is not equal to any
of these numbers R sub N. And

00:31:32.323 --> 00:31:36.303
but that's a contradiction because we had
assumed that we had every real number

00:31:36.363 --> 00:31:39.684
on the list, but yet here is a
real number Z that's not on the

00:31:39.744 --> 00:31:43.264
list, okay? And so that's
the main contradiction.

00:31:43.283 --> 00:31:45.313
- And so it's a kind of
proof by construction.

00:31:45.363 --> 00:31:48.164
- Exactly. So given a list
of numbers, Cantor's

00:31:48.264 --> 00:31:52.164
proving... It's interesting that you say that
actually, because there's a kind of philosophical

00:31:52.224 --> 00:31:56.143
controversy that occurs in connection with

00:31:56.184 --> 00:32:00.083
this observation about whether Cantor's
construction is constructive or not.

00:32:00.184 --> 00:32:03.803
Given a list of numbers,
Cantor gives us a specific

00:32:03.823 --> 00:32:07.744
means of constructing a real number
that's not on the list, is a

00:32:07.764 --> 00:32:14.103
way of thinking about it. There's this one
aspect, which I alluded to earlier, but

00:32:14.204 --> 00:32:16.964
some real numbers have
more than one decimal

00:32:16.984 --> 00:32:20.964
representation, and it
causes this slight problem

00:32:21.004 --> 00:32:27.904
in the argument. For example, the
number one, you can write it as 1.0000

00:32:27.964 --> 00:32:34.524
forever, but you can also write it
as 0.999 forever. Those are two

00:32:34.664 --> 00:32:38.164
different decimal representations
of exactly the same number.

00:32:38.224 --> 00:32:41.944
- You beautifully got rid of the zeros and the nines.
Therefore, we don't need to even consider that,

00:32:42.043 --> 00:32:44.323
and the proof still works.

00:32:44.363 --> 00:32:48.204
- Exactly, because the only kind of
case where that phenomenon occurs is

00:32:48.244 --> 00:32:52.204
when the number is eventually zero
or eventually nine. And so since our

00:32:52.244 --> 00:32:55.893
number Z never had any zeros or
nines in it, it wasn't one of those

00:32:55.964 --> 00:32:59.863
numbers. And so actually, in those cases,
we didn't need to do anything special to

00:32:59.904 --> 00:33:03.603
diagonalize. Just the mere fact that
our number has a unique representation

00:33:03.684 --> 00:33:07.623
already means that it's not equal
to those numbers. So maybe it

00:33:07.684 --> 00:33:11.244
was controversial in Cantor's day more
than 100 years ago, but I think it's

00:33:11.384 --> 00:33:15.244
most commonly looked at today
as, you know, one of the

00:33:15.404 --> 00:33:18.524
initial main results in
set theory, and it's

00:33:19.083 --> 00:33:22.744
profound and amazing and
insightful and the beginning

00:33:22.843 --> 00:33:26.764
point of so many later arguments.
And this diagonalization

00:33:26.843 --> 00:33:30.744
idea has proved to be an
extremely fruitful proof method,

00:33:31.384 --> 00:33:35.323
and almost every major
result in mathematical logic

00:33:35.384 --> 00:33:38.984
is using in an abstract way the idea of

00:33:39.043 --> 00:33:42.783
diagonalization. It was
really the start of so

00:33:42.823 --> 00:33:45.884
many other observations
that were made, including

00:33:46.484 --> 00:33:50.184
Russell's paradox and the halting
problem and the recursion

00:33:50.204 --> 00:33:56.583
theorem, and so many other principles are
using diagonalization at their core. So...

00:33:56.664 --> 00:33:58.694
- Can we just step back a little bit?

00:33:58.704 --> 00:33:58.764
- Sure.

00:33:58.783 --> 00:34:06.283
- This infinity crisis led to a kind of
rebuilding of mathematics. So it'd be

00:34:06.303 --> 00:34:10.234
nice if you lay out the things
it resulted in. So one is

00:34:10.234 --> 00:34:14.103
set theory became the foundation of
mathematics. All mathematics could now

00:34:14.123 --> 00:34:16.933
be built from sets, giving
math its first truly rigorous

00:34:16.984 --> 00:34:20.723
foundation. The axiomatization

00:34:21.304 --> 00:34:25.143
of mathematics, the paradoxes forced
mathematicians to develop ZFC and other

00:34:25.163 --> 00:34:31.092
axiomatic systems, and mathematical
logic emerged. Gödel, Turing, and

00:34:31.163 --> 00:34:37.944
others created entire new fields. So
can you explain what set theory is and,

00:34:38.024 --> 00:34:41.884
how does it serve as a foundation of
modern mathematics and maybe even the

00:34:41.904 --> 00:34:43.043
foundation of truth?

00:34:43.103 --> 00:34:46.864
- That's a great question.
Set theory really has two

00:34:47.364 --> 00:34:51.223
roles that it's serving. There's kind

00:34:51.264 --> 00:34:55.783
of two ways that set theory emerges.
On the one hand, set theory

00:34:56.864 --> 00:35:00.324
is its own subject of
mathematics, with its

00:35:00.424 --> 00:35:04.024
own problems and questions
and answers and proof

00:35:04.243 --> 00:35:07.764
methods. And so really, from this
point of view, set theory is

00:35:07.844 --> 00:35:14.264
about the transfinite recursive constructions
or well-founded definitions and

00:35:14.564 --> 00:35:18.484
constructions. And those
ideas have been enormously

00:35:18.544 --> 00:35:22.134
fruitful and set theorists
have looked into them and

00:35:22.364 --> 00:35:26.223
developed so many ideas
coming out of that. But set

00:35:26.243 --> 00:35:29.424
theory has also happened
to serve in this other

00:35:29.464 --> 00:35:33.334
foundational role. It's very
common to hear things said about

00:35:33.364 --> 00:35:37.254
set theory that really aren't taking
account of this distinction between

00:35:37.264 --> 00:35:41.104
the two roles that it's serving. It's its
own subject, but it's also serving as a

00:35:41.144 --> 00:35:44.964
foundation of mathematics. So
in its foundational role, set

00:35:45.044 --> 00:35:49.014
theory provides a way to think of a
collection of things as one thing.

00:35:49.064 --> 00:35:52.524
That's the central idea
of set theory. A set is a

00:35:52.584 --> 00:35:56.183
collection of things,
but you think of the set

00:35:56.243 --> 00:36:00.154
itself as one abstract
thing. So when you form the

00:36:00.243 --> 00:36:03.584
set of real numbers, then that
is a set. It's one thing. It's a

00:36:03.723 --> 00:36:07.624
set, and it has elements
inside of it. So it's sort of

00:36:07.644 --> 00:36:11.624
like a bag of objects. A set is kind of
like a bag of objects. And so we have a

00:36:11.663 --> 00:36:15.584
lot of different axioms that
describe the nature of this

00:36:15.683 --> 00:36:20.384
idea of thinking of a collection of things
as one thing itself, one abstract thing.

00:36:20.424 --> 00:36:27.723
- And axioms are, I guess, facts that we
assume are true, based on which we then

00:36:27.764 --> 00:36:33.344
build the ideas of mathematics. So there's
a bunch of facts, axioms about sets

00:36:34.243 --> 00:36:37.756
that we can put together, and
if they're sufficiently......

00:36:37.796 --> 00:36:42.376
powerful, we can then build on top of that
a lot of really interesting mathematics.

00:36:42.436 --> 00:36:46.296
- Yeah, I think that's right. So, I
mean, the history of the current set

00:36:46.336 --> 00:36:50.156
theory axioms, known as the
Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms, came out in the

00:36:50.196 --> 00:36:54.036
early 20th century with Zermelo's
idea. I mean, the history is quite

00:36:54.076 --> 00:37:00.036
fascinating because Zermelo
in 1904 offered a proof

00:37:00.876 --> 00:37:04.836
that what's called the
axiom of choice implies the

00:37:04.876 --> 00:37:08.856
well-order principle. So he
described his proof, and that was

00:37:08.876 --> 00:37:12.616
extremely controversial at
the time. And there was no

00:37:12.636 --> 00:37:16.316
theory, there weren't any axioms there.
Cantor was not working in an axiomatic

00:37:16.396 --> 00:37:20.176
framework. He didn't have a list of axioms
in the way that we have for set theory

00:37:20.216 --> 00:37:24.186
now, and Zermelo didn't either. And his

00:37:24.276 --> 00:37:29.786
ideas were challenged so much with
regard to the well-order theorem—

00:37:29.786 --> 00:37:33.345
—that he was pressed to produce the theory

00:37:33.416 --> 00:37:37.246
in which his argument could be
formalized, and that was the origin of

00:37:37.276 --> 00:37:39.236
what's known as Zermelo set theory.

00:37:39.376 --> 00:37:43.266
- And going to perplexity, the axiom of
choice is a fundamental principle in set

00:37:43.276 --> 00:37:46.866
theory which states that for any
collection of non-empty sets, it is

00:37:46.896 --> 00:37:50.876
possible to select exactly one
element from each set, even

00:37:50.916 --> 00:37:54.836
if no explicit rule to make
the choices given. This axiom

00:37:54.896 --> 00:37:58.456
allows the construction of a new set
containing one element from each

00:37:58.516 --> 00:38:01.636
original set, even in cases
where the collection is infinite

00:38:02.056 --> 00:38:05.916
or where there is no natural
way to specify a selection

00:38:05.976 --> 00:38:09.916
rule. So this was controversial and this

00:38:09.936 --> 00:38:14.316
was described before there's even
a language for axiomatic systems.

00:38:14.376 --> 00:38:18.656
- That's right. So on the one hand, I
mean, the axiom of choice principle is

00:38:20.196 --> 00:38:24.116
completely obvious that we want
this to be true, that it is

00:38:24.156 --> 00:38:27.506
true. I mean, a lot of people take
it as a law of logic. If you have

00:38:28.256 --> 00:38:31.456
a bunch of sets, then there's a way of
picking an element from each of them.

00:38:31.496 --> 00:38:35.146
picking an element from
each of them. There's a

00:38:35.176 --> 00:38:39.086
function. If I have a bunch of
sets, then there's a function that,

00:38:39.086 --> 00:38:43.056
when you apply it to any one of those
sets, gives you an element of that set.

00:38:43.116 --> 00:38:47.025
It's- it's a completely
natural principle. I mean,

00:38:47.055 --> 00:38:50.796
it's called the axiom of choice, which is
a way of sort of anthropomorphizing the

00:38:50.836 --> 00:38:54.405
mathematical idea. It's not
like the function is choosing

00:38:54.436 --> 00:38:58.296
something. I mean, it's just that
if you were to make such choices,

00:38:58.316 --> 00:39:02.136
there would be a function that
consisted of the choices that you made.

00:39:02.176 --> 00:39:05.676
And the difficulty is that when
you- when you can't specify a

00:39:05.836 --> 00:39:09.146
rule or a procedure by which you're making
choices, then it's difficult to say

00:39:09.236 --> 00:39:12.996
choices, then it's difficult to say what the
function is that you're asserting exists.

00:39:13.076 --> 00:39:17.016
function is that you're asserting
exists. You know, you- you

00:39:17.076 --> 00:39:21.016
want to have the view that, well, there
is a way of choosing. I don't have an

00:39:21.156 --> 00:39:25.136
easy way to say what the function
is, but there definitely is one.

00:39:25.216 --> 00:39:28.056
Yeah, this is the way of thinking
about the axiom of choice.

00:39:28.256 --> 00:39:31.876
- So we're going to say the- the- the three
letters of ZFC may be a lot on this

00:39:31.896 --> 00:39:33.756
conversation. You already mentioned-

00:39:33.836 --> 00:39:33.845
- Right

00:39:33.845 --> 00:39:37.676
- ...Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory, that's the
Z and the F and the C in that is this...

00:39:37.736 --> 00:39:41.936
and the C in that is this...
Comes from this axiom of choice.

00:39:41.976 --> 00:39:42.436
- That's right.

00:39:42.496 --> 00:39:46.456
- So ZFC sounds like a super
technical thing, but it is the

00:39:46.496 --> 00:39:49.736
set of axioms that's the
foundation of modern mathematics.

00:39:49.776 --> 00:39:53.396
- Yeah, absolutely. So one should be
aware also that there's huge parts of

00:39:53.456 --> 00:39:57.366
mathematics that don't... That pay
attention to whether the axiom of

00:39:57.366 --> 00:40:00.556
choice is being used and they don't want to
use the axiom of choice, so they work out

00:40:01.256 --> 00:40:05.056
the consequences that's- that are possible
without the axiom of choice or with weakened

00:40:05.156 --> 00:40:09.056
forms of- of Zermelo-Fraenkel set
theory and so on. And that's quite

00:40:09.276 --> 00:40:13.196
a- there's quite a vibrant amount of work
in that area. I mean, but going back to the

00:40:13.236 --> 00:40:21.016
axiom of choice for a bit, it's maybe
interesting to- to give Russell's description

00:40:21.076 --> 00:40:24.806
of how to think about the axiom
of choice. So Russell describes,

00:40:24.916 --> 00:40:32.896
this rich person who has a- an infinite
closet. And in that closet, he has

00:40:32.996 --> 00:40:40.046
infinitely many pairs of shoes
and he tells his butler to

00:40:40.276 --> 00:40:43.936
"Please go and give me
one shoe from each pair."

00:40:43.976 --> 00:40:47.836
And- and the butler can do this easily
because he can... For any pair of shoes, he

00:40:47.876 --> 00:40:51.776
can just always pick the left
shoe. I mean, there's a way

00:40:51.836 --> 00:40:55.756
of picking that we can describe.
We always take the left one or

00:40:55.816 --> 00:40:59.636
always take the right one, or take the left
one if it's a red shoe and the right one if

00:40:59.696 --> 00:41:03.616
it's a brown shoe or, you know.
We can invent rules that would

00:41:03.656 --> 00:41:07.235
result in these kind of choice
functions, so we can describe

00:41:07.296 --> 00:41:11.176
explicit choice functions. And for those
cases, you don't need the axiom of choice

00:41:11.236 --> 00:41:15.036
you don't need the Axiom of Choice to
know that there's a choice function.

00:41:15.096 --> 00:41:18.936
When you can describe a specific way
of choosing, then you don't need to

00:41:18.946 --> 00:41:21.416
appeal to the axiom to
know that there's a choice

00:41:21.496 --> 00:41:24.536
But the problematic case occurs when
you think about the infinite collection

00:41:25.956 --> 00:41:29.676
when you think about the infinite
collection of socks that the

00:41:29.716 --> 00:41:33.566
person has in their closet. And
if we assume that socks are

00:41:33.636 --> 00:41:37.526
sort of indistinguishable within each
pair, you know, they match each other,

00:41:37.576 --> 00:41:43.916
indiscernible, then the- the butler
wouldn't have any kind of rule for

00:41:43.976 --> 00:41:51.296
which sock in each pair to pick. And so
it's not so clear that he has a way of-

00:41:52.236 --> 00:41:55.416
of producing one sock from each pair

00:41:55.496 --> 00:41:59.356
because... Right? So that's what's
at stake, is the question of whether

00:41:59.416 --> 00:42:06.366
you can specify a rule by which the choice
function, you know, a rule that it obeys

00:42:06.796 --> 00:42:10.496
that defines the choice function, or
whether there's sort of this arbitrary

00:42:10.576 --> 00:42:14.556
choosing aspect to it. That's when
you need the axiom of choice to

00:42:14.576 --> 00:42:18.276
know that there is such a function.
But of course, as a matter of

00:42:18.316 --> 00:42:22.096
mathematical ontology, we might find
attractive the idea that, well,

00:42:22.156 --> 00:42:25.716
look, I mean, I don't- not every way of

00:42:25.776 --> 00:42:29.736
choosing the socks has to be defined
by rule. Why should everything that

00:42:29.776 --> 00:42:33.216
exists in mathematical
reality follow a rule or a

00:42:33.256 --> 00:42:36.936
procedure of that sort? If I have the

00:42:36.996 --> 00:42:40.736
idea that my mathematical
ontology is rich with objects,

00:42:40.776 --> 00:42:44.336
then I think that, that there
are all kinds of functions and

00:42:44.416 --> 00:42:48.176
ways of choosing. Those are all part
of the mathematical reality that I

00:42:48.216 --> 00:42:51.514
wanna be talking about.... and
so I don't have any problem

00:42:52.044 --> 00:42:55.663
asserting the Axiom of Choice.
Yes, there is a way of choosing,

00:42:55.764 --> 00:42:59.514
But I can't t- necessarily
tell you what it is.

00:42:59.524 --> 00:43:03.364
But in a mathematical argument, I
can assume that I fix the choice

00:43:03.424 --> 00:43:06.454
function because I know that
there is one. So it's a... The

00:43:06.464 --> 00:43:10.344
philosophical difference between working
when you have the Axiom of Choice

00:43:10.764 --> 00:43:14.364
and when you don't is the question
of this constructive nature of the

00:43:14.464 --> 00:43:18.324
argument. So if you make an argument
and you appeal to the Axiom of Choice,

00:43:18.384 --> 00:43:21.874
then maybe you're admitting
that the objects that

00:43:21.944 --> 00:43:25.924
you're producing in the proof
are not gonna be constructive.

00:43:25.944 --> 00:43:29.814
You're not gonna be able to necessarily
say specific things about them.

00:43:30.244 --> 00:43:34.234
But if you're just claiming to make an existence
claim, that's totally fine. Whereas if you have

00:43:34.284 --> 00:43:38.204
a constructive attitude about ma-
the nature of mathematics, and you

00:43:38.244 --> 00:43:42.124
think that mathematical claims maybe
are only warranted when you can

00:43:42.163 --> 00:43:45.884
provide an explicit procedure for producing
the mathematical objects that you're dealing

00:43:45.924 --> 00:43:51.604
with then you're probably gonna wanna deny
the axiom of choice and maybe much more.

00:43:51.644 --> 00:43:55.084
- Can we maybe speak to the axioms that

00:43:55.604 --> 00:43:59.464
underlie ZFC? So cone of perplexity,
ZFC, or Zermelo-Fraenkel

00:43:59.504 --> 00:44:03.444
set theory with the Axiom of Choice, as we
mentioned, is the standard foundation for most

00:44:03.524 --> 00:44:07.324
modern mathematics. It consists of
the following main axioms: Axiom

00:44:07.484 --> 00:44:11.344
of Extensionality, Axiom of Empty
Set, Axiom of Pairing, Axiom

00:44:11.384 --> 00:44:15.024
of Union, Axiom of Power Set,
Axiom of Infinity, Axiom of

00:44:15.064 --> 00:44:19.034
Separation, Axiom of Replacement,
Axiom of Regularity,

00:44:19.084 --> 00:44:24.924
and Axiom of Choice. Some of these
are quite basic, but it would be nice

00:44:25.724 --> 00:44:28.244
to kinda give people a sense-

00:44:28.254 --> 00:44:32.104
...of what it means to be an
axiom. Like, what kind of basic

00:44:33.084 --> 00:44:37.564
facts we can lay on the table on which
we can build some beautiful mathematics.

00:44:37.604 --> 00:44:41.504
- Yeah, so the history of it is really
quite fascinating. So, Zermelo introduced

00:44:41.624 --> 00:44:45.564
most of these axioms, I mean, as part
of what's now called Zermelo set

00:44:45.604 --> 00:44:49.454
theory, to formalize his
proof from the Axiom of

00:44:49.484 --> 00:44:53.464
Choice to the Well-Order Principle, which
was an extremely controversial result.

00:44:53.504 --> 00:44:57.204
So in 1904, he gave the proof without the
theory, and then he was challenged to

00:44:57.224 --> 00:45:00.984
provide the theory. And
so in 1908, he produced

00:45:01.184 --> 00:45:05.144
the Zermelo set theory
and gave the proof that

00:45:05.224 --> 00:45:09.163
in that theory, you can prove that
every set admits a well ordering.

00:45:09.264 --> 00:45:13.004
And so the axioms on the list, these
things like extensionality, express

00:45:13.014 --> 00:45:16.604
the most fundamental principles of the

00:45:16.663 --> 00:45:20.344
understanding of sets that he wanted
to be talking about. So for example,

00:45:20.354 --> 00:45:26.124
extensionality says if two sets have the
same members, then they're equal. So

00:45:26.163 --> 00:45:30.124
it's this idea that the
sets consist of the

00:45:30.163 --> 00:45:34.084
collection of their members, and that's it.
There's nothing else that's going on in

00:45:34.124 --> 00:45:37.884
the set. So it's just if two sets have
the same members, then they are the same

00:45:37.944 --> 00:45:44.944
set. So it's maybe the most
primitive axiom in some respect.

00:45:44.984 --> 00:45:48.744
- Well, there's also, just to give
a flavor, there exists a set

00:45:48.904 --> 00:45:52.764
with no elements, called the empty
set. For any two sets, there's a

00:45:52.824 --> 00:45:55.724
set that contains exactly
those two sets as

00:45:55.904 --> 00:45:59.663
elements. For any set, there's a set that
contains exactly the elements of the

00:45:59.824 --> 00:46:03.663
elements of that set, so the union
set. And then there's the power

00:46:03.724 --> 00:46:07.324
set. For any set, there's a set
whose elements are exactly the

00:46:07.364 --> 00:46:10.804
subsets of the original set,
the power set. In the axiom of

00:46:10.844 --> 00:46:14.774
infinity, there exists an
infinite set, typically a set

00:46:14.804 --> 00:46:18.744
that contains the empty set and is closed
under the operation of adding one more

00:46:18.804 --> 00:46:22.384
element. Back to our hotel example.

00:46:22.424 --> 00:46:23.294
- That's right.

00:46:23.324 --> 00:46:26.384
- And there's more, but this
is kind of fascinating.

00:46:26.484 --> 00:46:30.374
Just put yourself in the
mindset of people at

00:46:30.404 --> 00:46:34.364
the beginning of this, of
trying to formalize set theory.

00:46:34.504 --> 00:46:36.994
It's fascinating that humans can do that.

00:46:37.084 --> 00:46:40.714
- I read some historical
accounts by historians about

00:46:40.764 --> 00:46:44.584
that time period, specifically
about Zermelo's axioms and his

00:46:44.624 --> 00:46:51.984
proof of the well-order theorem. And the
historians were saying never before in the

00:46:52.004 --> 00:46:55.944
history of mathematics has a
mathematical theorem been argued

00:46:56.004 --> 00:47:01.913
about so publicly and so
vociferously as that theorem of

00:47:01.924 --> 00:47:08.474
Zermelo's. And it's fascinating also
because the axiom of choice was

00:47:08.503 --> 00:47:12.384
widely regarded as a kind of, you
know, basic principle at first,

00:47:12.424 --> 00:47:15.833
but then when, but people were very suspicious
of the well-order theorem because no one could

00:47:15.924 --> 00:47:19.684
imagine a well ordering, say,
of the real numbers. And so

00:47:19.884 --> 00:47:23.694
this was a case when Zermelo
seemed to be, from principles

00:47:23.724 --> 00:47:27.584
that seemed quite reasonable,
proving this obvious untruth.

00:47:28.224 --> 00:47:32.064
And so people were, mathematicians
were objecting. But then

00:47:32.184 --> 00:47:35.784
Zermelo and others
actually looked into the

00:47:35.844 --> 00:47:39.264
mathematical papers and so on of
some of the people who had been

00:47:39.304 --> 00:47:43.184
objecting so vociferously,
and found, in many

00:47:43.244 --> 00:47:46.854
cases, that they were implicitly
using the axiom of choice in their

00:47:46.964 --> 00:47:50.163
own arguments, even though they
would argue publicly against

00:47:50.203 --> 00:47:54.024
it. Because it's so
natural to use it because

00:47:54.104 --> 00:47:57.824
it's such an obvious principle
in a way. I mean, it's

00:47:57.884 --> 00:48:01.284
easy to just use it by accident
if you're not critical enough

00:48:01.844 --> 00:48:05.444
and you don't even realize that you're using
the axiom of choice. That's true now, even.

00:48:05.464 --> 00:48:09.064
People like to pay attention to when the
axiom of choice is used or not used in

00:48:09.084 --> 00:48:12.754
mathematical arguments, up until
this day. It used to be more

00:48:12.784 --> 00:48:16.744
important. In the early 20th century it was
very important because people didn't know if it

00:48:16.784 --> 00:48:20.724
was a consistent theory or not, and
there were these antinomies arising.

00:48:20.764 --> 00:48:24.214
and so there was a worry about
consistency of the axioms.

00:48:24.564 --> 00:48:28.494
but then, of course, eventually,
with the result of, of

00:48:28.584 --> 00:48:32.494
Godel and Cohen and so on, they... this
consistency question specifically about the

00:48:32.544 --> 00:48:36.344
axiom of choice sort of falls away. We
know that the axiom of choice itself

00:48:36.384 --> 00:48:40.324
choice itself will never be the
source of inconsistency in set

00:48:40.364 --> 00:48:44.264
theory. If there's inconsistency with the
axiom of choice, then it's, it's already

00:48:44.284 --> 00:48:47.644
inconsistent without the axiom of
choice. So it's not the cause of

00:48:47.703 --> 00:48:51.344
inconsistency. And so in that... from
that point of view, the need to pay

00:48:51.384 --> 00:48:55.264
attention to whether you're using it or not from
a consistency point of view is somehow less

00:48:55.284 --> 00:48:58.424
important. But still there's this

00:48:59.024 --> 00:49:02.884
reason to pay attention to it on
the grounds of these constructivist

00:49:02.984 --> 00:49:05.614
ideas that I had mentioned earlier.

00:49:05.614 --> 00:49:09.584
- And we should say, in set theory,
consistency means that it is impossible to

00:49:09.604 --> 00:49:12.354
derive a contradiction from
the axioms of the theory.

00:49:12.404 --> 00:49:15.814
It means that there are no
contradictions. That's a...

00:49:15.814 --> 00:49:15.964
- That's right

00:49:15.984 --> 00:49:19.364
- A consistent axiomatic system is
that there are no contradictions.

00:49:19.404 --> 00:49:22.894
- A consistent theory is one for which you
cannot prove a contradiction from that

00:49:22.904 --> 00:49:23.844
theory.

00:49:23.864 --> 00:49:26.264
- Maybe a quick pause, a quick
break, a quick bathroom break.

00:49:28.344 --> 00:49:32.084
You mentioned to me offline we were
talking about Russell's paradox and that

00:49:32.154 --> 00:49:37.764
there's a- a nice, another kind
of anthropomorphizable proof of

00:49:37.824 --> 00:49:40.944
uncountability. I was wondering
if you can lay that out.

00:49:41.024 --> 00:49:42.324
- Oh yeah, sure. Absolutely.

00:49:42.344 --> 00:49:44.144
- Both Russell's paradox and the proof.

00:49:44.204 --> 00:49:49.284
- Right. So we talked about Cantor's proof

00:49:49.324 --> 00:49:53.184
that the real numbers, the set of real
numbers is an uncountable infinity,

00:49:53.224 --> 00:49:57.084
it's a strictly larger infinity than
the natural numbers. But Cantor

00:49:57.184 --> 00:50:00.924
actually proved a- a
much more general fact,

00:50:00.984 --> 00:50:04.904
namely that for any set
whatsoever, the power

00:50:05.044 --> 00:50:09.024
set of that set is a strictly
larger set. So the power set

00:50:09.404 --> 00:50:13.904
is the set containing all the subsets of
the original set. So if you have a set

00:50:14.924 --> 00:50:18.824
and you look at the collection of all
of its subsets, then Cantor proved

00:50:18.864 --> 00:50:22.024
that this is- this is a
bigger set. They're not

00:50:22.084 --> 00:50:25.884
equinumerous. Of course, there's always
at least as many subsets as elements

00:50:25.984 --> 00:50:29.944
because for any element you can
make, the- the singleton subset

00:50:29.984 --> 00:50:33.804
that has only that guy
as a member, right? So

00:50:33.844 --> 00:50:37.664
there's always at least as many subsets
as elements. But the question is

00:50:37.784 --> 00:50:41.544
whether they, whether it's
strictly more or not. And so

00:50:41.664 --> 00:50:45.404
Cantor reasoned like this. It's
very simple. It's a kind of

00:50:45.464 --> 00:50:48.884
distilling the abstract
diagonalization idea

00:50:48.984 --> 00:50:55.084
without being encumbered by the complexity
of the real numbers. So, we have a set X,

00:50:56.164 --> 00:51:00.064
and we're looking at all of its
subsets. That's the power set of X.

00:51:00.144 --> 00:51:03.644
Suppose that X and the power
set of X have the same

00:51:03.684 --> 00:51:07.674
size. Suppose, towards contradiction,
they have the same size.

00:51:07.724 --> 00:51:13.944
So that means we can associate to
every individual of X a subset.

00:51:14.764 --> 00:51:18.404
And so now let me define a new
set. Another set, I'm going to

00:51:18.424 --> 00:51:22.344
define it. Let's call it
D. And D is the subset

00:51:22.404 --> 00:51:29.344
of X that contains all the individuals that
are not in their set. Every individual

00:51:30.504 --> 00:51:34.444
was associated with a subset of X, and
I'm looking at the individuals that

00:51:34.484 --> 00:51:36.224
are not in their set.

00:51:37.284 --> 00:51:41.164
Maybe nobody's like that. Maybe there's
no element of X that's like that,

00:51:41.204 --> 00:51:43.934
or maybe they're all like that, or maybe
some of them are and some of them aren't.

00:51:43.944 --> 00:51:47.404
It doesn't really matter for the
argument. I defined a subset

00:51:47.544 --> 00:51:51.384
D consisting of the individuals
that are not in the set that's

00:51:51.424 --> 00:51:55.144
attached to them, but that's a
perfectly good subset. And so

00:51:55.184 --> 00:51:58.904
because of the equinumerosity, it would have
to be attached to a particular individual,

00:51:58.944 --> 00:52:06.324
you know? And- ...but that...
let's call that person, it should

00:52:06.404 --> 00:52:10.704
be a name starting with D, so Diana.

00:52:10.724 --> 00:52:14.604
And now we ask, is Diana
an element of D or not?

00:52:15.164 --> 00:52:18.883
But if Diana is an element
of D, then she is in her

00:52:18.984 --> 00:52:22.664
set. So she shouldn't be because the

00:52:23.064 --> 00:52:27.984
set D was the set of individuals
that are not in their set.

00:52:28.044 --> 00:52:31.804
So if Diana is in D, then she
shouldn't be. But if she isn't in

00:52:31.904 --> 00:52:35.784
D, then she wouldn't be in her
set. And so she should be in D.

00:52:35.804 --> 00:52:39.784
That's a contradiction.
So therefore, the number

00:52:39.884 --> 00:52:44.244
of subsets is always greater than
the number of elements for any set.

00:52:45.764 --> 00:52:48.124
And the anthropomorphizing
idea is the following.

00:52:49.084 --> 00:52:53.044
I'd like to talk about it
this way. For any collection

00:52:53.084 --> 00:52:57.004
of people, you can form
more committees from them

00:52:57.764 --> 00:53:03.104
than there are people, even if
you have infinetely many people.

00:53:03.184 --> 00:53:06.844
Suppose you have an infinite
set of people. And what's a

00:53:06.884 --> 00:53:10.744
committee? Well, a committee is just a
list of who's on the committee, basically.

00:53:10.784 --> 00:53:14.664
The members of the committee. So
there's all the two-person committees

00:53:14.704 --> 00:53:17.964
and there's all the one-person
committees, and there's the universal,

00:53:17.984 --> 00:53:21.964
the worst committee, the one that
everyone is on. Okay. The best committee

00:53:22.024 --> 00:53:27.144
is the empty committee. With no members
and never meets and so on. Or is the empty

00:53:27.204 --> 00:53:29.744
committee meeting all
the time? I'm not sure.

00:53:29.824 --> 00:53:31.984
- Yeah. That's... wow, that's
a profound question.

00:53:32.024 --> 00:53:35.233
And does a committee with just
one member meet also as a-

00:53:35.343 --> 00:53:38.004
- Yeah, maybe it's always
in session. I don't know.

00:53:38.404 --> 00:53:44.764
So the claim is that there are
more committees than people.

00:53:44.844 --> 00:53:48.804
Okay. Suppose not. Well, then we
could make an association between the

00:53:48.844 --> 00:53:52.324
people and the committees. So
we would have every committee

00:53:52.744 --> 00:53:56.704
could be named after a
person in a one-to-one way.

00:53:56.724 --> 00:54:00.634
And I'm not saying that the person is on
the committee that's named after them,

00:54:00.664 --> 00:54:04.524
or not on it, whatever. Maybe sometimes that
happens, sometimes it doesn't. I don't know.

00:54:04.544 --> 00:54:10.124
It doesn't matter. But let's form what I
call committee D, which consists of all the

00:54:10.164 --> 00:54:16.584
people that are not on the
committee that's named after them.

00:54:16.744 --> 00:54:20.334
Okay. Maybe that's everyone, maybe it's no
one, maybe it's half the people. It doesn't

00:54:20.424 --> 00:54:26.764
matter. That's a committee. It's a set of
people. And so it has to be named after

00:54:26.824 --> 00:54:33.264
someone. Let's call that person
Daniella. So now we ask, is

00:54:33.304 --> 00:54:37.144
Daniella on the committee
that's named after her?

00:54:37.424 --> 00:54:41.344
Well, if she is, then she
shouldn't be because it was the

00:54:41.404 --> 00:54:45.364
committee of people who aren't
on their own committee.

00:54:45.444 --> 00:54:48.364
And if she isn't, then she
should be. So again, it's a

00:54:48.404 --> 00:54:55.404
contradiction. So when I was teaching at
Oxford, one of my students came up with the

00:54:55.444 --> 00:54:59.404
following different
anthropomorphization of Cantor's

00:54:59.484 --> 00:55:03.324
argument. Let's consider
all possible fruit

00:55:03.384 --> 00:55:07.144
salads. We have a given
collection of fruits.

00:55:07.164 --> 00:55:11.064
You know, apples and oranges and grapes,
whatever. And a fruit salad consists of

00:55:11.564 --> 00:55:15.544
some collection of those fruits. So
there's the banana, pear, grape salad and

00:55:15.604 --> 00:55:19.144
so on. There are a lot of different
kinds of salad. Every set of fruits

00:55:19.384 --> 00:55:23.356
makes a salad, a fruit
salad. Okay. And we want to

00:55:23.376 --> 00:55:27.236
prove that for any collection of
fruits, even if there are infinitely

00:55:27.296 --> 00:55:31.215
many different kinds of
fruit, for any collection

00:55:31.256 --> 00:55:36.736
of fruits, there are more possible
fruit salads than there are fruits.

00:55:38.276 --> 00:55:41.736
So if not, then you can put a
one-to-one correspondence between the

00:55:41.816 --> 00:55:45.556
fruits and the fruit salads,
so you could name every fruit

00:55:45.656 --> 00:55:49.536
salad after a fruit. That
fruit might not be in

00:55:49.576 --> 00:55:52.596
that salad, it doesn't matter. We're just...
it's a naming, a one-to-one correspondence.

00:55:53.496 --> 00:55:58.766
And then, of course, we form the
diagonal salad, which consists

00:55:58.766 --> 00:56:02.876
of all the fruits that are not in
the salad that's named after them.

00:56:04.096 --> 00:56:08.076
And that's a perfectly
good salad. It might be

00:56:08.136 --> 00:56:11.856
the kind of diet salad, if it was the
empty salad, or it might be the universal

00:56:11.916 --> 00:56:12.216
salad

00:56:12.226 --> 00:56:16.136
which had all fruits in it, if all the fruits
were in it. Or it might have just some and

00:56:16.176 --> 00:56:20.036
not all. So that diagonal salad
would have to be named after

00:56:20.116 --> 00:56:23.916
some fruit. So let's suppose
it's named after durian,

00:56:23.976 --> 00:56:27.936
meaning that it was associated with durian
in the one-to-one correspondence. And then

00:56:27.976 --> 00:56:35.076
we ask, well, is durian in the salad that
it's named after? And if it is, then it

00:56:35.116 --> 00:56:39.096
shouldn't be. And if it isn't, then it
should be. And so it's again the same

00:56:39.136 --> 00:56:42.296
contradiction. So all of those
arguments are just the same as

00:56:42.356 --> 00:56:45.806
Cantor's proof that the
power set of any set is

00:56:45.996 --> 00:56:49.826
bigger than the set. And this
is exactly the same logic

00:56:49.876 --> 00:56:53.676
that comes up in Russell's paradox,
because Russell is arguing

00:56:53.756 --> 00:56:58.556
that the class of all sets can't be a set,

00:56:59.876 --> 00:57:03.556
because if it were, then we could form the

00:57:03.836 --> 00:57:08.436
the set of all sets that are
not elements of themselves.

00:57:09.276 --> 00:57:12.836
So basically, what Russell is
proving is that there are more

00:57:12.876 --> 00:57:18.876
collections of sets than
elements. Because we can form the

00:57:18.896 --> 00:57:22.436
diagonal class, you know, the
class of all sets that are not

00:57:22.536 --> 00:57:26.476
elements of themselves. If that
were a set, then it would be an

00:57:26.556 --> 00:57:30.456
element of itself if and only if it
was not an element of itself. It's

00:57:30.496 --> 00:57:34.466
exactly the same logic in all
four of those arguments. Yeah.

00:57:34.496 --> 00:57:38.236
So there can't be a class of all sets, because if
there were, then there would have to be a class of all

00:57:38.256 --> 00:57:42.156
sets that aren't elements
of themselves. But that set

00:57:42.376 --> 00:57:45.956
would be an element of itself if and only if
it's not an element of itself, which is a

00:57:45.996 --> 00:57:51.436
contradiction. So this is the essence of
the Russell paradox. I don't call it the

00:57:51.456 --> 00:57:55.016
Russell paradox. Actually, when I teach it,
I call it Russell's theorem. There's no

00:57:55.096 --> 00:57:58.736
universal set. And it's not really

00:57:58.776 --> 00:58:05.756
confusing anymore. At the time, it was very
confusing, but now we've absorbed this

00:58:05.836 --> 00:58:09.756
nature of set theory into our
fundamental understanding of how sets

00:58:09.796 --> 00:58:13.786
are, and it's not confusing anymore. I mean,
the history is fascinating though about

00:58:13.816 --> 00:58:17.656
the Russell paradox, because before that

00:58:17.696 --> 00:58:20.956
time, Frege was working
on his monumental work

00:58:21.656 --> 00:58:25.616
undertaking, implementing the
philosophy of logicism, which is

00:58:25.676 --> 00:58:29.496
the attempt to reduce all
of mathematics to logic.

00:58:30.176 --> 00:58:33.716
So Frege wanted to give an
account of all of mathematics in

00:58:33.776 --> 00:58:37.636
terms of logical notions, and he

00:58:37.676 --> 00:58:41.596
was writing this monumental work
and had formulated his basic

00:58:41.606 --> 00:58:45.156
principles. And those
principles happened to

00:58:45.216 --> 00:58:51.456
imply that for any property whatsoever, you
could form the set of objects with that

00:58:51.476 --> 00:58:59.445
property. This is known as the
general comprehension principle. And

00:58:59.476 --> 00:59:03.396
he was appealing to the principles
that support that axiom,

00:59:03.476 --> 00:59:07.416
throughout his work. I
mean, it wasn't just an

00:59:07.496 --> 00:59:12.976
incidental thing. He was really using this
principle. And Russell wrote him a letter

00:59:13.816 --> 00:59:17.656
when he observed the work
in progress, that there was

00:59:17.696 --> 00:59:21.656
this problem, because if you accept the principle
that for any property whatsoever, you can make

00:59:21.696 --> 00:59:25.516
a set of objects with that property,
then you could form the set of

00:59:25.616 --> 00:59:29.036
all sets that are not members
of themselves. That's just an

00:59:29.096 --> 00:59:34.756
instance of the general
comprehension principle. And

00:59:36.196 --> 00:59:40.056
the set of all sets that aren't elements of
themselves can't be a set, because if it

00:59:40.096 --> 00:59:43.636
were, then it would be an element of
itself if and only if it's not a member of

00:59:43.676 --> 00:59:45.416
itself, and that's a contradiction.

00:59:46.456 --> 00:59:50.066
And so Russell wrote this letter to
Frege, and it was just at the moment

00:59:50.156 --> 00:59:53.896
when Frege was finishing his work.
It was already at the publishers

00:59:54.016 --> 00:59:57.616
and, you know, in press
basically. But it's

00:59:57.676 --> 01:00:01.136
completely devastating. I
mean, it must have been such a

01:00:01.216 --> 01:00:04.636
horrible situation for
Frege to be placed in

01:00:04.716 --> 01:00:09.036
because he's finished this
monumental work, you know,

01:00:10.076 --> 01:00:14.496
years of his life dedicated to
this, and Russell finds this

01:00:15.516 --> 01:00:20.776
basically one-line proof of a contradiction
in the fundamental principles of

01:00:20.856 --> 01:00:26.296
the thesis that completely
destroys the whole system. And

01:00:27.916 --> 01:00:31.236
Frege had put in the
appendix of his work a

01:00:31.286 --> 01:00:35.076
response to Russell's letter in which he
explained what happened, and he wrote

01:00:35.156 --> 01:00:38.836
very gracefully, "Hardly anything
more unwelcome can befall a

01:00:38.876 --> 01:00:42.616
scientific writer than to have one of the
foundations of his edifice shaken after the

01:00:42.716 --> 01:00:46.566
work is finished. This is the position
into which I was put by a letter from

01:00:46.596 --> 01:00:49.156
Mr. Bertrand Russell as the
printing of this volume was nearing

01:00:49.196 --> 01:00:53.076
completion." And then he goes on to explain
the matter, it concerns his basic law

01:00:53.156 --> 01:00:54.386
five, and so on, and...

01:00:54.396 --> 01:00:57.056
- It's heartbreaking. I mean,
there's nothing more traumatic to

01:00:58.056 --> 01:01:01.976
a person who dreams of constructing
mathematics all from logic.

01:01:02.716 --> 01:01:08.386
to get a very clean, simple
contradiction. I mean, that's just...

01:01:08.396 --> 01:01:13.416
- You devote your life to this work, and
then it's shown to be contradictory, and

01:01:13.496 --> 01:01:15.006
that must have been heartbreaking.

01:01:16.676 --> 01:01:20.596
- What do you think about the Frege
project, the philosophy of logic,

01:01:20.606 --> 01:01:22.376
the dream of the power of logic-

01:01:22.496 --> 01:01:22.596
- Right

01:01:22.606 --> 01:01:24.176
- ... to construct a mathematical universe?

01:01:24.196 --> 01:01:27.996
- So, of course, the project
of logicism did not die with

01:01:28.016 --> 01:01:31.616
Frege, and it was continued,
and, you know, there's a whole

01:01:31.676 --> 01:01:35.256
movement, the neologicists and
so on, in contemporary times

01:01:35.356 --> 01:01:39.284
even. But my view of the
matter is that, really, we

01:01:39.324 --> 01:01:44.814
should view the main goals of logicism
are basically completely fulfilled

01:01:45.684 --> 01:01:49.284
in the rise of set-theoretic
foundationalism. I mean,

01:01:49.424 --> 01:01:56.804
When you view ZFC as the foundation of
mathematics, and in my view, the principles of

01:01:56.844 --> 01:02:00.824
ZFC are fundamentally illogical in
character including the axiom of

01:02:00.864 --> 01:02:04.824
choice, as I mentioned, as a
principle of logic. This is a

01:02:04.864 --> 01:02:08.784
highly disputed point of view, though, cause
a lot of people take even the axiom of

01:02:08.844 --> 01:02:12.513
infinity as inherently mathematical and

01:02:12.584 --> 01:02:16.344
not logical and so on. But I
think if you adopt the view

01:02:17.044 --> 01:02:20.774
that the principles of ZFC have
to do with the principles of

01:02:20.884 --> 01:02:24.604
abstract, you know, set
formation, which is fundamentally

01:02:24.684 --> 01:02:28.164
logical in character, then
it's complete success for

01:02:28.184 --> 01:02:32.024
logicism. So the fact that set theory
is able to serve as a foundation

01:02:32.104 --> 01:02:35.724
means that mathematics
can be founded on logic.

01:02:35.804 --> 01:02:39.784
- I think this is a good moment to
talk about Gödel's incompleteness

01:02:39.844 --> 01:02:43.763
theorems. So, can you explain
them and what do they teach

01:02:43.804 --> 01:02:46.964
us about the nature of mathematical truth?

01:02:47.104 --> 01:02:51.004
- Absolutely. It's one of the most
profound developments in mathematical

01:02:51.164 --> 01:02:53.144
logic. I mean, the
incompleteness theorems is when

01:02:54.124 --> 01:02:58.904
mathematical logic, in my view,
first became sophisticated.

01:02:59.744 --> 01:03:03.544
It's a kind of birth of the
subject of mathematical

01:03:03.604 --> 01:03:07.544
logic. But to understand the theorems,
you really have to start a little

01:03:07.584 --> 01:03:09.644
bit earlier with Hilbert's program.

01:03:10.564 --> 01:03:14.464
because at that time, you know, with the Russell Paradox
and so on, there were these various contradictions

01:03:14.584 --> 01:03:18.124
popping up in various parts of
set theory and the Burali-Forti

01:03:18.244 --> 01:03:25.644
paradox and so on. And, and Hilbert was
famously supportive of set theory. I mean,

01:03:25.704 --> 01:03:29.484
there's this quote of him saying, "No one

01:03:29.524 --> 01:03:33.104
shall cast us from the paradise
that Cantor has created for

01:03:33.204 --> 01:03:36.974
us." And what I take him
to mean by that is he was

01:03:37.004 --> 01:03:40.944
so captured by the idea of using
set theory as a foundation

01:03:40.984 --> 01:03:44.904
of mathematics and it was so powerful
and convenient and unifying in a

01:03:44.944 --> 01:03:48.664
way that was extremely important. And
he wasn't, he didn't wanna give that

01:03:48.704 --> 01:03:52.184
up, despite the danger of these

01:03:53.224 --> 01:03:58.233
paradoxes, these contradictions, basically,
is how some people viewed them. And so,

01:03:58.233 --> 01:04:00.094
- this minefield of paradoxes. Yeah.

01:04:00.104 --> 01:04:03.844
- Right. A minefield. That's a really good
way of describing the situation. And

01:04:03.924 --> 01:04:07.084
so Hilbert said, "Well,
look, we have to fix this

01:04:07.424 --> 01:04:11.404
problem, you know. We wanna use the
set theory foundations, but we want to

01:04:11.444 --> 01:04:15.154
do it in a way that is trustworthy
and reliable. We can't

01:04:15.184 --> 01:04:18.544
allow that the foundations
of mathematics are in

01:04:18.664 --> 01:04:23.804
question. You know, this is a kind of
attitude, I think, that underlies Hilbert

01:04:24.704 --> 01:04:28.644
and the Hilbert program.
And so he proposed, "Look,

01:04:28.744 --> 01:04:32.724
we're going to have this strong theory,
this set theory that we want to be proving

01:04:32.764 --> 01:04:36.704
our theorems in but I

01:04:36.764 --> 01:04:40.644
I mean, on the one hand, we want it
to be as strong as possible. We would

01:04:40.704 --> 01:04:44.524
like it to answer all the
questions." There's another

01:04:44.564 --> 01:04:48.194
famous quote of Hilbert in
his retirement address where,

01:04:48.284 --> 01:04:51.984
he proclaims, "Wir müssen wissen, wir

01:04:51.994 --> 01:04:55.934
werden wissen." So, "We must
know, we will know," in

01:04:55.964 --> 01:04:59.724
which he's very optimistic
about the ability of

01:04:59.784 --> 01:05:04.144
mathematics to answer all of the
questions of mathematics that

01:05:05.244 --> 01:05:09.214
we have posed. We have all these problems
we want to solve and he is saying,

01:05:09.264 --> 01:05:13.164
"We're going to do it. We're going to solve all these
problems." So we want to propose this strong theory

01:05:13.464 --> 01:05:16.244
and one has the sense
that he had in mind set

01:05:16.324 --> 01:05:19.924
theory in which all the
questions are going to be

01:05:19.984 --> 01:05:27.084
answered. Okay? But secondly, we
want to combine that with, in a very

01:05:27.284 --> 01:05:31.944
weak arithmetic, purely finitistic
theory, we want to prove

01:05:32.904 --> 01:05:36.024
that the reasoning process
of the strong theory is

01:05:36.104 --> 01:05:39.824
safe. Okay? So in order to make
sense of that point of view, you

01:05:39.864 --> 01:05:46.264
basically have to invent the philosophy of
formalism, where we can look at what is a

01:05:46.324 --> 01:05:49.204
proof, what is the nature of mathematical

01:05:49.304 --> 01:05:53.104
reasoning. And on Hilbert's
way of thinking about

01:05:53.164 --> 01:06:00.484
this, a proof is basically itself a
finitistic kind of object. It's a sequence

01:06:00.584 --> 01:06:04.304
of... If you think about the nature of
what a proof is, it's a sequence of

01:06:04.344 --> 01:06:08.264
assertions which can be viewed
as sort of sequences of symbols

01:06:08.274 --> 01:06:12.224
that conform with certain
rules of logical reasoning.

01:06:12.284 --> 01:06:16.044
And this is a formalist way of
understanding the nature of

01:06:16.084 --> 01:06:19.344
proof. So we think about a proof
in a kind of syntactic, formal

01:06:19.384 --> 01:06:23.064
way. Even though the contents
of those statements might be

01:06:23.144 --> 01:06:26.964
referring to infinite uncountable objects,

01:06:27.124 --> 01:06:31.064
the statements themselves are not infinite
uncountable objects. The statements themselves are

01:06:31.124 --> 01:06:33.144
just finite sequences of symbols.

01:06:33.184 --> 01:06:36.844
- So when you think of proof as, maybe
it's fair to say, almost like a

01:06:36.984 --> 01:06:40.924
outside of math. It's like, tools
operating on math. And then for

01:06:40.984 --> 01:06:45.704
Hilbert, he thought proof is inside the
axiomatic system. Something like this.

01:06:45.764 --> 01:06:46.864
- Yeah, that's helpful.

01:06:46.884 --> 01:06:47.664
- That's wild.

01:06:48.344 --> 01:06:52.084
- The main thing about formalism is that you

01:06:52.184 --> 01:06:55.984
think of the process of doing
mathematics. You divorce it

01:06:56.104 --> 01:07:00.084
from the meaning of the mathematical
assertions, right? So the

01:07:00.144 --> 01:07:04.004
meaning of the mathematical assertions
that you make in this infinitary theory

01:07:04.064 --> 01:07:08.034
has to do with these huge uncountable
infinities and so on possibly.

01:07:08.064 --> 01:07:15.864
And that's a very sort of uncertain realm
maybe and the source of the paradoxes

01:07:15.904 --> 01:07:19.694
and so on in some people's
minds. But the reasoning

01:07:19.764 --> 01:07:23.604
process itself consists of
writing down sequences of symbols

01:07:23.684 --> 01:07:27.044
on your page and, you
know, undertaking or,

01:07:27.144 --> 01:07:33.044
an argument with them which is
following these finitary rules. And so,

01:07:33.984 --> 01:07:37.494
if we divorce the meaning of the
symbols from just the process of

01:07:37.524 --> 01:07:40.904
manipulating the symbols, it's a way of
looking at the nature of mathematics

01:07:40.944 --> 01:07:43.574
as a kind of formal game in which-

01:07:43.574 --> 01:07:47.562
the meaning may be totally absent.
I don't think it's necessarily

01:07:47.752 --> 01:07:51.232
part of the formalist view that there
is no meaning behind, but rather it's

01:07:51.292 --> 01:07:55.112
emphasizing that we can
divorce the meaning of

01:07:55.172 --> 01:07:58.852
the sentences from the process
of manipulating those sentences.

01:07:59.532 --> 01:08:02.852
And then Hilbert wanted to
prove in this purely finitary

01:08:02.912 --> 01:08:06.692
theory that if we follow the
rules of that game, we're

01:08:06.702 --> 01:08:09.652
never going to get a contradiction.

01:08:09.692 --> 01:08:13.532
So those were the two aims of
the Hilbert program, is to

01:08:13.592 --> 01:08:16.932
found the strong infinitary
theory, probably set

01:08:16.952 --> 01:08:20.732
theory, which is going to answer
all the questions. And then

01:08:20.832 --> 01:08:28.272
secondly, prove in the finitary
theory that the strong theory is

01:08:28.292 --> 01:08:31.542
safe. In other words, consistent, yeah?

01:08:31.591 --> 01:08:34.192
- What does the word "finitary"
in finitary theory mean?

01:08:34.272 --> 01:08:37.971
- Yeah. Well, this is, of course,
philosophically contentious, and people

01:08:38.011 --> 01:08:42.002
have different ideas about what exactly
it should mean. So there's hundreds

01:08:42.051 --> 01:08:45.562
of papers on exactly that question.
But I like to take it just kind of

01:08:45.612 --> 01:08:49.252
informally. I mean, it means that we're
talking about finite sequences of

01:08:49.292 --> 01:08:52.852
symbols, and we're going to
have a theory, you know, finite

01:08:52.932 --> 01:08:56.671
strings of symbols. A
finitary theory would be

01:08:56.772 --> 01:09:00.352
one whose subject matter is about
those kinds of things so that we

01:09:00.412 --> 01:09:04.312
can conceivably argue about the nature

01:09:04.452 --> 01:09:08.341
of these finite strings. A proof is
just a finite sequence of statements,

01:09:08.412 --> 01:09:12.252
so that every statement is either
one of the axioms or follows

01:09:12.332 --> 01:09:15.932
by the laws of logic from the
earlier statements in some specified

01:09:15.992 --> 01:09:20.332
manner, like using modus ponens or
some other law of logic like that.

01:09:21.211 --> 01:09:25.192
And such that the last line on the
list is, you know, the theorem

01:09:25.252 --> 01:09:29.692
that you're proving. So that's what a
proof is in this kind of way of thinking.

01:09:29.732 --> 01:09:33.711
To take a specific example, I mean, I
always conceive of the, perhaps the

01:09:33.752 --> 01:09:37.312
most natural finitary theory
that one would be called upon to

01:09:37.532 --> 01:09:41.432
exhibit would be Peano arithmetic, the
theory of Peano arithmetic, which-

01:09:41.471 --> 01:09:44.832
which is a first order
theory of the nature of

01:09:44.872 --> 01:09:48.752
arithmetic. But okay, so some
people say, "Well, Peano

01:09:48.772 --> 01:09:52.532
arithmetic has these strong first order
induction axioms, and there's much,

01:09:52.612 --> 01:09:56.562
much weaker versions of arithmetic,
like I-sigma-naught or I-sigma-1 and

01:09:56.612 --> 01:09:59.812
so on, which are even
more finitary than Peano

01:09:59.852 --> 01:10:03.592
arithmetic." So different
philosophical positions take different

01:10:03.652 --> 01:10:07.592
attitudes about what is, what does it
take to be finitary? How finitary do you

01:10:07.632 --> 01:10:10.092
have to be to be truly finitary?

01:10:10.452 --> 01:10:13.642
- So according to Perplexity, Peano
arithmetic is a foundational system for

01:10:13.792 --> 01:10:17.672
formalizing the properties and operations
of natural numbers using a set of

01:10:17.732 --> 01:10:21.532
axioms called the Peano axioms.
Peano arithmetic provides a

01:10:21.592 --> 01:10:25.261
formal language and axioms for
arithmetic operations, such as

01:10:25.272 --> 01:10:29.172
addition and multiplication over the
natural numbers. The axioms define the

01:10:29.212 --> 01:10:32.792
existence of a first natural
number, usually zero or

01:10:32.812 --> 01:10:36.732
one, the concept of a successor
function, which generates

01:10:36.772 --> 01:10:40.752
the next natural number, rules for addition
and multiplication built from these

01:10:40.812 --> 01:10:44.512
concepts, the principle of induction
allowing proofs around all

01:10:44.552 --> 01:10:48.192
natural numbers, and it goes on. So it's
a very particular kind of arithmetic

01:10:48.212 --> 01:10:51.712
that is finitary.

01:10:51.772 --> 01:10:55.632
- You know, in my... I view it as finitary, but this
is a contentious view. Not everyone agrees with

01:10:55.672 --> 01:10:58.012
that. That's what I was trying to hint at.

01:10:58.032 --> 01:10:58.232
- Okay. I got it. All right.

01:10:58.272 --> 01:11:04.622
- Peano arithmetic is one of the
hugely successful theories

01:11:04.812 --> 01:11:07.952
of the natural numbers and
elementary number theory.

01:11:07.992 --> 01:11:11.832
Essentially, all of
classical number theory, so

01:11:11.852 --> 01:11:15.122
whatever kind of theorems you want to
be proving about the prime numbers or

01:11:15.152 --> 01:11:18.972
factorization or any kind
of finitary reasoning about

01:11:19.032 --> 01:11:22.912
finite combinatorial objects,
all of it can be formalized in

01:11:22.952 --> 01:11:26.812
Peano arithmetic. I mean,
that's the basic situation. Of

01:11:26.832 --> 01:11:30.202
course, one has to qualify those statements
in light of the Gödel incompleteness

01:11:30.252 --> 01:11:37.412
theorem, but for the most part, the
classical number theoretic analysis of

01:11:37.492 --> 01:11:44.592
the finite numbers is almost entirely
developable inside Peano arithmetic.

01:11:45.552 --> 01:11:49.812
So if we go back to the Hilbert program,
so Hilbert has these two goals:

01:11:50.832 --> 01:11:54.332
produce the strong theory which is going
to answer all the questions, and then

01:11:54.392 --> 01:11:56.552
prove by purely finitary means

01:11:57.392 --> 01:12:01.212
that that theory will never lead
into contradiction. And one

01:12:01.272 --> 01:12:05.252
can think about, well, the incompleteness
theorem should be viewed as a

01:12:05.262 --> 01:12:09.252
decisive refutation of the
Hilbert program. It defeats

01:12:09.292 --> 01:12:15.932
both of those goals decisively,
completely. But before explaining

01:12:15.942 --> 01:12:19.712
that, maybe one should think about, you know,
what if Hilbert had been right? What would

01:12:19.832 --> 01:12:24.962
be the nature of mathematics in the world
that Hilbert is telling us to search for?

01:12:24.972 --> 01:12:28.572
- And if I may, going to Perplexity's
definition of Hilbert's

01:12:28.612 --> 01:12:32.442
program, it was David Hilbert's early
20th century project to give all

01:12:32.472 --> 01:12:36.432
of classical mathematics a
completely secure finitary

01:12:36.512 --> 01:12:40.072
foundation. In essence, the
goal was to formalize all of

01:12:40.112 --> 01:12:43.932
mathematics in precise
axiomatic systems and then

01:12:44.032 --> 01:12:47.982
prove using only very
elementary finitary reasoning

01:12:48.052 --> 01:12:51.492
about symbols that these systems
are free of contradiction.

01:12:51.532 --> 01:12:55.472
- Right. Exactly right. Let's imagine
what it would be like if he had been

01:12:55.492 --> 01:12:58.592
right. So we would have
this finitary theory,

01:12:59.772 --> 01:13:03.412
and it would prove that the strong
theory was free of contradiction.

01:13:04.212 --> 01:13:10.392
So we could start enumerating proofs from
the strong theory. Right now, we can

01:13:11.272 --> 01:13:16.532
write a computer program that would
systematically generate all possible proofs

01:13:17.612 --> 01:13:26.492
from a given theory. And so we
could have, like, this theorem

01:13:27.412 --> 01:13:31.332
enumeration machine that would just
spit out theorems all day long in such

01:13:31.392 --> 01:13:35.402
a manner that every single theorem would
eventually be produced by this device.

01:13:37.012 --> 01:13:44.752
And so if you had a mathematical question
of any kind, you could answer it by just

01:13:45.132 --> 01:13:48.092
waiting for either the
answer to come out yes

01:13:48.112 --> 01:13:52.048
or from the machine or the
answer to come out no. So

01:13:52.108 --> 01:13:55.688
the nature of mathematical
investigation in Hilbert's world

01:13:55.928 --> 01:13:59.808
is one of just turning the crank
of the theorem enumeration

01:13:59.867 --> 01:14:03.708
machine, devoid of creative thinking or

01:14:03.748 --> 01:14:07.558
imagination, it's just getting
the answer from this by rote.

01:14:07.628 --> 01:14:15.348
procedure. So Hilbert, in effect, is telling
us, I mean, with his program, that the

01:14:15.388 --> 01:14:19.327
fundamental nature of mathematics is
rote computation. I mean, the way I

01:14:19.348 --> 01:14:22.648
think about the Hilbert program
seems extremely attractive in the

01:14:23.008 --> 01:14:26.968
historical context of being
worried about the antinomies,

01:14:26.987 --> 01:14:31.838
the inconsistencies, and so
how can we kind of block them?

01:14:31.838 --> 01:14:35.768
It seems natural, first of all, to have
a strong theory that's going to answer

01:14:35.788 --> 01:14:39.487
all the questions, because the
idea of logical independence and

01:14:39.508 --> 01:14:46.808
pervasiveness that we now know exists
just wasn't, you know, there was

01:14:46.867 --> 01:14:50.708
no known. They didn't know
anything like that happening ever.

01:14:50.788 --> 01:14:54.598
And so it's natural to think that
it wouldn't happen, and also

01:14:54.668 --> 01:14:58.327
that they would be able to guard against
this inconsistency. So it seems like the

01:14:58.348 --> 01:15:03.848
goals of the Hilbert program are quite
natural in that historical context.

01:15:03.867 --> 01:15:07.848
But, you know, when you think a little more
about what the nature of it would be like,

01:15:07.888 --> 01:15:11.728
it shows you this kind of rote procedure.
And now you're saying, well, that

01:15:11.768 --> 01:15:15.208
doesn't seem so unlikely maybe,
I mean, in the light of the

01:15:15.268 --> 01:15:19.148
increasing computer power and so on,
it's actually maybe turning into

01:15:19.168 --> 01:15:23.028
our everyday experience, where the
machines are calculating more and more for

01:15:23.108 --> 01:15:30.508
us in a way that could be alarming.
Okay. But, okay, so to talk about the

01:15:30.548 --> 01:15:33.907
alternative to the Hilbert
point of view, I mean, if he's

01:15:33.928 --> 01:15:37.867
wrong, then what is the nature of
mathematical reality? Well, it would mean

01:15:37.928 --> 01:15:41.688
that we couldn't ever maybe,
for the first goal, we

01:15:41.708 --> 01:15:44.867
couldn't ever write down a
theory that answered all the

01:15:44.928 --> 01:15:48.848
questions. So we would always be in

01:15:48.888 --> 01:15:53.788
a situation where our best theory,
even the infinitary theories,

01:15:55.728 --> 01:15:59.528
would have questions that they stumble
with and are unable to answer.

01:15:59.547 --> 01:16:03.508
Independence would occur.
But then also, because of

01:16:03.548 --> 01:16:07.148
the failure of the second
goal, we would also have to be

01:16:07.208 --> 01:16:11.188
constantly worrying about whether our theories
were consistent or not, and we wouldn't

01:16:11.228 --> 01:16:14.867
have any truly convincing means of

01:16:14.947 --> 01:16:18.748
saying that they were free
from contradiction. And

01:16:18.808 --> 01:16:26.288
the fact of Gödel's Incompleteness Theorem
shows that that is exactly the nature of

01:16:26.327 --> 01:16:30.258
mathematical reality, actually. Those
are the two incompleteness theorems.

01:16:30.288 --> 01:16:33.487
So the first incompleteness
theorem says you cannot write

01:16:33.568 --> 01:16:37.367
down a computably axiomatizable
theory that answers all the

01:16:37.407 --> 01:16:40.867
questions. Every such
theory will be incomplete,

01:16:40.938 --> 01:16:44.208
assuming it includes a certain
amount of arithmetic. And

01:16:44.288 --> 01:16:48.168
secondly, no such theory can ever prove
its own consistency. So not only is

01:16:48.208 --> 01:16:51.827
it the case that the finitary theory
can't prove the consistency of the

01:16:51.968 --> 01:16:55.827
strong infinitary theory, but even
the infinitary theory can't prove

01:16:55.888 --> 01:16:59.288
its own consistency, right?
That's the second incompleteness

01:16:59.348 --> 01:17:05.588
theorem. And so it's, in that sense,
a decisive takedown of the Hilbert

01:17:05.628 --> 01:17:09.508
program, which is really
quite remarkable, the

01:17:09.548 --> 01:17:13.367
extent to which his theorem
just really answered that

01:17:13.447 --> 01:17:17.088
whole puzzle. It's quite amazing.

01:17:17.568 --> 01:17:21.508
I mean, there's another aspect,
kind of easy to think about.

01:17:21.528 --> 01:17:25.367
I mean, if you're wondering
about theories that prove their

01:17:25.407 --> 01:17:29.288
own consistency, then, I mean,
would you trust a theory

01:17:29.367 --> 01:17:33.248
that proves of itself
that it's consistent? I

01:17:33.288 --> 01:17:36.968
mean, that's like... it's
like the used car salesman

01:17:37.068 --> 01:17:41.008
telling you, "Oh, I'm trustworthy."
I mean, it's not a reason

01:17:41.048 --> 01:17:44.568
to trust the used car salesman,
is it? Just because he says that.

01:17:45.108 --> 01:17:49.048
So similarly, if you have a theory that
proves its own consistency, well, even an

01:17:49.108 --> 01:17:52.987
inconsistent theory would prove its
own consistency. And so it doesn't

01:17:53.028 --> 01:17:56.987
seem to be a logical reason to believe
in the consistency, if you have a

01:17:57.028 --> 01:17:58.978
theory that proves itself consistent.

01:17:59.068 --> 01:18:03.028
- Just for clarification,
you used the word theory.

01:18:03.088 --> 01:18:07.388
Is it, in this context,
synonymous with axiomatic system?

01:18:07.467 --> 01:18:11.407
- Right. So in mathematical logic,
"theory" is a technical term.

01:18:11.458 --> 01:18:15.348
And it means any set of sentences
in a formal language. And so

01:18:15.407 --> 01:18:19.047
if you say axiomatic system,
it's basically synonymous to my

01:18:19.148 --> 01:18:22.827
usage with theory. So a
theory means, you know, the

01:18:22.907 --> 01:18:26.808
consequences of a set of axioms or... People
are sometimes unclear on whether they just mean

01:18:26.827 --> 01:18:29.077
the axioms or the consequences
of the axioms, but...

01:18:29.088 --> 01:18:32.748
- So theory includes both the axioms
and the consequences of the

01:18:32.848 --> 01:18:36.827
axioms, and you use it interchangeably
and the context is supposed to

01:18:36.888 --> 01:18:40.788
help you figure out which of the two
you're talking about? The axioms

01:18:40.808 --> 01:18:44.168
or the consequences? Or maybe to
you, they're basically the same?

01:18:44.228 --> 01:18:47.878
- Yeah, well, they're so closely connected,
although all the features aren't the same.

01:18:47.907 --> 01:18:55.708
So if you have a computable list
of axioms for a theory, then you

01:18:55.768 --> 01:18:59.008
can start enumerating
the consequences of the

01:18:59.048 --> 01:19:02.848
axioms, but you won't be
able to computably decide

01:19:02.867 --> 01:19:06.748
whether a given statement is a
consequence or not. You can enumerate the

01:19:06.808 --> 01:19:10.688
consequences, so you can semi-decide the

01:19:10.728 --> 01:19:14.648
consequences, but you won't be able to
decide yes or no whether a given statement

01:19:14.688 --> 01:19:16.358
is a consequence or not.

01:19:17.327 --> 01:19:21.128
So it's the distinction between a
problem being computably decidable and a

01:19:21.148 --> 01:19:24.468
problem being computably
enumerable, which,

01:19:24.588 --> 01:19:28.518
was made clear following the
work of Turing and others

01:19:28.568 --> 01:19:32.388
that came from that. I mean, so that's
one difference between the list of

01:19:32.508 --> 01:19:36.407
axioms of the theory and the
theory itself. The axioms could

01:19:36.447 --> 01:19:40.327
be... You can decide, maybe computably,
whether something is an axiom or not, but

01:19:40.348 --> 01:19:44.208
that doesn't mean that you can decide computably
whether or not something is a theorem

01:19:44.248 --> 01:19:47.827
or not. Usually, you only
get to decide the positive

01:19:47.867 --> 01:19:51.788
instances. If something is a theorem, you will eventually
come to recognize that, but if something isn't

01:19:51.808 --> 01:19:56.298
a theorem, maybe at no point will you be
able to say, "No, that's not a theorem."

01:19:56.327 --> 01:19:58.508
- And that's of course connected
to the halting problem.

01:19:58.648 --> 01:20:02.036
...and all of these
contradictions and paradoxes are

01:20:02.116 --> 01:20:06.276
all nicely, beautifully interconnected.

01:20:06.296 --> 01:20:09.156
So can we just linger on
Gödel's incompleteness theorem?

01:20:09.176 --> 01:20:11.356
You mentioned the two components there.

01:20:12.176 --> 01:20:15.816
You know, there's so many questions to
ask, like what is the difference between

01:20:15.976 --> 01:20:19.816
provability and truth?
What is true and what

01:20:19.856 --> 01:20:21.806
is provable? Maybe that's
a good line to draw.

01:20:21.816 --> 01:20:25.816
- Yeah, this is a really
core distinction that

01:20:27.436 --> 01:20:31.336
it's fascinating to me to go back and read

01:20:32.256 --> 01:20:37.136
even the early 20th century
people before Gödel and Tarski,

01:20:38.336 --> 01:20:41.876
and they were totally sloppy
about this distinction

01:20:41.976 --> 01:20:45.536
between truth and proof.
It wasn't clear at all

01:20:45.596 --> 01:20:48.866
until Gödel, basically.
Although even as late as

01:20:49.316 --> 01:20:52.756
Bourbaki has the kind of confusion in this

01:20:52.816 --> 01:20:56.396
foundational work. So, this
standard graduate-level

01:20:56.456 --> 01:21:03.726
textbook used in France in the presentation
of logic, they are conflating truth and

01:21:03.836 --> 01:21:07.776
proof. To be true for them
means to be provable. So, in

01:21:07.796 --> 01:21:11.496
the early days, maybe it wasn't clear
enough that the concept of truth

01:21:11.596 --> 01:21:15.176
needed a mathematical investigation or

01:21:15.216 --> 01:21:19.156
analysis. Maybe it was already
taken to be fully clear.

01:21:19.176 --> 01:21:22.836
But because of the incompleteness theorem,
we realized that actually there's quite

01:21:23.016 --> 01:21:26.856
subtle things happening, right?
And so, why don't we talk about

01:21:26.896 --> 01:21:30.616
this distinction a bit? To me, it's
absolutely core and fundamental

01:21:30.636 --> 01:21:33.546
to our understanding of
mathematical logic now.

01:21:34.016 --> 01:21:40.076
This distinction between
truth and proof. So, truth is

01:21:41.036 --> 01:21:44.936
on the semantic side of the
syntax-semantics dichotomy.

01:21:44.956 --> 01:21:48.916
Truth has to do with the
nature of reality. I

01:21:48.976 --> 01:21:52.866
mean, okay, when I talk about reality,
I'm not talking about physical reality.

01:21:52.896 --> 01:21:56.516
I'm talking about mathematical reality.
So, we have a concept of something being

01:21:56.576 --> 01:22:00.476
true in a structure, a statement being
true in a mathematical structure.

01:22:00.496 --> 01:22:04.376
Like maybe you have the real field or something,
and you want to know, does it satisfy this

01:22:04.456 --> 01:22:08.416
statement or that statement? Or you
have a group of some kind, or maybe

01:22:08.436 --> 01:22:11.876
you have a graph. This is a particular
kind of mathematical structure

01:22:12.336 --> 01:22:15.776
that has a bunch of vertices
and edges, and you want to know

01:22:16.296 --> 01:22:19.776
does this graph satisfy
that statement? And

01:22:19.816 --> 01:22:23.716
Tarski gave this absolutely
wonderful account of the

01:22:23.756 --> 01:22:27.676
nature of truth in what's now
known as the disquotational

01:22:27.696 --> 01:22:34.956
theory of truth. And what Tarski says
is the sentence, "Snow is white,"

01:22:35.036 --> 01:22:45.576
is true if and only if snow is white. And
what he means by that is, look, to say

01:22:46.496 --> 01:22:50.476
truth is a property of an assertion,
so we can think of the assertion as it

01:22:51.076 --> 01:22:56.336
syntactically. So, the sentence is true

01:22:57.216 --> 01:23:00.916
if and only if the content of
the sentence is the case. You

01:23:00.936 --> 01:23:08.176
know? So, the sentence, "Snow is white,"
you know, in quotations is true, that

01:23:08.276 --> 01:23:12.046
just means that snow is white. And

01:23:12.096 --> 01:23:16.066
that's why it's called the disquotational
theory because we remove the quotation marks.

01:23:16.476 --> 01:23:20.306
from the assertion, right?
And you can use this idea of

01:23:20.416 --> 01:23:24.356
disquotation to give a formal
definition of truth in a

01:23:24.396 --> 01:23:28.366
mathematical structure of a statement in
a formal language. So, for example, if I

01:23:28.396 --> 01:23:31.756
have a formal language that allows
me to make atomic statements

01:23:31.816 --> 01:23:34.976
about the objects and relations of the

01:23:35.036 --> 01:23:38.596
structure, and I can build up a
formal language with, you know,

01:23:38.616 --> 01:23:41.945
with the logical connectives
of "and" and "or" and

01:23:41.976 --> 01:23:45.676
"implies" and "not" and so on, and
maybe I have quantifiers, right? Then,

01:23:46.356 --> 01:23:49.836
for example, to say that
the structure satisfies phi

01:23:50.076 --> 01:23:53.876
and psi, that that single statement, phi

01:23:53.976 --> 01:24:00.135
and psi, I'm thinking of that as one
statement, just means that it satisfies phi

01:24:00.596 --> 01:24:05.176
and it satisfies psi. And if
you notice what happened there,

01:24:06.656 --> 01:24:10.196
I... At first, the 'and' was
part of the sentence inside the

01:24:10.216 --> 01:24:14.176
sentence, but then in the second
part, I was using the word

01:24:14.356 --> 01:24:17.436
'and' to refer to the conjunction
of the two conditions. So-

01:24:17.456 --> 01:24:18.806
- Yeah, it has the disquotation.

01:24:18.816 --> 01:24:20.216
- Yeah, it has the disquotation.

01:24:20.286 --> 01:24:24.085
And so this idea can be done for all the
logical connectors and quantifiers and

01:24:24.236 --> 01:24:27.996
everything. You're applying
Tarski's idea of disquotation,

01:24:28.836 --> 01:24:32.756
and it allows you to define
by induction the truth of any

01:24:32.816 --> 01:24:36.716
assertion in a formal language inside
any mathematical structure. And

01:24:36.756 --> 01:24:40.596
so to say that a sentence is true,
first of all, it's ambiguous

01:24:40.636 --> 01:24:44.326
unless you tell me which structure
you're talking about it being true in.

01:24:45.316 --> 01:24:49.176
And so maybe we have in mind the
standard model of arithmetic

01:24:49.316 --> 01:24:53.116
or something with the natural numbers and the arithmetic
structure, and I want to know is a given statement

01:24:53.196 --> 01:24:56.926
true in that structure. Then we have a
formal definition of what that means

01:24:56.976 --> 01:25:04.396
according to the Tarski recursive
definition of truth. Okay, that's

01:25:04.436 --> 01:25:08.226
truth. Proof, on the other
hand, is, you know, in

01:25:08.296 --> 01:25:12.266
this Hilbert way of thinking, we
can develop proof theory. What is

01:25:12.316 --> 01:25:15.396
a proof for a mathematician,
for a mathematical logician? A

01:25:15.456 --> 01:25:22.896
proof is a certain sequence or arrangement
of sentences in the formal language that

01:25:22.956 --> 01:25:26.676
accord with the logical rules of a proof

01:25:26.716 --> 01:25:29.876
system. So there are certain
modes of reasoning that are

01:25:29.936 --> 01:25:33.916
allowed. So if you know A
and you know A implies B in

01:25:33.956 --> 01:25:37.296
the proof, then at a later
step you're allowed to

01:25:37.316 --> 01:25:41.176
write B as a consequence. So if you know A

01:25:41.256 --> 01:25:44.936
and you know A implies B, those are both
two statements that are known, then

01:25:45.436 --> 01:25:49.136
you can deduce B as a consequence
according to the rule of modus

01:25:49.146 --> 01:25:53.126
ponens. This is the rule of modus ponens.
And, you know, there are a lot of other

01:25:53.156 --> 01:25:57.116
rules. Some people would call this
implication elimination. There are

01:25:57.156 --> 01:26:00.976
different kinds of proof systems.
There are a lot of different formal

01:26:01.056 --> 01:26:05.016
proof systems that exist that are studied by
the proof theorists, and all of them have

01:26:05.036 --> 01:26:09.032
the property that they're
sound, which means

01:26:09.492 --> 01:26:13.112
that if the premises of
the argument are all

01:26:13.212 --> 01:26:16.352
true in a structure and
you have a proof to get a

01:26:16.372 --> 01:26:20.192
conclusion, then the conclusion is
also true in that structure. So

01:26:20.232 --> 01:26:26.512
that's what it means to be sound.
Proofs preserve truth. They're truth-

01:26:26.612 --> 01:26:33.812
preserving arguments. Okay?
But also the proof systems are

01:26:33.852 --> 01:26:37.172
also generally complete. They're both
sound and complete, and complete

01:26:37.232 --> 01:26:44.652
means that whenever a statement is a
consequence, a logical consequence of some

01:26:44.772 --> 01:26:48.612
other statements, which means that
whenever the assumptions are true, then

01:26:48.652 --> 01:26:51.452
then the consequence is
also true in the structure.

01:26:52.632 --> 01:26:55.412
So whenever you have a logical
consequence, then there is a proof of

01:26:55.452 --> 01:26:59.292
it. Okay? And the proof systems generally

01:26:59.312 --> 01:27:03.292
have both of those properties; they're sound and
complete. There's a third property a lot of logicians

01:27:03.352 --> 01:27:04.042
talk about

01:27:04.872 --> 01:27:08.652
sound and complete, sound and complete this, sound
and complete that. But actually, there's a hidden

01:27:08.752 --> 01:27:13.572
third adjective that they should always be
talking about in any such case, which is

01:27:13.652 --> 01:27:17.452
that you should be able
to recognize whether or

01:27:17.512 --> 01:27:21.402
whether or not something is a proof or
not. So there's a computable aspect

01:27:22.012 --> 01:27:25.952
to the proof systems. We want to be able
to recognize whether something is a proof.

01:27:25.992 --> 01:27:29.932
It should be computably decidable whether
a given sequence of statements is a proof

01:27:29.992 --> 01:27:33.472
or not. So we don't want
a proof system in which

01:27:33.952 --> 01:27:37.812
someone claims to have a proof, but
we can't check that fact, whether

01:27:37.872 --> 01:27:43.712
it's a proof or not. We want to
be able to correctly adjudicate

01:27:43.852 --> 01:27:46.732
all claims to having a proof.

01:27:46.812 --> 01:27:50.712
- Yeah. A mathematician comes to mind that
said he has a proof, but the margins are

01:27:50.752 --> 01:27:51.512
too small

01:27:51.552 --> 01:27:51.642
- That's right.

01:27:51.642 --> 01:27:52.072
- to continue.

01:27:52.092 --> 01:27:53.592
- Exactly. So

01:27:53.632 --> 01:27:54.992
- So that doesn't count as a proof.

01:27:55.002 --> 01:27:58.992
- Yeah. So generally, all the classical
proof systems that are used are sound

01:27:59.002 --> 01:28:02.892
and complete and also computably decidable
in the sense that we can decide whether

01:28:02.952 --> 01:28:04.572
something is a proof or not.

01:28:04.612 --> 01:28:08.452
- So what is, again, the tension
between truth and proof?

01:28:08.472 --> 01:28:12.452
Which is more powerful, and
how do the two interplay

01:28:12.572 --> 01:28:15.502
with the contradictions
that we've been discussing?

01:28:15.512 --> 01:28:19.392
- Right. So the incompleteness
theorem is the question whether we

01:28:19.432 --> 01:28:21.932
could, say, write down a theory

01:28:22.912 --> 01:28:26.832
for arithmetic. Say, for the standard model
of arithmetic where we have the natural

01:28:26.892 --> 01:28:30.652
numbers and plus and times and zero,
one, and less than, and so on.

01:28:30.752 --> 01:28:34.542
In that formal language, we can
express an enormous number of

01:28:34.592 --> 01:28:37.942
statements about the nature not
only of arithmetic, but actually by

01:28:38.332 --> 01:28:41.732
various coding methods, we can
express essentially all of finite

01:28:41.792 --> 01:28:45.682
mathematics in that structure.
So the question would be, can

01:28:45.772 --> 01:28:49.572
we write down a computable list
of axioms that will answer

01:28:49.672 --> 01:28:53.332
all those questions by proof?
In other words, we want to

01:28:53.392 --> 01:28:59.932
have a complete theory, a theory of
arithmetic that proves all and only the true

01:29:00.072 --> 01:29:03.972
statements. That would be the goal. Hilbert
would love that. I mean, that would

01:29:04.012 --> 01:29:07.692
be supportive of Hilbert's
program to have such a complete

01:29:07.732 --> 01:29:11.701
theory of arithmetic, and
Godel proved that this is

01:29:11.752 --> 01:29:15.662
impossible. You cannot write down a
computable list of axioms that is complete

01:29:15.732 --> 01:29:19.432
in that sense. There will always
be statements... If the theory is

01:29:19.472 --> 01:29:23.302
consistent, there will always be statements
that you cannot prove and you cannot

01:29:23.332 --> 01:29:26.512
refute. So they are
independent of that theory.

01:29:26.532 --> 01:29:30.772
- How traumatic is that, that there are statements
that are independent from the theory?

01:29:30.832 --> 01:29:36.042
- I mean, my view is that this isn't
traumatic at all. This is rather

01:29:38.572 --> 01:29:42.292
completely eye-opening in terms of our

01:29:42.352 --> 01:29:49.432
understanding of the nature of
mathematical reality. I mean, we're not...

01:29:49.512 --> 01:29:53.292
We understand this profound fact about our

01:29:53.352 --> 01:29:57.332
situation with regard
to mathematical truth.

01:29:57.372 --> 01:30:01.232
The incompleteness theorem tells us,
look, we just can't write down a list of

01:30:01.312 --> 01:30:05.172
axioms that is going to be consistent and
it's going to answer all the questions.

01:30:05.232 --> 01:30:09.032
It's impossible. And so I
don't think of it as trauma.

01:30:09.092 --> 01:30:12.962
I just think, look, this is the nature of
mathematical reality and it's good that

01:30:12.992 --> 01:30:16.882
we know it, and so now we need to
move on from that. And, you know,

01:30:16.912 --> 01:30:19.201
do what we can in light of that.

01:30:19.252 --> 01:30:22.892
- Is it fair to say that in
general it means if I give you a

01:30:22.972 --> 01:30:31.292
statement, you can't know if your axiomatic
system would be able to prove it?

01:30:31.302 --> 01:30:35.172
- That's right. In general, you
cannot. The provability problem,

01:30:35.212 --> 01:30:38.852
we can formulate it as a decision
problem. Given a theory and given a

01:30:38.932 --> 01:30:42.902
statement, is that statement a
consequence of that theory? Yeah.

01:30:42.932 --> 01:30:46.852
This is one of the most famous decision
problems. In fact, the very first one,

01:30:46.952 --> 01:30:49.732
because it's equivalent
to the Hilbert-Ackermann

01:30:49.832 --> 01:30:53.612
Entscheidungsproblem, which is
also appearing in the title of

01:30:53.832 --> 01:31:01.052
Turing's 1936 paper that was so important
for computability theory. So, it's a

01:31:01.172 --> 01:31:05.012
formulation of the Entscheidungsproblem.
Does a given theory

01:31:05.992 --> 01:31:09.912
have a given statement as a logical
consequence? Which, because

01:31:09.972 --> 01:31:13.792
of Gödel's completeness theorem, not his
incompleteness theorem, but his earlier

01:31:13.832 --> 01:31:17.712
completeness theorem, Gödel had proved
that the proof systems that they

01:31:17.772 --> 01:31:21.692
studied did have this completeness
property that I mentioned. So provability

01:31:21.732 --> 01:31:25.652
is the same as logical consequence.
And this is an undecidable decision

01:31:25.732 --> 01:31:30.652
problem. Turing proved and we now know
it's equivalent to the Halting Problem.

01:31:30.732 --> 01:31:34.552
- Can you describe the Halting Problem?
Because it's a thing that shows up in a

01:31:34.612 --> 01:31:38.342
very useful and, again, traumatic
way through a lot of computer

01:31:38.432 --> 01:31:39.732
science, through a lot of mathematics.

01:31:39.972 --> 01:31:43.492
- Yeah. The Halting Problem
is expressing a fundamental

01:31:43.592 --> 01:31:46.972
property of computational processes. So,

01:31:47.532 --> 01:31:51.512
given a program, or maybe we think of it
as a program together with its input,

01:31:51.552 --> 01:31:54.352
but let me just call it a program. So
given a program, we could run that

01:31:54.392 --> 01:31:58.092
program, but I want to
pose it as a decision

01:31:58.152 --> 01:32:01.912
problem. Will this
program ever complete its

01:32:01.972 --> 01:32:05.892
task? Will it ever halt? And the
Halting Problem is the question, given

01:32:05.992 --> 01:32:13.400
a program, will it halt? Yes
or no? And, of course, for

01:32:13.420 --> 01:32:16.780
any one instance, the answer's either
yes or no. That's not what we're talking

01:32:16.800 --> 01:32:20.680
about. We're talking about whether
there's a computable procedure to answer

01:32:20.980 --> 01:32:24.880
all instances of this question.
So, it's a decision problem is

01:32:24.940 --> 01:32:28.520
given as a scheme of instances for all
possible programs that you could ask

01:32:28.580 --> 01:32:32.430
about. What I want to know is, is there
a computable procedure that will answer

01:32:32.460 --> 01:32:33.320
those questions?

01:32:34.200 --> 01:32:37.580
And it turns out the answer's no.
The Halting Problem is computably

01:32:37.620 --> 01:32:41.260
undecidable. There is no computable
procedure that will correctly

01:32:41.360 --> 01:32:48.290
answer all instances of whether a given
program will halt. And of course, we can

01:32:48.320 --> 01:32:51.070
get half the answers in the sense that

01:32:52.760 --> 01:32:56.380
you give me a program and you say,
"Will this halt?" And I could take that

01:32:56.400 --> 01:32:59.200
program and I could run it.

01:32:59.240 --> 01:33:02.680
And I could keep running it,
and maybe in a week, it would

01:33:02.720 --> 01:33:05.820
halt. And at that time,
I could say, "Yes, it

01:33:05.860 --> 01:33:11.680
halted." So I can get the yes answers
correctly for halting, all the yes answers.

01:33:13.480 --> 01:33:14.520
But the problem is

01:33:17.020 --> 01:33:20.940
if it didn't halt yet, like maybe I
waited, you know, a thousand years

01:33:21.360 --> 01:33:22.660
and it still hasn't halted,

01:33:23.800 --> 01:33:27.520
I don't seem entitled to say, "No,
it's not going to halt." Yet, because

01:33:27.560 --> 01:33:31.440
maybe in a thousand and one years,
it'll halt. And so at no point can I

01:33:31.540 --> 01:33:34.940
seem to say, "No." In order to
say, "No, it won't ever halt," it

01:33:35.620 --> 01:33:39.080
seems like I would have to really
understand how the program

01:33:39.220 --> 01:33:40.960
worked and what it was doing.

01:33:41.980 --> 01:33:45.840
So giving the "yes" answers was sort of trivial.
You didn't have to understand it. You just needed

01:33:45.880 --> 01:33:49.860
to run it, which is a kind of rote
task. But to give the "no" answers,

01:33:49.920 --> 01:33:53.520
you need to have a kind of deep insight into
the nature of the program and what it's

01:33:53.580 --> 01:33:58.800
doing in such a way that you would understand
it and be able to see, "Oh, no, I can

01:33:58.940 --> 01:34:02.660
see this program is never gonna halt."
Because, you know, it's a much more

01:34:02.680 --> 01:34:06.560
difficult task to say, "No, it won't
halt," than it is to say, "Yes,

01:34:06.640 --> 01:34:10.180
it halted because I ran it
and it halted." And it turns

01:34:10.200 --> 01:34:14.060
out to be impossible to have a
computable procedure that gives

01:34:14.100 --> 01:34:18.060
the "no" answers, you know? And the argument
is not very difficult. Should we do it?

01:34:18.100 --> 01:34:19.189
- Yes, let's do it.

01:34:19.240 --> 01:34:23.160
- Okay. Suppose toward contradiction.
I mean, all these proofs are by

01:34:23.200 --> 01:34:27.040
contradiction, and this argument is going
to be a diagonal argument in the same

01:34:27.160 --> 01:34:30.640
style as the Russell argument
and the Cantor argument and

01:34:30.700 --> 01:34:34.420
Gödel's argument that we haven't
talked about yet. So many diagonal

01:34:34.480 --> 01:34:36.360
arguments come in. So

01:34:37.440 --> 01:34:41.280
suppose towards contradiction that we had a
procedure for determining whether a given program

01:34:41.300 --> 01:34:48.860
halted on a given input. Now, let me
describe. I'm gonna use that procedure

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:52.820
as a subroutine in the
following process. And

01:34:52.860 --> 01:34:56.920
my process, let's call it Q,
process Q, and it takes as input

01:34:57.900 --> 01:35:04.460
a program P, okay? And the first thing
it does is it asks that subroutine,

01:35:04.480 --> 01:35:08.430
"Hey, would P halt if I ran it on

01:35:08.560 --> 01:35:14.680
P itself?" Okay, that's the diagonal part
because we're applying P to P, right?

01:35:14.720 --> 01:35:18.400
Okay, so I'm describing program
Q, and program Q takes as input

01:35:18.460 --> 01:35:22.060
P, which is itself a program. And
the first thing it does is it asks

01:35:22.760 --> 01:35:25.860
the halting subroutine
program, "Would P halt on

01:35:25.980 --> 01:35:29.960
P?" And if the answer comes
back from the subroutine,

01:35:29.980 --> 01:35:33.940
"Yeah, that would halt,"
then what I do in program Q

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:37.689
is I immediately jump into
an infinite loop. So I don't

01:35:37.700 --> 01:35:41.340
halt. If P halts on P, I don't halt.

01:35:41.360 --> 01:35:45.280
But if the answer came back, "No,
P is never gonna halt on P," then

01:35:45.400 --> 01:35:53.240
I halt immediately. Okay, so and
that's it. I've described what Q does.

01:35:53.280 --> 01:36:00.580
And the thing about Q is that Q's
behavior on P was the opposite of P's

01:36:00.640 --> 01:36:08.300
behavior on P. I mean, that's how we
designed Q specifically so that Q on P

01:36:09.300 --> 01:36:13.100
had the opposite behavior
as P on P. Okay, so

01:36:13.160 --> 01:36:16.830
now, of course, what do we
do? Well, the same thing that

01:36:16.940 --> 01:36:23.620
Russell did and so forth, and Cantor,
we ask, "Well, what would Q do on

01:36:23.960 --> 01:36:27.640
Q?" And because of this opposite behavior,

01:36:28.000 --> 01:36:31.539
Q would halt on Q if and
only if Q does not halt on

01:36:31.760 --> 01:36:35.560
Q, which is a contradiction, because Q
has to have the opposite behavior on

01:36:35.620 --> 01:36:38.040
Q than Q does, but that's
just contradictory.

01:36:38.100 --> 01:36:39.340
- What a beautiful proof. Simple.

01:36:39.380 --> 01:36:43.040
- It's absolutely beautiful. Yeah,
I agree. And it's following the

01:36:43.140 --> 01:36:47.100
same logic of Russell and
Cantor. I mean, going back to

01:36:47.160 --> 01:36:50.760
Cantor basically, because Russell
is also quoting Cantor in

01:36:50.800 --> 01:36:54.480
Cantor basically, because Russell is also quoting
Cantor in his letter to Frege. So, therefore, the

01:36:54.520 --> 01:36:58.340
conclusion is that the halting
problem is not computably

01:36:58.380 --> 01:37:02.280
decidable. And now we can
immediately prove Godel's

01:37:02.300 --> 01:37:06.150
decidable. And now we can immediately prove Gödel's theorem using this,
actually. It's an immediate consequence. So why don't we just do that?

01:37:06.260 --> 01:37:07.980
I view this as the simplest proof

01:37:08.820 --> 01:37:12.340
I view this as the simplest proof of Gödel's
theorem. You don't need the Gödel sentence to

01:37:12.380 --> 01:37:18.520
prove Gödel's theorem. You can do it
with the halting problem. So, suppose

01:37:19.440 --> 01:37:23.420
that we could write down a
computable axiomatization of all

01:37:23.500 --> 01:37:29.280
that we could write down a computable axiomatization of all of
the true facts of elementary mathematics, meaning arithmetic

01:37:29.360 --> 01:37:33.200
and finite combinatorial
things such as Turing

01:37:33.240 --> 01:37:36.960
and finite combinatorial things such as Turing
machine computations and so on. So in fact, all those

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:40.600
finite combinatorial processes are
formalizable inside arithmetic with the

01:37:40.660 --> 01:37:44.540
finite combinatorial processes are formalizable inside arithmetic
with the standard arithmetization coding process. But let

01:37:44.560 --> 01:37:48.100
me just be a little bit informal and say
suppose we could write down a complete

01:37:48.160 --> 01:37:50.800
me just be a little bit informal and say, suppose we could
write down a complete theory of elementary finite mathematics.

01:37:52.540 --> 01:37:55.190
So we have a, an
axiomatization of that theory.

01:37:56.680 --> 01:37:59.900
So we have an axiomatization of that theory. Then
we could produce all possible theorems from those

01:38:00.000 --> 01:38:03.560
axioms in the way that I
was describing earlier with

01:38:03.580 --> 01:38:07.370
axioms in the way that I was describing earlier with Hilbert's
program. I mean, if we had a complete theory of elementary

01:38:07.420 --> 01:38:11.380
mathematics, we could construct a
theorem enumeration machine that

01:38:11.440 --> 01:38:14.980
mathematics, we could construct a theorem enumeration machine
that produced all the theorems and only the theorems from that

01:38:15.020 --> 01:38:22.912
theory.... so now, I have this theorem
enumeration device on my desk, and I announce

01:38:22.992 --> 01:38:26.832
theory. So now I have this theorem enumeration device on my desk, and I announce
that I'm open for business to solve the halting problem. So you give me a program

01:38:26.972 --> 01:38:29.072
and input that you wanna
run that program on,

01:38:29.892 --> 01:38:33.692
and input that you want to run that program on, and I'm going to
answer the halting problem. And the way I'm going to do it is I'm just

01:38:33.732 --> 01:38:34.872
gonna wait for the

01:38:35.872 --> 01:38:39.712
going to wait for the statement coming out of the
theorem enumeration device that asserts either that

01:38:39.812 --> 01:38:43.612
P does halt on that input or I wait
for the statement that P does not

01:38:43.652 --> 01:38:47.322
P does halt on that input or I wait for the statement that P does not
halt on that input. But one of them's going to happen because it was a

01:38:47.352 --> 01:38:50.782
complete theory that was enumerating
all the true statements of elementary

01:38:50.892 --> 01:38:54.852
complete theory that was enumerating all the true statements of elementary
mathematics. So therefore, if I had such a system, I could solve the halting

01:38:54.872 --> 01:38:58.272
problem, but we already proved that
you cannot solve the halting problem,

01:38:58.872 --> 01:39:02.252
problem, but we already proved that you cannot solve the halting
problem, so therefore you cannot have such a complete theory of

01:39:02.272 --> 01:39:04.652
arithmetic. So that
proves Gödel's theorem.

01:39:05.432 --> 01:39:09.162
- Maybe to take a little bit of a tangent, can you speak... You've
written a wonderful book about proofs and the art of mathematics.

01:39:09.232 --> 01:39:13.052
So what can you say about proving stuff
in mathematics? What is the process of

01:39:13.152 --> 01:39:17.072
say about proving stuff in
mathematics? What is the process of

01:39:17.112 --> 01:39:20.862
proof? What are the tools? What is
the art? What is the science of

01:39:20.892 --> 01:39:22.652
proving things in mathematics?

01:39:22.692 --> 01:39:26.592
- proving things in mathematics? So this is
something that I find so wonderful to teach young

01:39:26.772 --> 01:39:30.632
mathematicians who are learning
how to become mathematicians and

01:39:30.772 --> 01:39:34.692
mathematicians who are learning how to become mathematicians and
learning about proof, and I wrote that book when I was teaching such a

01:39:34.732 --> 01:39:37.172
proofwriting class in New York.

01:39:37.212 --> 01:39:41.092
proofwriting class in New York. So many universities have
such a course, the proofreading course, which is usually

01:39:41.172 --> 01:39:45.052
taken by students who have
learned some mathematics.

01:39:45.112 --> 01:39:48.532
taken by students who have learned some mathematics. Usually, they've
completed maybe the calculus sequence and are making the kind of

01:39:48.572 --> 01:39:52.472
transition to higher mathematics,
which tends to involve

01:39:52.532 --> 01:39:55.462
much more proof, and it's a kind
of challenging step for them.

01:39:56.492 --> 01:40:00.392
Many math departments have this kind
of course on proofwriting where the

01:40:00.452 --> 01:40:04.272
students would get exposed to
how to write proofs. I wasn't

01:40:04.312 --> 01:40:08.232
happy with most of the other
books that exist for those

01:40:08.312 --> 01:40:15.672
kind of courses, and the reason was
that they were so often so dull because

01:40:15.972 --> 01:40:19.132
they would concentrate on, like, these-

01:40:20.192 --> 01:40:23.832
totally uninteresting parts
of what it's like to write a

01:40:23.852 --> 01:40:25.572
proof, these kind of mechanistic

01:40:26.632 --> 01:40:30.532
procedures about how to write a proof.
You know, if you're going to prove an

01:40:30.612 --> 01:40:34.452
implication, then you assume the hypothesis
and argue for the conclusion, and so on.

01:40:34.512 --> 01:40:38.292
And all of that is true and fine and that's
good to know, except if that's all that you're

01:40:38.352 --> 01:40:42.172
saying about the nature of proof,
then I don't think you're really

01:40:42.212 --> 01:40:46.052
learning very much. So I felt
that it was possible to have a

01:40:46.092 --> 01:40:49.652
much better kind of book,
one that was much more

01:40:49.732 --> 01:40:53.532
interesting and that had
interesting theorems in

01:40:53.612 --> 01:40:57.592
it that still admitted of
elementary proof. So I wrote this

01:40:57.732 --> 01:41:01.532
book and tried to fill it with all of the

01:41:01.612 --> 01:41:05.352
compelling mathematical
statements with very elementary

01:41:05.412 --> 01:41:09.152
proofs that exhibited lots
of different proof styles in

01:41:09.212 --> 01:41:12.912
it. And so, I found that the
students appreciated it a lot.

01:41:12.992 --> 01:41:16.572
- We should say, we dedicate the
book to my students, may all their

01:41:16.692 --> 01:41:20.592
theorems be true, proved by elegant
arguments that flow effortlessly from

01:41:20.632 --> 01:41:26.412
hypothesis to conclusion while revealing
fantastical mathematical beauty.

01:41:27.532 --> 01:41:31.812
Are there some interesting
proofs that maybe illustrate,

01:41:33.292 --> 01:41:37.232
for people outside of mathematics or
for people who just take math classes-

01:41:37.472 --> 01:41:37.502
- Right

01:41:37.502 --> 01:41:39.442
- ...in high school and so on?

01:41:39.452 --> 01:41:41.602
- Yeah, let's do a proof.
There's one in the book.

01:41:41.632 --> 01:41:44.892
We can talk about it. I think
it's a nice problem. It's in

01:41:44.972 --> 01:41:48.332
the discrete math, yeah,
the 5.1, that one,

01:41:48.912 --> 01:41:52.812
more pointed at than pointing.
Okay. So this is the

01:41:52.872 --> 01:41:55.932
following problem. Suppose
you're gathered with some

01:41:55.992 --> 01:41:59.792
friends, you know, in a
circle, and you can point

01:41:59.852 --> 01:42:02.762
at each other however you want,
or yourself, whatever, it doesn't

01:42:02.792 --> 01:42:06.672
matter, and you can point at more than one
person, you know, use all your fingers or

01:42:06.712 --> 01:42:10.612
your feet or whatever you want. So maybe
you point at three of your friends or

01:42:10.672 --> 01:42:14.512
something and they point at two or three of
their friends or whatever, and one person

01:42:14.552 --> 01:42:18.492
is pointing at 10 people and somebody isn't
pointing at anybody maybe, or and various

01:42:18.512 --> 01:42:24.692
people are pointed at also, right? So the
question is, could we arrange a pattern of

01:42:24.752 --> 01:42:28.972
pointing so that everyone
was more pointed at

01:42:30.072 --> 01:42:33.832
than they are pointing at
others? So in other words, maybe

01:42:33.871 --> 01:42:37.652
there's seven people pointing at me, but
I'm only pointing at five people and

01:42:37.692 --> 01:42:41.472
maybe there's, you know,
20 people pointing at you,

01:42:41.512 --> 01:42:45.492
but you're only pointing at 15 people or
something like that, right? So I want to

01:42:45.532 --> 01:42:48.222
know. There's a similar
question on Twitter.

01:42:49.592 --> 01:42:53.512
For a group of people on
Twitter, could you arrange

01:42:54.152 --> 01:43:00.072
that everyone has more followers than
following? Yeah, it's the same question.

01:43:00.092 --> 01:43:02.492
Mathematically, it's identical.

01:43:02.532 --> 01:43:06.312
Although, I don't know, it's not identical,
because I said you could point at yourself,

01:43:06.372 --> 01:43:09.222
and I think that's not...
Can you follow yourself?

01:43:09.232 --> 01:43:10.082
- No, I don't think so, no.

01:43:10.132 --> 01:43:13.832
- I don't think you can.
Okay. So can you arrange it

01:43:13.912 --> 01:43:17.802
so that everyone is more pointed
at than pointing? And in my book,

01:43:17.852 --> 01:43:21.772
I give a couple of different proofs of
this. I think I give an induction proof

01:43:21.792 --> 01:43:25.582
and then there's another proof. I think
there's three different proofs in there.

01:43:25.652 --> 01:43:27.622
But why don't we just talk
about my favorite proof?

01:43:28.592 --> 01:43:32.392
Suppose it were possible to arrange that
we're all more pointed at than pointing,

01:43:32.472 --> 01:43:35.792
okay? Now what we're going
to do, we're going to agree,

01:43:36.632 --> 01:43:40.892
we're going to give a dollar to
everyone that we're pointing at.

01:43:40.972 --> 01:43:44.992
Okay? And so what happens?
Everybody made money,

01:43:46.372 --> 01:43:50.082
because I was pointed at by more
people than I'm pointing, so I got

01:43:50.082 --> 01:43:54.032
$10, but I only paid out
$7. And similarly, you

01:43:54.072 --> 01:43:57.912
got paid $20, but you
only paid out $15. So,

01:43:57.932 --> 01:44:01.412
if everyone is more pointed at than
pointing, then everyone makes money.

01:44:01.732 --> 01:44:05.622
But it's obviously impossible for us to
make money as a group by just trading

01:44:05.652 --> 01:44:07.912
money with ourselves.

01:44:07.952 --> 01:44:12.252
And therefore, it can't be possible that
we're all more pointed at than pointing.

01:44:13.112 --> 01:44:16.812
And this proof illustrates something.
It's one of my habits that I

01:44:16.832 --> 01:44:21.752
suggest in the book: to anthropomorphize
your mathematical ideas.

01:44:22.212 --> 01:44:26.062
You should imagine that
the mathematical objects

01:44:26.152 --> 01:44:28.892
that are playing a role
in your question are

01:44:29.032 --> 01:44:32.884
people, or active, somehow, animals, or

01:44:32.943 --> 01:44:36.824
something that maybe have a
will and a goal and so on.

01:44:36.864 --> 01:44:40.764
This is this process
of anthropomorphizing.

01:44:40.844 --> 01:44:44.824
And it often makes the problems
easier to understand because we all

01:44:44.864 --> 01:44:48.584
are familiar with the fact that
it's difficult to make money,

01:44:48.624 --> 01:44:52.174
and the proof is totally convincing
because of our knowledge that

01:44:52.244 --> 01:44:55.664
we can't make money as a group by trading

01:44:56.603 --> 01:45:01.844
dollars between us, you know, without
any new money coming into the group.

01:45:01.853 --> 01:45:04.364
But that by itself is actually a difficult

01:45:04.404 --> 01:45:07.884
mathematical claim. I
mean, if someone had to

01:45:07.964 --> 01:45:11.464
prove that you can't make
money by trading within a

01:45:11.504 --> 01:45:15.224
group, you know, it can't be
that everyone in the group

01:45:15.304 --> 01:45:19.264
makes money just by shifting money around
in the group. Maybe you think that's

01:45:19.344 --> 01:45:22.794
obvious, and it is obvious if you think
about money. But if you had asked the

01:45:22.904 --> 01:45:26.624
question, you know, about mathematical
functions of a certain kind and so on,

01:45:26.664 --> 01:45:30.464
then maybe it wouldn't be as clear as
it is when you're talking about this

01:45:30.523 --> 01:45:32.384
money thing, because of

01:45:33.704 --> 01:45:37.664
we can build on our human experience
about the difficulty of getting

01:45:37.704 --> 01:45:41.494
money and, you know, or other resources. It
doesn't have to be money, it could be candy,

01:45:41.523 --> 01:45:45.384
whatever. You know, we just
know that you can't easily get

01:45:45.443 --> 01:45:48.804
more things in that kind just
by trading within a group.

01:45:48.813 --> 01:45:52.483
- And we should say that sometimes
the power of proof is such that the

01:45:52.544 --> 01:45:56.434
non-obvious can be shown, and then
over time that becomes obvious.

01:45:56.464 --> 01:45:58.014
So in the context of money,

01:45:58.014 --> 01:46:01.244
or social systems, there's a bunch
of things that are non-obvious.

01:46:01.504 --> 01:46:05.464
And the whole point is
that proof can guide us

01:46:05.523 --> 01:46:09.364
to the truth, to the accurate description

01:46:09.424 --> 01:46:12.964
of reality. We just proved
a property of money.

01:46:14.704 --> 01:46:18.544
- It's interesting to think about, well,
