mathematical objects or
abstract objects that was more

01:48:35.924 --> 01:48:41.384
like, you know, the existence of
tables and chairs and rocks and so on.

01:48:42.364 --> 01:48:49.443
And so there seems to be this desire
to reduce mathematical existence to

01:48:49.624 --> 01:48:53.264
something, you know, that we can
experience physically in the real

01:48:53.304 --> 01:48:58.204
world. But my attitude about this attempt

01:49:00.184 --> 01:49:04.004
is that it's very
backward, I think, because

01:49:06.664 --> 01:49:10.464
I don't think we have such a clear
understanding of the nature of

01:49:10.563 --> 01:49:14.523
physical objects, actually. I
mean, we all have experience

01:49:14.784 --> 01:49:18.704
about existing in the physical
world, as we must, because we do

01:49:18.784 --> 01:49:22.724
exist in the physical world,
but I don't know of any

01:49:24.004 --> 01:49:27.164
satisfactory account of
what it means to exist

01:49:27.443 --> 01:49:34.603
physically. I mean, if I ask you,
say, "Imagine a certain kind of

01:49:35.483 --> 01:49:39.404
steam locomotive," you know, and
I describe the engineering of

01:49:39.483 --> 01:49:44.334
it and the weight of it and the
nature of the gear linkages and

01:49:45.224 --> 01:49:49.023
you know, and I show you schematic
drawings of the whole design and so

01:49:49.144 --> 01:49:52.844
on and, you know, we talk in
detail about every single detailed

01:49:52.983 --> 01:49:56.404
aspect of this steam
locomotive. But then suppose

01:49:56.724 --> 01:50:00.523
after all that conversation, I
say, "Okay, now I would like

01:50:00.864 --> 01:50:04.603
you to tell me what would it mean for
it to exist physically, I mean, as

01:50:04.624 --> 01:50:07.764
opposed to just being an
imaginary steam locomotive?" Then

01:50:08.204 --> 01:50:12.184
what, what could you
possibly say about it? I

01:50:12.224 --> 01:50:16.063
mean, except by saying, "Oh, I just mean that it exists
in the physical world." But what does that mean?

01:50:16.084 --> 01:50:19.904
That's the question, right? It's not an
answer to the question. That is the question.

01:50:20.023 --> 01:50:23.964
So I don't think that there's
anything sensible that

01:50:23.983 --> 01:50:27.504
we can say about the nature of
physical existence. It is a profound

01:50:27.764 --> 01:50:31.664
mystery. In fact, it becomes
more and more mysterious

01:50:31.724 --> 01:50:35.443
the more physics we know.
I mean, back in, say,

01:50:35.483 --> 01:50:39.184
Newtonian physics, one had a picture
of the nature of physical objects

01:50:39.224 --> 01:50:43.124
as, you know, little billiard balls or something,
or maybe they're infinitely divisible or something

01:50:43.164 --> 01:50:47.019
like that. Okay, but then this
picture is upset with the

01:50:47.060 --> 01:50:51.030
atomic theory of matter. But
then that picture's upset

01:50:51.080 --> 01:50:54.940
when we realize that the atoms actually
can be split and consist of electrons and

01:50:55.000 --> 01:50:58.200
protons and neutrons and so on.
But then that picture's upset

01:50:58.820 --> 01:51:02.780
when we realize that those things themselves are
built out of quarks and leptons and so on, and

01:51:02.820 --> 01:51:06.480
who knows what's coming. Furthermore,
all of those things, the nature of their

01:51:06.519 --> 01:51:10.200
existence is actually as wave functions in

01:51:10.300 --> 01:51:14.290
you know, some cloud of probability
and so on. So it just becomes

01:51:14.340 --> 01:51:18.200
more and more and more mysterious
the more we learn, and not at all

01:51:18.300 --> 01:51:22.120
clarifying. So the nature
of what it means to

01:51:22.200 --> 01:51:25.480
say that, you know, there's an apple on my

01:51:25.540 --> 01:51:28.940
desk, and to give an account of
what that physical existence

01:51:29.240 --> 01:51:33.140
really is at bottom, I think,
is totally absent. Whereas we

01:51:33.160 --> 01:51:36.420
do seem to have a much more

01:51:36.540 --> 01:51:40.420
satisfactory account of the nature
of abstract existence. I mean, I

01:51:40.460 --> 01:51:44.340
can talk about the nature of the
empty set. You know, this is the

01:51:44.380 --> 01:51:48.260
predicate which is never true or
something like that. I can talk

01:51:48.340 --> 01:51:51.900
about those kind of
logical properties or the

01:51:51.960 --> 01:51:55.740
singleton of the empty set and so on. I mean,
of course, it's very difficult if you go very

01:51:56.360 --> 01:52:00.340
far with it, but the point is that it doesn't
get more and more mysterious. The more that you

01:52:00.400 --> 01:52:07.060
say, it becomes only more and more
clear. So it seems to me that,

01:52:07.760 --> 01:52:11.220
we don't really have any
understanding of what the

01:52:11.440 --> 01:52:15.110
physical world is as opposed to
the abstract world, and it's the

01:52:15.200 --> 01:52:19.540
abstract world where
existence is much more clear.

01:52:19.620 --> 01:52:20.860
- It is very true

01:52:21.720 --> 01:52:25.519
that we don't know anything about the soda bottle
or the steam locomotive just because we can

01:52:25.540 --> 01:52:29.160
poke at it. Again, we anthropomorphize,
and that actually gets us into

01:52:29.220 --> 01:52:33.180
trouble sometimes because I'm not
feeling the quantum mechanics when

01:52:33.220 --> 01:52:34.140
I'm touching it.

01:52:34.180 --> 01:52:34.560
- That's right.

01:52:34.580 --> 01:52:39.940
- And therefore, it's easy to forget
and feel like this is real and

01:52:41.019 --> 01:52:44.600
mathematical objects are not, but
you're making the opposite argument.

01:52:44.620 --> 01:52:48.570
When you draw a distinction between
numerals and numbers, which numerals are

01:52:48.600 --> 01:52:51.430
the representation of the
number on the page, and so on,

01:52:52.260 --> 01:52:57.280
but could you say that a number
is real? Do numbers exist?

01:52:57.760 --> 01:53:01.430
- I happen to think so. I mean,
I'm on the side of realism in

01:53:01.460 --> 01:53:05.060
mathematics, and I think that these
abstract objects do have a real

01:53:05.100 --> 01:53:10.149
existence in a way that we can give an account
of, in a way I just tried to describe.

01:53:10.180 --> 01:53:14.269
- So, you would describe it as the size
of a set with four elements in it?

01:53:14.280 --> 01:53:18.120
- Well, there are different ways to understand the
nature of four. I mean, actually, this gets into

01:53:18.180 --> 01:53:24.260
the question of structuralism, which is
maybe a good place to talk about it.

01:53:24.300 --> 01:53:25.340
- What is structuralism?

01:53:25.519 --> 01:53:29.500
- Structuralism is a philosophical
position in mathematics,

01:53:29.519 --> 01:53:33.180
or the philosophy of mathematics,
by which one emphasizes that what's

01:53:33.220 --> 01:53:37.100
important about mathematical objects
is not what they're made out of or

01:53:37.120 --> 01:53:40.860
what their substance or essence is,
but rather how they function in a

01:53:40.900 --> 01:53:44.180
mathematical structure.
And so, what I call the

01:53:44.440 --> 01:53:48.360
structuralist attitude in
mathematics is that we should

01:53:48.420 --> 01:53:52.340
only care about our
mathematical structures up

01:53:52.380 --> 01:53:56.240
to isomorphism. If I have a mathematical
structure of a certain kind,

01:53:56.380 --> 01:54:00.240
and I make an exact copy of it
using different individuals

01:54:00.340 --> 01:54:02.980
to form the elements of that structure,

01:54:03.840 --> 01:54:07.779
then the isomorphic copy is just as
good mathematically, and there's no

01:54:07.960 --> 01:54:11.180
important mathematical
difference that would ever arise

01:54:11.260 --> 01:54:14.660
from working with this isomorphic
copy instead of the original

01:54:14.960 --> 01:54:18.640
structure. And so, therefore,
that's another way of saying

01:54:18.720 --> 01:54:22.589
that the substance of individuals,
you know, in a mathematical

01:54:22.680 --> 01:54:28.269
structure is irrelevant with regard
to any mathematical property of that

01:54:28.320 --> 01:54:37.660
structure. And so, to ask a question like,
"What is the number four really?" is an

01:54:37.740 --> 01:54:41.620
anti-structuralist thing
because, you know, if you have

01:54:41.660 --> 01:54:45.519
if you have a structure, say, the natural
numbers, you know, with all the numbers in it: 0,

01:54:45.660 --> 01:54:47.680
1, 2, 3, 4, and so on, then

01:54:48.620 --> 01:54:52.580
I could replace the number four
with something else, like, you

01:54:52.620 --> 01:54:54.620
know, this bottle of water

01:54:55.460 --> 01:54:59.280
could play the role of the number four
in that structure, and it would be

01:54:59.360 --> 01:55:03.180
isomorphic. And it wouldn't matter
at all for any mathematical

01:55:03.220 --> 01:55:07.110
purpose to use this alternative
mathematical system, you know?

01:55:07.160 --> 01:55:11.130
That's to say that we don't
care what the number four is

01:55:11.180 --> 01:55:15.059
really. That is irrelevant. The only
thing that matters is what are the

01:55:15.100 --> 01:55:18.900
properties of the number four in
a given mathematical system, you

01:55:18.940 --> 01:55:22.240
know, and recognizing that there
are other isomorphic copies of that

01:55:22.340 --> 01:55:26.280
system, and the properties of that
other system's number four are

01:55:26.320 --> 01:55:30.180
going to be identical to the
properties of this system's number

01:55:30.500 --> 01:55:34.220
four with regard to any question that's
important about the number four. But those

01:55:34.260 --> 01:55:38.200
questions won't be about
essence. So, in a sense,

01:55:38.280 --> 01:55:42.780
structuralism is an
anti-essential in mathematics.

01:55:42.820 --> 01:55:46.680
- So, is it fair to think of
numbers as a kind of pointer to

01:55:46.760 --> 01:55:48.520
a deep underlying structure?

01:55:48.559 --> 01:55:51.820
- Yeah, I think so, because I
guess part of the point of

01:55:51.860 --> 01:55:55.740
structuralism is that it doesn't
make sense to consider mathematical

01:55:56.120 --> 01:55:59.940
objects or individuals in isolation.

01:55:59.980 --> 01:56:03.860
What's interesting and important about
mathematical objects is how they interact with

01:56:03.880 --> 01:56:07.820
each other and how they behave in a
system, and so maybe one wants to

01:56:07.840 --> 01:56:11.300
think about the structural role that
the objects play, you know, in a larger

01:56:11.500 --> 01:56:15.300
system, a larger structure.
There's a famous question

01:56:15.340 --> 01:56:19.130
that Frege had asked actually when
he was looking into the nature of

01:56:19.200 --> 01:56:23.059
numbers, because in his logicist
program, right, he was trying to

01:56:23.080 --> 01:56:26.780
reduce all of mathematics
to logic. And in that

01:56:26.840 --> 01:56:30.720
process, he was referring
to the Cantor-Hume

01:56:30.780 --> 01:56:34.220
principle that, you know,
whenever two sets are

01:56:34.260 --> 01:56:37.460
equinumerous, then they have the same
number of elements, I mean, if and only

01:56:37.500 --> 01:56:41.370
if. And he founded his
theory of number on this

01:56:41.460 --> 01:56:45.340
principle, but he recognized
that there was something that

01:56:45.380 --> 01:56:49.059
dissatisfied him about that
situation, which is that the

01:56:49.100 --> 01:56:53.032
Cantor-Hume principle
does not seem to give

01:56:53.072 --> 01:56:56.672
you criteria for which things
are numbers. It only tells

01:56:56.752 --> 01:57:00.732
you a kind of identity criteria
for when two numbers are equal to

01:57:00.772 --> 01:57:04.532
each other. Well, two numbers are
equal just in case the sets of

01:57:04.592 --> 01:57:07.932
those sizes are equinumerous, so
that's the criteria for number

01:57:07.992 --> 01:57:10.972
identity. But it is not
a criteria for what is a

01:57:11.072 --> 01:57:14.792
number. And so this problem
has become known as the Julius

01:57:14.832 --> 01:57:19.612
Caesar problem because Frege said we
don't seem to have any way of telling

01:57:20.592 --> 01:57:24.132
from the Hume principle
whether Julius Caesar is a

01:57:24.172 --> 01:57:28.012
number or not. So he's asking
about the essence of number and

01:57:28.052 --> 01:57:35.192
whether... Of course, one has a sense that
he picked maybe what he was trying to

01:57:35.232 --> 01:57:36.942
present as a ridiculous example,

01:57:36.942 --> 01:57:40.562
because maybe you have the idea that
well, obviously Julius Caesar is not a

01:57:40.612 --> 01:57:43.872
number, and there's a lot of philosophical
writing that seems to take that line

01:57:43.972 --> 01:57:47.792
also, that obviously the answer
is that Julius Caesar is not a

01:57:47.832 --> 01:57:51.032
number. But the structuralists
disagree with that

01:57:51.172 --> 01:57:54.632
position. The structuralist attitude is,

01:57:54.652 --> 01:57:59.372
"Look, you give me a number system.
If Julius Caesar isn't a number, then

01:58:00.212 --> 01:58:04.172
I can just... let's take the number
17 out of that system and plug

01:58:04.252 --> 01:58:08.042
in Julius Caesar for that role, and
now I've got a new number system, and

01:58:08.092 --> 01:58:10.822
now Julius Caesar happens
to be the number 17."

01:58:10.822 --> 01:58:14.432
And that's totally fine,
you know. So the point of

01:58:14.492 --> 01:58:18.482
structuralism is is that the question of

01:58:18.512 --> 01:58:21.752
whether Julius Caesar is a
number or not is irrelevant to

01:58:21.772 --> 01:58:25.022
mathematics. It is irrelevant
because it is not about

01:58:25.192 --> 01:58:30.572
structure, it's about this essence
of the mathematical objects.

01:58:30.652 --> 01:58:35.492
So that's the structuralist
criticism of Frege's point.

01:58:35.532 --> 01:58:37.492
- You've kind of made the case that you can

01:58:38.332 --> 01:58:41.992
say more concrete things about the
existence of objects in mathematics

01:58:42.132 --> 01:58:46.772
than you can in our physical reality,
about which to us human brains,

01:58:47.872 --> 01:58:51.642
things are obvious or not.
So what's more real? The

01:58:51.712 --> 01:58:59.212
reality we see with our eyes or the reality
we can express in mathematical theorems?

01:58:59.272 --> 01:59:08.452
- I'm not quite sure. I mean, I live entirely
in the Platonic realm, and I don't

01:59:08.492 --> 01:59:13.852
really understand the physical universe
at all. So I don't have strong views.

01:59:13.861 --> 01:59:19.762
- Let's talk about the Platonic realm. Is it-
because you live there, is it real? Or-

01:59:19.812 --> 01:59:23.772
- Oh yeah, totally, yeah. This is the
realist position in mathematics is that

01:59:23.792 --> 01:59:27.592
abstract objects have a real existence.
And okay, what's meant by that

01:59:27.632 --> 01:59:32.752
is that there's some sense of existence in
which those objects can be regarded as real.

01:59:32.772 --> 01:59:36.112
- How should we think about that? How should we
try to visualize that? What does it mean to

01:59:36.192 --> 01:59:40.912
live amongst abstract objects?

01:59:41.292 --> 01:59:41.732
- Right.

01:59:41.741 --> 01:59:46.112
- Because life is finite. We're
all afraid of death. We f-

01:59:46.932 --> 01:59:51.252
fall in love with other physical
manifestations of objects.

01:59:52.932 --> 01:59:56.812
And you're telling me that maybe
reality actually exists elsewhere,

01:59:56.832 --> 01:59:59.052
and this is all just a projection-

01:59:59.132 --> 01:59:59.812
- Well, I mean-

01:59:59.832 --> 02:00:02.452
- ... from the abstract realm.

02:00:02.492 --> 02:00:07.542
- Do abstract objects exist in a place and
at a time? That's very debatable, I think.

02:00:07.672 --> 02:00:08.832
- Right. And what does place and time mean?

02:00:08.842 --> 02:00:10.162
- Uh, all time, yeah, so...

02:00:10.332 --> 02:00:15.812
- So what's more real, physics or
the mathematical Platonic space?

02:00:16.332 --> 02:00:18.992
- Well, the mathematical Platonic realm

02:00:19.412 --> 02:00:23.092
is... I'm not sure I would say
it's more real, but I'm saying we

02:00:23.152 --> 02:00:27.532
understand the reality of it
in a much deeper and more-

02:00:27.552 --> 02:00:31.212
...a more convincing way. I don't think
we understand the nature of physical

02:00:31.272 --> 02:00:33.492
reality very well at all. And I think

02:00:34.512 --> 02:00:37.972
most people aren't even
scratching the surface of the

02:00:38.252 --> 02:00:42.052
question as I intend to be asking
it. So, you know, obviously we

02:00:42.092 --> 02:00:44.622
understand physical reality.
I mean, I knock on the table-

02:00:44.622 --> 02:00:48.412
...and so on, and we know all about what
it's like to, you know, have a birthday

02:00:48.452 --> 02:00:52.432
party or to drink a martini or
whatever. And so we, we, we

02:00:52.612 --> 02:00:56.552
have a deep understanding of
existing in the physical world.

02:00:56.592 --> 02:01:00.152
But maybe understanding is the wrong
word. We have an experience of

02:01:00.252 --> 02:01:01.332
living in the world-

02:01:01.512 --> 02:01:01.642
- Yeah, experience.

02:01:01.642 --> 02:01:05.472
- ...and riding bicycles and all those
things, but I don't think we actually

02:01:05.592 --> 02:01:09.392
have an understanding at all.
I mean, very, very little

02:01:09.472 --> 02:01:12.532
of the nature of physical
existence. I think it's a profound

02:01:12.572 --> 02:01:19.352
mystery. Whereas I think that we do
have something a little better of an

02:01:19.412 --> 02:01:23.352
understanding of the nature of mathematical
existence and abstract existence.

02:01:23.392 --> 02:01:26.092
So that's how I would describe the point.

02:01:26.152 --> 02:01:33.752
- Somehow it feels like we're approaching
some deep truth from different directions,

02:01:34.912 --> 02:01:38.072
and we just haven't traveled
as far in the physics

02:01:38.772 --> 02:01:41.362
world as we have in the
mathematical world.

02:01:41.532 --> 02:01:45.192
- Maybe I could hope that someone
will give, you know, the

02:01:45.352 --> 02:01:49.292
convincing account, but it seems to be
a profound mystery to me. I can't even

02:01:49.332 --> 02:01:52.892
imagine what it would be like to give
an account of physical existence.

02:01:52.912 --> 02:01:56.332
- Yeah, I wonder, like a thousand years
from now as physics progresses...

02:01:56.432 --> 02:01:56.442
- Right

02:01:56.442 --> 02:01:59.092
- ...what this same
conversation would look like.

02:01:59.172 --> 02:02:00.752
- Right. That would be quite interesting.

02:02:00.852 --> 02:02:04.552
- Do you think there's breakthroughs a thousand
years from now on the mathematics side?

02:02:04.812 --> 02:02:11.172
Because we've just discussed, and we'll
return to, a lot of turmoil a century ago.

02:02:11.232 --> 02:02:11.772
- Right.

02:02:12.092 --> 02:02:14.812
- Do you think there's
more turmoil to be had?

02:02:14.872 --> 02:02:18.832
- It's interesting to me because
I have my feet in two worlds

02:02:18.892 --> 02:02:22.872
of mathematics and philosophy,
and to compare the

02:02:22.912 --> 02:02:26.852
differences between these subjects.
And one of the, one of the

02:02:26.972 --> 02:02:30.452
big... There's many cultural differences,
but one of the big cultural differences is

02:02:30.832 --> 02:02:34.252
towards the idea of progress in the

02:02:34.312 --> 02:02:38.092
subject. Because mathematics
has huge progress. We

02:02:38.132 --> 02:02:41.242
simply understand the
mathematical ideas much, much

02:02:41.252 --> 02:02:45.156
better, you're continually
improving our understanding and

02:02:45.187 --> 02:02:49.107
there's growth in knowledge. We understand
the nature of infinity now better

02:02:49.147 --> 02:02:52.968
than they did 100 years ago. I
mean, definitely better. And they

02:02:52.977 --> 02:02:56.928
understood it better 100 years ago than they did,
you know, for the previous thousands of years

02:02:56.947 --> 02:03:00.758
and so on. So, in almost every
part of mathematics, there's

02:03:00.788 --> 02:03:04.487
improved understanding of
the core issues so much

02:03:04.588 --> 02:03:08.348
so that, you know, the
questions at hand become

02:03:08.407 --> 02:03:11.617
totally different and the
field sort of moves on to more

02:03:11.708 --> 02:03:15.687
difficult, interesting questions.
Whereas in philosophy,

02:03:15.727 --> 02:03:19.117
there's... That's a little
bit true that there's

02:03:19.227 --> 02:03:23.048
progress. But meanwhile, it's
also true that there are these

02:03:23.088 --> 02:03:26.968
eternal questions that have been
with us for thousands of years

02:03:27.147 --> 02:03:30.867
and in fact, so much so that you
can find a lot of philosophers

02:03:30.987 --> 02:03:34.827
arguing the important
contribution of philosophy is in

02:03:34.907 --> 02:03:38.848
asking the questions rather than
answering them because it's hopeless

02:03:38.888 --> 02:03:42.407
to answer them. I mean, the nature
of these deep philosophical

02:03:42.928 --> 02:03:46.848
questions is so difficult.
Less of a sense of

02:03:46.907 --> 02:03:50.748
progress is what I'm trying to
say. I don't see any reason to

02:03:50.808 --> 02:03:54.748
think that the progress in mathematics,
in the growth in our mathematical

02:03:54.808 --> 02:03:58.748
understanding and knowledge
won't simply continue. And

02:03:58.808 --> 02:04:04.027
so, a thousand years from now, maybe the
mathematics that they will be doing at that time

02:04:04.867 --> 02:04:08.668
would probably be completely
unrecognizable to me. I maybe

02:04:08.708 --> 02:04:12.487
wouldn't even begin to understand what
they're talking about, even without sort of

02:04:12.508 --> 02:04:15.977
witnessing, you know, the intervening

02:04:16.088 --> 02:04:19.748
developments. So if you
bring someone from ancient

02:04:19.808 --> 02:04:23.367
times to today, they maybe wouldn't even
understand what we're talking about

02:04:23.447 --> 02:04:27.367
with some of the questions.
But I feel that,

02:04:27.428 --> 02:04:30.647
you know, if Archimedes
came and we were able to

02:04:30.687 --> 02:04:34.348
communicate, I think I would
be able to tell him, you

02:04:34.407 --> 02:04:37.857
know, about some of the
things that are going on in

02:04:37.888 --> 02:04:42.517
mathematics now and,
and maybe, you know...

02:04:43.628 --> 02:04:48.388
Or, or anyone from that time, I
mean. So I think it is possible to

02:04:49.388 --> 02:04:53.088
have this kind of progress even
when the subject kind of shifts

02:04:53.147 --> 02:04:57.708
away from the earlier concerns as a
result of the progress, basically.

02:04:57.767 --> 02:05:01.208
- To take a tangent on a
tangent since you mentioned

02:05:01.248 --> 02:05:05.128
philosophy, maybe potentially more
about the questions and maybe

02:05:05.138 --> 02:05:08.107
mathematics is about the
answers, I have to say you are a

02:05:08.227 --> 02:05:12.107
legend on MathOverflow,
which is like Stack Overflow

02:05:12.128 --> 02:05:15.527
but for math. You're ranked number
one all time on there with currently

02:05:15.607 --> 02:05:23.147
over 246,000 reputation points. How do you
approach answering difficult questions on

02:05:23.227 --> 02:05:23.748
there?

02:05:24.147 --> 02:05:27.987
- Well, MathOverflow has really been
one of the great pleasures of

02:05:28.067 --> 02:05:32.027
my, of my life. I've really
enjoyed it. I mean... And I've

02:05:32.128 --> 02:05:39.308
learned so much from interacting on
MathOverflow. I've been on there since

02:05:39.428 --> 02:05:43.407
2009, which was shortly after it started. I mean,
it wasn't exactly at the start, but a little

02:05:43.447 --> 02:05:47.447
bit later. And and

02:05:48.987 --> 02:05:52.968
I think it gives you the stats for how
many characters I typed and I don't

02:05:53.008 --> 02:06:00.208
know how many million it is, but
uh, this enormous amount of um,

02:06:01.267 --> 02:06:05.048
time that I've spent thinking about those
questions and it has really just been

02:06:05.067 --> 02:06:06.477
amazing to me. Uh-

02:06:06.487 --> 02:06:09.987
- How do you find the questions that
grab you and how do you go about-

02:06:10.027 --> 02:06:10.147
- Right

02:06:10.248 --> 02:06:11.447
- ... answering them?

02:06:11.548 --> 02:06:15.388
- So, I'm interested in any
question that I find interesting.

02:06:15.397 --> 02:06:18.947
So... And it's not all questions.
Sometimes certain kinds of

02:06:18.987 --> 02:06:21.888
