appeal to me that much.

02:06:21.947 --> 02:06:23.918
- So you go outside of set theory as well?

02:06:23.947 --> 02:06:27.777
- So, I think when I first
joined MathOverflow, I

02:06:27.808 --> 02:06:31.487
was, I was basically one of
the only, one of the few

02:06:31.508 --> 02:06:35.367
people in logic who was answering. I
mean, there were other people who know

02:06:35.407 --> 02:06:38.577
some logic, particularly from
category theory and other parts of

02:06:38.628 --> 02:06:42.428
mathematics that aren't in
the most traditional parts of

02:06:42.527 --> 02:06:46.428
logic, but they were answering some of the
logic questions. So I really found myself

02:06:46.447 --> 02:06:49.888
able to make a contribution
in those very early days by

02:06:49.947 --> 02:06:53.827
engaging with the
logic-related questions. But

02:06:54.388 --> 02:06:57.837
there weren't many logic people asking
questions either. But what I found was

02:06:57.867 --> 02:07:00.968
that there was an enormous
amount of interest

02:07:01.107 --> 02:07:05.048
in topics that were logic-adjacent. So a

02:07:05.227 --> 02:07:09.168
question would arise, you know, in group
theory, but it had a logic aspect or an

02:07:09.208 --> 02:07:12.248
analysis or whatever, and
there would be some logic

02:07:12.788 --> 02:07:15.968
angle on it. And what I found
was that I was often able

02:07:16.888 --> 02:07:20.848
to figure out an answer
by learning enough about

02:07:20.928 --> 02:07:24.907
that other subject matter. This is what was so rewarding
for me, because basically I had to learn enough.

02:07:25.048 --> 02:07:28.647
had to learn enough. My
expertise, my main expertise was

02:07:28.727 --> 02:07:31.987
logic, but someone would ask a
question, you know, that, that

02:07:32.048 --> 02:07:35.788
was about, say, the axiom of
choice in this other subject

02:07:35.807 --> 02:07:39.527
matter or the continuum hypothesis or
something like that in an, in the other

02:07:39.607 --> 02:07:43.598
subject matter. And I would have to learn
enough about that other subject and

02:07:43.647 --> 02:07:47.048
the context of the question in order
to answer and I was often able to do

02:07:47.088 --> 02:07:51.008
that. And so I was quite happy
to do that. And, and also

02:07:51.107 --> 02:07:53.147
I learned a lot by doing that because

02:07:54.168 --> 02:07:57.867
I had to learn about these other
problem areas. And so it really

02:07:57.968 --> 02:08:01.147
allowed me to grow enormously
as a mathematician.

02:08:01.168 --> 02:08:05.128
- To give some examples of questions you've
answered, what are some reasonable

02:08:05.147 --> 02:08:09.138
sounding statements that are
independent of ZFC? What are the most

02:08:09.168 --> 02:08:13.107
misleading alternate definitions
in taught mathematics? Is

02:08:13.128 --> 02:08:16.727
the analysis as taught in universities
in fact the analysis of definable

02:08:16.788 --> 02:08:20.168
numbers? Solutions to the
continuum hypothesis?

02:08:20.687 --> 02:08:24.468
Most unintuitive application of
the axiom of choice? Non-trivial

02:08:24.487 --> 02:08:29.827
theorems with trivial proofs?
Reductio ad absurdum or the

02:08:29.947 --> 02:08:33.248
contrapositive? What is a chess piece

02:08:33.307 --> 02:08:37.248
mathematically? We should say you worked
quite a bit on infinite chess, which we

02:08:37.288 --> 02:08:40.928
should definitely talk about. It's awesome.
You've worked on so many fascinating

02:08:40.968 --> 02:08:44.962
things. Has philosophy ever
clarified mathematics?...

02:08:44.992 --> 02:08:48.772
why do we have two theorems
when one implies the other?

02:08:48.852 --> 02:08:52.502
And, of course, just as an
example you've given a really, a

02:08:52.532 --> 02:08:56.252
great, almost historical
answer on the topic of the

02:08:56.292 --> 02:09:00.232
continuum hypothesis. Maybe that's a good
place to go. We've touched on it a little

02:09:00.272 --> 02:09:03.632
bit, but it would be nice to
lay out what is the continuum

02:09:03.712 --> 02:09:07.692
hypothesis that Cantor struggled with.
And I would love to also speak to the

02:09:07.712 --> 02:09:11.272
psychology of his- his own life
story, his own struggle with it.

02:09:11.352 --> 02:09:14.562
It's the human side of
mathematics is also fascinating.

02:09:14.772 --> 02:09:16.312
So what is the continuum hypothesis?

02:09:16.352 --> 02:09:20.052
- So the continuum hypothesis
is the question that arises

02:09:20.062 --> 02:09:23.732
so naturally whenever you prove
that there's more than one size of

02:09:23.772 --> 02:09:29.252
infinity. So Cantor proved that the infinity
of the real numbers is strictly larger

02:09:30.212 --> 02:09:34.752
than the infinity of the natural numbers.
But immediately when you prove that,

02:09:36.272 --> 02:09:40.152
one wants to know, well, is there anything
in between? I mean, what could be a

02:09:40.192 --> 02:09:41.952
more natural question to ask

02:09:42.932 --> 02:09:46.862
immediately after that? And so
Cantor did ask it, and he spent his

02:09:46.912 --> 02:09:50.902
whole life thinking about this question.
And so the continuum hypothesis

02:09:50.952 --> 02:09:54.862
is the assertion that there is no
infinity in between the natural numbers

02:09:54.892 --> 02:09:58.772
and the real numbers. And, of
course, Cantor knew many sets

02:09:58.852 --> 02:10:02.292
of real numbers. Everything in between...
I mean, everything that's in that

02:10:02.352 --> 02:10:05.732
interval would be equinumerous
with some set of real

02:10:05.792 --> 02:10:09.512
numbers. But we know lots of sets of real
numbers. I mean, there's all these various

02:10:09.572 --> 02:10:13.492
closed sets, Cantor sets, and so on.
There's Vitali sets. We have all kinds of

02:10:13.532 --> 02:10:17.132
sets of real numbers. And so you
might think, well, if the continuum

02:10:17.142 --> 02:10:21.112
hypothesis is false, then we've probably
seen the- the set already. We just have

02:10:21.152 --> 02:10:24.892
to prove, you know, that it's
strictly in between. But it turned

02:10:24.972 --> 02:10:28.872
out that for all the sets that
anyone ever could define or pick

02:10:28.932 --> 02:10:32.752
out or observe, for all the sets of
real numbers, it was always the case

02:10:32.852 --> 02:10:36.732
either that they were countable,
in which case they're equinumerous

02:10:36.832 --> 02:10:40.752
with the natural numbers or
else finite. Or they were

02:10:40.832 --> 02:10:44.732
fully equinumerous with the
whole real line. And so

02:10:44.832 --> 02:10:48.452
they were never strictly in between. I
mean, you're in this situation and you

02:10:48.492 --> 02:10:52.112
have 100, thousands of sets that are

02:10:52.212 --> 02:10:56.112
candidates to be in between,
but in every single case,

02:10:56.192 --> 02:10:58.212
you can prove it's on
one side or the other

02:10:59.132 --> 02:11:02.992
and not strictly in between.
And so in every situation

02:11:03.012 --> 02:11:06.512
where you're able to figure out
whether it's in between or not, it's

02:11:06.612 --> 02:11:08.872
always never strictly in between.

02:11:09.292 --> 02:11:11.872
- Now, Cantor was obsessed with this.

02:11:11.952 --> 02:11:15.242
- I think he was. Yeah, I'm not a historian,
so I don't know the exact history.

02:11:15.272 --> 02:11:18.812
- Well, everything I've seen, it seems to
be the question that broke him, huh? Um,

02:11:19.572 --> 02:11:23.452
I mean, just struggling with
different opinions on the hypothesis

02:11:23.912 --> 02:11:29.532
within himself and... ...Desperately
chasing, trying to prove it.

02:11:29.592 --> 02:11:32.372
- So he had a program for
proving it, which has been

02:11:33.412 --> 02:11:37.172
affirmed in a certain respect. Of
course, the continuum hypothesis holds

02:11:37.212 --> 02:11:40.372
for open sets. That's easy
to see. If you have an open

02:11:40.472 --> 02:11:44.392
interval, then this is fully
equinumerous with the whole

02:11:44.492 --> 02:11:46.982
real line. Any interval is
equinumerous with the whole line

02:11:47.872 --> 02:11:51.712
because all you would need is a function,
you know, like the arctangent function

02:11:51.752 --> 02:11:55.692
or something that maps the whole
real line into an interval. And

02:11:55.732 --> 02:11:59.592
that's a one-to-one function.
So we know the open sets

02:11:59.892 --> 02:12:03.652
have the property that their
non-trivial open sets are all

02:12:03.692 --> 02:12:06.732
fully equinumerous with the whole real
line. So, never strictly in between.

02:12:07.712 --> 02:12:11.612
But remarkably, Cantor proved
it also for the closed sets,

02:12:11.892 --> 02:12:15.812
and that is using what's called
the Cantor-Bendixson theorem. So,

02:12:15.852 --> 02:12:19.432
it's quite a remarkable result.
It's definitely not obvious.

02:12:20.232 --> 02:12:24.192
And in this theorem actually was
the origin of the ordinals. Cantor

02:12:24.272 --> 02:12:31.812
had to invent the ordinals in order to make
sense of his Cantor-Bendixson process.

02:12:31.872 --> 02:12:34.332
- Can you define the open and the
closed set in this context?

02:12:34.392 --> 02:12:38.382
- Oh, yeah. Sure. So a set
of reals is open if every

02:12:38.512 --> 02:12:42.132
point that it contains is
surrounded by a little interval of

02:12:42.252 --> 02:12:46.122
points, the whole tiny
little interval. But that

02:12:46.172 --> 02:12:49.492
tiny little interval is already just by
itself equinumerous with the whole line.

02:12:49.512 --> 02:12:53.252
So that's why that question is sort
of easy for open sets. A closed

02:12:53.332 --> 02:12:56.972
set is a complement of an open
set, and there's a lot of

02:12:57.032 --> 02:13:00.811
closed sets that are really
complicated of varying

02:13:00.852 --> 02:13:04.482
sizes. So of course, any closed interval
is a closed set, but it's not only those.

02:13:04.512 --> 02:13:08.112
There's also things like the Cantor
set, which you get by omitting middle

02:13:08.212 --> 02:13:12.092
thirds. Maybe some people have
seen this construction. Or you can

02:13:12.152 --> 02:13:15.932
imagine sort of randomly
taking a lot of little tiny

02:13:16.012 --> 02:13:19.992
open intervals, you know, all over the line
and so on. So that altogether would be an open

02:13:20.092 --> 02:13:24.032
set, and the complement of it would be
a closed set. So you can imagine just

02:13:24.072 --> 02:13:27.772
kind of tossing down these open
intervals, and what's left over

02:13:27.952 --> 02:13:31.852
is the closed set. Those sets can be
quite complicated, and they can have

02:13:31.952 --> 02:13:35.852
isolated points, for example, if
the two open intervals were just

02:13:35.912 --> 02:13:39.342
kissing and leaving only the one point
between them. But also you could

02:13:39.432 --> 02:13:43.232
have sequences that are
converging to a point, that would

02:13:43.292 --> 02:13:47.172
also be a closed set, or
convergent sequences of convergent

02:13:47.252 --> 02:13:50.472
sequences and so on. That
would be a closed set also.

02:13:50.512 --> 02:13:54.492
- The Cantor set is constructed by iteratively
removing open intervals, middle thirds,

02:13:54.552 --> 02:13:55.592
like you mentioned, from the interval,

02:13:56.512 --> 02:14:00.552
and trying to see, can we do a
thing that that goes in between?

02:14:00.612 --> 02:14:04.192
- Right. So the question would
be, can you produce a set

02:14:05.032 --> 02:14:09.562
that has an intermediate size? an
intermediate cardinality, right?

02:14:09.572 --> 02:14:13.532
And Cantor proved, with the closed set,
"No, it's impossible." Every closed

02:14:13.592 --> 02:14:18.272
set is either countable or
equinumerous with the whole real line.

02:14:18.312 --> 02:14:23.872
And the Cantor program for solving
the Continuum Hypothesis was,

02:14:25.152 --> 02:14:29.002
a sort of working up. So you did it
for open sets and for closed sets,

02:14:29.092 --> 02:14:32.922
and you sort of work up. Maybe he wants to
go into what are called the Borel sets,

02:14:32.952 --> 02:14:36.582
which are sort of combinations of open
and closed sets. And there's a vast

02:14:36.632 --> 02:14:40.582
hierarchy of Borel complexity. And it

02:14:40.632 --> 02:14:44.542
turns out that the Continuum
Hypothesis has been proved also

02:14:44.552 --> 02:14:48.544
for the Borel sets in this hierarchy.
But then one wants to go beyond.

02:14:48.624 --> 02:14:52.514
What about more complicated sets? So
there's this hierarchy of complexity

02:14:52.584 --> 02:14:56.524
for sets of real numbers. And Cantor's
idea was to sort of work your way up the

02:14:56.544 --> 02:15:00.354
hierarchy by proving that
the Continuum Hypothesis

02:15:00.404 --> 02:15:04.274
was more and more true for those more
and more complicated sets, based on our

02:15:04.324 --> 02:15:07.924
understanding of the
earlier cases. And that has

02:15:07.984 --> 02:15:15.014
been carried out to a remarkable degree.
It turns out that one begins to need

02:15:15.564 --> 02:15:19.544
large cardinal assumptions,
though, in order to get to

02:15:19.584 --> 02:15:22.704
the higher realms, even at the
level of projective hierarchy,

02:15:23.504 --> 02:15:27.424
which are sets that you can define by
using quantifiers over the real numbers

02:15:27.444 --> 02:15:31.284
themselves. So you get this hierarchy
on top of the Borel hierarchy,

02:15:32.024 --> 02:15:35.864
the hierarchy of projectively
definable sets. And it

02:15:35.904 --> 02:15:41.014
turns out that if you have enough large
cardinals, then the projective sets

02:15:42.284 --> 02:15:45.844
also are always either countable or
equinumerous with the whole real

02:15:45.904 --> 02:15:49.884
line. And then one can try
to go beyond this and so

02:15:49.924 --> 02:15:53.904
on. So I view all of those results
which came, you know, in the past 50

02:15:53.924 --> 02:16:01.714
years, the later ones, as fulfilling
this Cantor idea that goes back,

02:16:01.764 --> 02:16:05.734
you know, 120 years to his idea
that we would prove the Continuum

02:16:05.744 --> 02:16:09.404
Hypothesis by establishing more
and more instances for greater and

02:16:09.484 --> 02:16:12.604
greater complexity of sets. But of course,

02:16:13.684 --> 02:16:17.404
even with what we know now, it
hasn't fully succeeded and it

02:16:17.464 --> 02:16:21.304
can't because the hierarchy
of complexity doesn't include

02:16:21.504 --> 02:16:25.244
all sets of real numbers. Some of them
are, sort of, transcending this hierarchy

02:16:25.284 --> 02:16:28.264
completely, in a way. And

02:16:29.264 --> 02:16:33.184
so the program can't ever fully be
successful, especially in light

02:16:33.244 --> 02:16:34.434
of the independence result.

02:16:34.964 --> 02:16:38.844
- Yeah. Well, spoiler alert, can you
go to the independence result?

02:16:38.884 --> 02:16:39.274
- Sure.

02:16:39.304 --> 02:16:43.244
- So what does that mean? So the Continuum

02:16:43.284 --> 02:16:46.574
Hypothesis was shown to be independent
from the ZFC axioms of mathematics?

02:16:46.604 --> 02:16:50.504
- Right. So the ZFC axioms
were the axioms that were

02:16:50.544 --> 02:16:54.443
put forth first by Zermelo
in 1908 in regard to his

02:16:54.484 --> 02:16:58.464
proof of the well-order theorem
using the axiom of choice. That

02:16:58.504 --> 02:17:02.324
wasn't fully ZFC. At that time, it
was just Zermelo theory because he

02:17:02.364 --> 02:17:06.344
sort of... There was a kind of missing
axiom, the replacement axiom, and the

02:17:06.384 --> 02:17:09.864
foundation axiom were added later, and
that's what makes the Zermelo-Fraenkel

02:17:10.524 --> 02:17:12.693
axiomatization, which
became, sort of, standard.

02:17:13.684 --> 02:17:17.644
Actually, there's another aspect, which
is Zermelo's original theory allowed

02:17:17.804 --> 02:17:20.564
for the existence of ur-elements, or these

02:17:20.744 --> 02:17:24.464
atoms, mathematical
objects that are not sets

02:17:25.484 --> 02:17:28.724
but out of which we build
the set theoretic universe,

02:17:28.764 --> 02:17:35.144
whereas set theorists today generally
don't use ur-elements at all. I,

02:17:36.824 --> 02:17:40.604
I argue that it's really the
philosophy of structuralism that

02:17:40.644 --> 02:17:44.364
leads them to omit the ur-elements
because it turns out that

02:17:44.984 --> 02:17:52.584
if you adopt ZFC axioms with ur-elements,
ZFCU it's called, or ZFA, then any

02:17:52.704 --> 02:17:56.684
structure that exists, any mathematical structure
that exists in that set theoretic universe

02:17:56.724 --> 02:18:01.204
with the atoms is isomorphic to a structure
that doesn't use the atoms at all.

02:18:02.684 --> 02:18:06.563
And you don't need the atoms if you're a
structuralist because you only care about

02:18:06.604 --> 02:18:10.504
the structures up to isomorphism
anyways, and the theory is simply more

02:18:10.544 --> 02:18:13.744
elegant and clear without
the atoms. They're just not

02:18:13.804 --> 02:18:17.784
needed. And so that's why today when
we talk about set theory, generally we

02:18:17.824 --> 02:18:20.904
talk about the atom-free
version, and ZFC has no

02:18:20.984 --> 02:18:24.924
ur-elements. Okay. So we formulate the ZFC

02:18:25.044 --> 02:18:28.284
axioms of set theory. These
are expressing the main

02:18:28.744 --> 02:18:35.784
principle ideas that we have about the
nature of sets and set existence. And

02:18:38.064 --> 02:18:40.304
Canter had asked about
the continuum hypothesis

02:18:41.604 --> 02:18:50.084
in the late 19th century, and it
remained open, totally open until 1938.

02:18:50.564 --> 02:18:53.904
- We should mention, I apologize,
that it was the number one

02:18:54.384 --> 02:18:58.244
problem in the Hilbert's 23 set
of problems formulated at the

02:18:58.284 --> 02:18:59.324
beginning of the century.

02:18:59.364 --> 02:18:59.864
- That's right.

02:18:59.884 --> 02:19:02.414
- Maybe you can comment on why
did he put that as number one.

02:19:02.844 --> 02:19:06.734
- So... Right. So Hilbert had introduced
at his famous address at the

02:19:06.784 --> 02:19:10.584
turn of the century this list
of problems that he thought

02:19:11.384 --> 02:19:14.744
could guide or were
important to consider in the

02:19:15.424 --> 02:19:19.244
coming century of mathematics. I mean, that's how
people talk about it now, although I'm not sure at

02:19:19.324 --> 02:19:22.914
all... Of course, I can't really
speak for Hilbert at all, but if

02:19:23.004 --> 02:19:25.784
you were a very prominent mathematician,

02:19:27.644 --> 02:19:31.504
I find it a little hard to believe that
Hilbert would have conceived of his list

02:19:31.704 --> 02:19:35.452
in the same way that we now
take his lists. I mean,

02:19:35.544 --> 02:19:39.404
having observed the century
unfold, we know that that list of

02:19:39.544 --> 02:19:43.474
23 problems did in fact guide
whole research programs, and

02:19:43.524 --> 02:19:47.424
it was extremely important and
influential. But at the time, Hilbert

02:19:47.443 --> 02:19:51.324
would have no reason to think that
that would be true, and he was

02:19:51.384 --> 02:19:55.304
just giving a lecture and
had a list of problems that

02:19:55.324 --> 02:19:59.314
he thought were very important.
And so I tend to I would find

02:19:59.344 --> 02:20:03.124
it more reasonable to think that he was just
making a list of problems that he thought were

02:20:03.224 --> 02:20:07.124
extremely interesting and important
and fundamental in a way without

02:20:07.204 --> 02:20:11.044
the kind of heavy burden of

02:20:11.124 --> 02:20:15.044
guiding this 20th century
research. Although it turns out

02:20:15.104 --> 02:20:16.944
that in fact that's exactly what they did.

02:20:18.144 --> 02:20:21.964
And we already discussed how
Hilbert's views on the nature of set

02:20:22.044 --> 02:20:24.864
theory and the fundamental
character, that quote

02:20:25.804 --> 02:20:29.204
where he said, "No one will
cast us from the paradise that

02:20:29.544 --> 02:20:33.084
Canter has created for us." So, so I think

02:20:33.324 --> 02:20:37.084
Hilbert was convinced by Canter
on the importance and the

02:20:37.164 --> 02:20:41.144
fundamental nature of the continuum hypothesis
for the foundations of mathematics,

02:20:41.164 --> 02:20:44.884
which was a critically important
development for the unity of

02:20:44.964 --> 02:20:48.924
mathematics. I mean, before set theory
emerged as a foundation of mathematics,

02:20:48.984 --> 02:20:52.600
you know, there are different
subjects in mathematics.

02:20:52.620 --> 02:20:56.140
There's algebra and there's analysis,
real analysis, and topology and

02:20:56.200 --> 02:20:59.000
geometry, and so on. There are
all these disparate subjects

02:21:00.180 --> 02:21:03.800
with their own axioms,
separate axioms, right?

02:21:03.810 --> 02:21:07.600
And sometimes it happens, like when
you're proving, say, the fundamental

02:21:07.660 --> 02:21:11.520
theorem of algebra, you know, that the
complex numbers are an algebraically closed

02:21:11.560 --> 02:21:15.210
field that you can solve
any polynomial equation in.

02:21:16.300 --> 02:21:19.699
But the proof methods for
that theorem come from

02:21:19.770 --> 02:21:23.680
other parts of mathematics. You know,
those topological proofs and so

02:21:23.800 --> 02:21:27.490
on. And so how does that

02:21:27.540 --> 02:21:31.480
work? I mean, if you have totally different
axiom systems, but you're using results from

02:21:31.600 --> 02:21:35.220
one subject in another subject,
it's somehow incoherent

02:21:35.280 --> 02:21:37.720
unless there's one underlying

02:21:38.660 --> 02:21:42.640
subject. So the unity of
mathematics was provided by the

02:21:42.680 --> 02:21:46.590
existence of a mathematical foundation like set
theory. And at the time, it was set theory.

02:21:47.220 --> 02:21:51.170
And so it's critically
important to be able to have a

02:21:51.240 --> 02:21:55.180
single theory in which one views
all of mathematics as taking

02:21:55.220 --> 02:21:59.050
place to resolve that kind
of transfer and borrowing

02:21:59.060 --> 02:22:02.980
phenomenon that was definitely
happening. So that must

02:22:03.000 --> 02:22:06.980
have been part of Hilbert's thinking about
why it's so important to have a uniform

02:22:07.020 --> 02:22:10.990
foundation, and set theory was playing that
role at the time. Now, of course, we have

02:22:11.020 --> 02:22:14.400
other possible foundations coming
from category theory or type

02:22:14.500 --> 02:22:17.970
theory, and there's univalent

02:22:18.060 --> 02:22:21.880
foundations now. So there are sort of
competing foundations now. There's no

02:22:21.960 --> 02:22:25.860
need to just use one foundation, one
set theoretic foundation. Although

02:22:25.900 --> 02:22:29.420
set theory continues to, in my
view, have an extremely successful

02:22:29.880 --> 02:22:33.600
meta-mathematical analysis as a
foundation, I think is much more

02:22:33.620 --> 02:22:37.420
successful than set theory for any
of those other foundations, but

02:22:37.680 --> 02:22:41.640
it's much less amenable though to things like
computer proof and so on, which is part of

02:22:41.680 --> 02:22:45.560
the motivation to find these alternative
foundations. So, yeah, okay, so

02:22:45.660 --> 02:22:49.060
just to talk about Hilbert
though, I think he was motivated

02:22:49.080 --> 02:22:52.570
by the need for a unifying foundation of

02:22:52.620 --> 02:22:56.600
mathematics, and set theory was playing
that role, and the continuum hypothesis

02:22:56.640 --> 02:23:00.579
is such a core, fundamental
question to ask, so it

02:23:00.900 --> 02:23:04.620
seems quite natural that he would
put it on the list. There were other

02:23:04.660 --> 02:23:08.510
logic-related questions though, like Hilbert's
tenth problem is also related to logic.

02:23:08.510 --> 02:23:12.440
This is the question about
Diophantine equations, and

02:23:12.500 --> 02:23:16.000
he asked to provide an algorithm
to decide whether a given

02:23:16.020 --> 02:23:19.920
Diophantine equation has a solution
in the integers. So a Diophantine

02:23:19.940 --> 02:23:23.929
equation is just, I mean, it's
maybe a fancy way of talking about

02:23:23.960 --> 02:23:27.830
something that's easy to understand,
a polynomial equation, except it's

02:23:27.900 --> 02:23:31.040
not just one variable, many variables.

02:23:31.380 --> 02:23:35.040
So you have polynomials in
several variables over the

02:23:35.080 --> 02:23:38.960
integers, and you want to know, can
you solve it? So the problem is,

02:23:38.980 --> 02:23:42.240
as stated by Hilbert, to provide an

02:23:42.360 --> 02:23:45.680
algorithm for answering the
question whether a given

02:23:45.740 --> 02:23:48.680
polynomial equation has a
solution in the integers.

02:23:49.740 --> 02:23:53.700
So he's sort of presuming that there is an
algorithm, but he wants to know what it

02:23:53.760 --> 02:24:01.240
is. What is the algorithm? But the problem
was solved by proving that there is no

02:24:01.280 --> 02:24:04.760
algorithm. It's an undecidable
problem, like the halting problem.

02:24:05.460 --> 02:24:09.179
There is no computable procedure that
will correctly decide whether a given

02:24:09.270 --> 02:24:13.240
polynomial equation has a solution
in the integers. So that's quite

02:24:13.280 --> 02:24:16.580
a remarkable development, I think.
There were also a few other

02:24:17.180 --> 02:24:20.200
logic-related questions on the list.

02:24:20.220 --> 02:24:24.180
- And so eventually, continuum hypothesis
was shown to be independent from ZFC

02:24:24.260 --> 02:24:28.280
axioms, as we've mentioned. So,
how does that make you feel?

02:24:29.220 --> 02:24:30.970
What is independence,
and what does that mean?

02:24:30.970 --> 02:24:32.810
- But once you tell the story,
the historical story...

02:24:32.820 --> 02:24:32.900
- Yes

02:24:32.980 --> 02:24:34.090
- ...is really quite dramatic.

02:24:34.140 --> 02:24:34.149
- Yeah, that's great

02:24:34.149 --> 02:24:39.260
- I think, because Cantor poses the
question, you know, late 19th century.

02:24:39.270 --> 02:24:43.200
And then it's totally open. Hilbert asks
about it, you know, at the turn of the

02:24:43.340 --> 02:24:47.279
20th century. Nobody has
any clue. There's no answer

02:24:47.380 --> 02:24:53.820
coming until 1938. This is four
decades later, right? So a long

02:24:53.880 --> 02:25:01.170
time, and Gödel, Kurt Gödel, proved
half of it. What he proved is that

02:25:03.020 --> 02:25:09.559
if the axioms of set theory are consistent,
then there is a set theoretic world

02:25:10.660 --> 02:25:15.800
where both the axiom of choice and
the continuum hypothesis are true.

02:25:17.400 --> 02:25:22.400
So what he's doing is showing this is called
the constructible universe, Gödel's L.

02:25:24.180 --> 02:25:28.060
So he solved this. This is the same result

02:25:28.120 --> 02:25:31.920
where he answers the safety question
of the axiom of choice, but

02:25:31.980 --> 02:25:36.440
also for the continuum hypothesis. They're
true in the same set theoretic universe

02:25:37.280 --> 02:25:41.160
we get. So if ZF, without the axiom
of choice, is consistent, then so is

02:25:41.220 --> 02:25:47.890
ZFC plus the continuum hypothesis is the
result. 1938. It's really such a beautiful

02:25:47.960 --> 02:25:51.330
argument. It's just
incredible, I think, because

02:25:51.380 --> 02:25:54.820
he's building an alternative mathematical

02:25:54.900 --> 02:25:58.210
reality. That's the structure
of the proof, is that, okay,

02:25:58.260 --> 02:26:02.080
if there's any mathematical reality,
if there's any set theoretic

02:26:02.160 --> 02:26:05.920
world, then we're going to build
another one, a separate one, a

02:26:05.960 --> 02:26:09.080
different one, maybe different. Maybe it's
the same as the original one, it could be.

02:26:09.140 --> 02:26:12.670
If we started already in the one that he
built, then it would be the same. But

02:26:13.140 --> 02:26:16.900
there's no reason to assume it was
the same. So he has this kind of

02:26:17.060 --> 02:26:20.440
model construction method to build this

02:26:20.520 --> 02:26:24.470
alternative set theoretic reality,
the constructible universe. And then

02:26:24.500 --> 02:26:28.450
he proves that the axiom of choice is true
there, and also the continuum hypothesis is

02:26:28.480 --> 02:26:32.040
true there, and it's just amazing.
Really beautiful argument.

02:26:32.720 --> 02:26:36.700
Okay, so then for the other part of the
independence, that's only half of it,

02:26:36.740 --> 02:26:40.400
because Gödel shows basically

02:26:40.460 --> 02:26:44.410
that you can't refute the continuum
hypothesis, but that's not

02:26:44.440 --> 02:26:48.380
the same thing as proving
that it's true. He showed

02:26:48.440 --> 02:26:52.158
that if set theory is consistent...

02:26:52.188 --> 02:26:55.468
without the continuum hypothesis, then it's
consistent with the continuum hypothesis.

02:26:55.548 --> 02:26:59.408
So that's not the same thing as
proving that it's true. Yeah.

02:26:59.468 --> 02:27:06.628
And then it didn't come until 1963, when
Paul Cohen invented the method of forcing.

02:27:06.748 --> 02:27:10.188
And proved that if there's a model of set

02:27:10.208 --> 02:27:13.768
theory, then there's a model of
set theory in which the continuum

02:27:13.828 --> 02:27:18.468
hypothesis is false. So Cohen also is

02:27:19.668 --> 02:27:23.208
giving us this extremely
powerful tool for building

02:27:23.228 --> 02:27:26.828
alternative mathematical
realities, is how I think about

02:27:26.868 --> 02:27:30.648
it. He's explained to us how
to take any set theoretic

02:27:30.748 --> 02:27:34.428
world and build another different one
in which the continuum hypothesis is

02:27:34.468 --> 02:27:37.608
false. The forcing extension.

02:27:37.648 --> 02:27:40.788
- It's just such a fascinating technique,

02:27:40.868 --> 02:27:44.698
tool of forcing. Maybe I'm
anthropomorphizing it,

02:27:44.788 --> 02:27:52.008
but it seems like a way to escape one
mathematical universe into another, or to

02:27:52.048 --> 02:27:55.928
expand it or to alter it. So
you travel between mathematical

02:27:55.968 --> 02:27:57.738
universes. Can you explain
the technique of forcing?

02:27:57.748 --> 02:28:01.378
- Yeah, exactly. It's all those things. It's
so wonderful. I mean, that's exactly how

02:28:01.748 --> 02:28:03.658
I think about it. I mean...

02:28:03.658 --> 02:28:07.488
- And we should mention, maybe this is
a good place to even give a bigger

02:28:07.548 --> 02:28:11.468
picture. One of your more
controversial ideas in mathematics as

02:28:11.568 --> 02:28:14.988
laid out in the paper, The
Set-Theoretic Multiverse, you

02:28:15.028 --> 02:28:18.328
describe that there may not be one true

02:28:18.428 --> 02:28:21.548
mathematics, but rather multiple
mathematical universes, and

02:28:21.728 --> 02:28:25.678
forcing is one of the techniques that
gets you from one to the other, so...

02:28:25.688 --> 02:28:25.748
- The-

02:28:25.788 --> 02:28:27.398
- Can you explain the whole
shebang? The whole...

02:28:27.408 --> 02:28:34.668
- Yeah, sure. Let's get into it. So the
lesson of Cohen's result and Gödel's

02:28:34.748 --> 02:28:38.688
result and so on, these producing
these alternative set theoretic

02:28:38.808 --> 02:28:42.588
universes. We've observed that
the continuum hypothesis is

02:28:42.628 --> 02:28:46.228
independent and the axiom of choice
is independent of the other axioms,

02:28:46.248 --> 02:28:50.048
but it's not just those two. We have
thousands of independence results.

02:28:50.108 --> 02:28:53.488
Practically every non-trivial
statement of infinite

02:28:53.508 --> 02:28:56.468
combinatorics is independent
of ZFC. I mean, this is the

02:28:56.528 --> 02:29:00.068
fact. It's not universally true. There are

02:29:00.108 --> 02:29:03.708
some extremely difficult
prominent results where

02:29:03.748 --> 02:29:07.638
people proved things in
ZFC, but for the most

02:29:07.668 --> 02:29:11.388
part, if you ask a non-trivial
question about infinite

02:29:11.448 --> 02:29:14.628
cardinalities, then it's very
likely to be independent of

02:29:14.668 --> 02:29:18.588
ZFC. And we have these
thousands of arguments, these

02:29:18.608 --> 02:29:22.588
forcing arguments that are
used to establish that. And

02:29:22.648 --> 02:29:26.638
so how should we take that? I
mean, on the one hand, if you have

02:29:26.688 --> 02:29:30.628
a theory and it doesn't answer
any of the questions that you're

02:29:30.688 --> 02:29:34.648
interested in... Okay, so what does
that mean? If you're following what I

02:29:34.728 --> 02:29:37.268
call the universe view or the monist view,

02:29:38.748 --> 02:29:45.768
you might naturally say, "Well, look, ZFC
is a weak theory, and there's the true

02:29:46.888 --> 02:29:50.608
set theoretic reality out there,
and we need a better theory

02:29:50.708 --> 02:29:53.478
'cause the current theory isn't
answering the questions. Everything's

02:29:53.588 --> 02:29:57.408
independent." And so that seems
like a quite reasonable thing

02:29:57.448 --> 02:30:01.348
to take. If you think that there is...
that every set theoretic question has a

02:30:01.388 --> 02:30:05.208
definite answer and there's a unique
set theoretic truth or a unique

02:30:05.348 --> 02:30:08.708
fact of the matter, right,
this is the universe view.

02:30:09.108 --> 02:30:10.598
- And by the way, to reiterate,

02:30:11.428 --> 02:30:14.928
independent means it cannot be
proved or disproved within this

02:30:14.988 --> 02:30:16.888
axiomatic system within this theory.

02:30:16.968 --> 02:30:20.908
- Right. Exactly. So to be independent means you
can't prove it and also you can't prove that

02:30:20.948 --> 02:30:22.448
it's false. You can't refute it.

02:30:22.608 --> 02:30:26.488
- And you're saying that's why the
statement is so traumatic or sad, that

02:30:26.548 --> 02:30:30.528
most of the interesting stuff, as you
said, has been shown to be independent.

02:30:31.128 --> 02:30:31.778
of ZFC.

02:30:31.868 --> 02:30:35.748
- But, but that's an interesting way to put
it, I think, because it reminds me of this,

02:30:35.868 --> 02:30:39.848
uh... when I was a graduate
student in Berkeley, there was

02:30:39.888 --> 02:30:43.768
another graduate student who
was working with a non-logic

02:30:43.848 --> 02:30:47.728
professor in C-star algebras or something

02:30:47.768 --> 02:30:51.148
like this. So it's a part of
analysis or functional analysis,

02:30:51.908 --> 02:30:55.348
and they were looking at a
question, and it turned out to be

02:30:55.408 --> 02:30:59.168
independent of ZFC, right?
And the attitude of this

02:30:59.268 --> 02:31:02.778
other professor was that, "Oh,
I guess I asked the wrong

02:31:02.828 --> 02:31:06.808
question." But my attitude and the

02:31:06.868 --> 02:31:10.737
attitude of all the set theorists
was when you ask a question that

02:31:10.768 --> 02:31:14.608
turns out to be independent, then you asked
exactly the right question because this is the

02:31:14.648 --> 02:31:18.448
one... You know, it's carving
nature at its joints.

02:31:18.508 --> 02:31:22.328
You're adjudicating the nature
of set theoretic reality

02:31:22.348 --> 02:31:25.148
by finding these two realms.
You find one of these

02:31:25.168 --> 02:31:28.928
dichotomies. You know, there's the worlds where
it's true and the worlds where it's false.

02:31:28.948 --> 02:31:32.888
And so when you ask that question, that's to
be celebrated. It means you asked exactly

02:31:32.928 --> 02:31:36.688
the right, interesting, fascinating
question. So it's not a kind of bleak

02:31:36.768 --> 02:31:40.608
thing that you can't prove it and you can't
refute it, and that's such a disaster.

02:31:40.648 --> 02:31:48.148
Rather, it means that you found this...
this... this cleavage in reality, in

02:31:48.208 --> 02:31:52.958
mathematical reality, and it's good to know
about those when they happen, you know?

02:31:52.968 --> 02:31:55.928
- Carving nature at its joints.
So what can you do about the

02:31:56.028 --> 02:31:59.848
things that are shown to
be independent from ZFC?

02:32:00.048 --> 02:32:00.358
- Right. So...

02:32:00.368 --> 02:32:01.198
- What are the techniques?

02:32:01.198 --> 02:32:03.908
- So one thing is that because
of the incompleteness theorem,

02:32:04.948 --> 02:32:08.738
we know that there's
going to be... For any

02:32:08.848 --> 02:32:12.488
theory that we can write down, there's
going to be things that we can't

02:32:12.668 --> 02:32:16.488
prove, true things we can't prove in it.
So there's those things are gonna be

02:32:16.548 --> 02:32:23.528
independent. And so we're already aware of
the fact that there will always be these

02:32:23.768 --> 02:32:27.418
independent phenomenon for
any theory that we write. And

02:32:27.508 --> 02:32:31.328
furthermore, some of those theories
we won't even be able to prove

02:32:31.348 --> 02:32:34.588
that they're consistent, you know, like the
consistency of their own theory. So that's called the

02:32:34.668 --> 02:32:36.588
consistency-strength hierarchy.

02:32:37.448 --> 02:32:41.168
So it's a direct consequence of Gödel's
second incompleteness theorem that

02:32:42.328 --> 02:32:46.128
for any theory we can write down,
then towering over it is this

02:32:46.188 --> 02:32:49.708
incredibly tall tower of
consistency strength,

02:32:49.948 --> 02:32:53.188
where the strength in theories
aren't just adding another

02:32:53.268 --> 02:32:57.008
axiom, but they're adding another
axiom even whose consistency was not

02:32:57.048 --> 02:33:00.578
provable in the previous
layers of the hierarchy.

02:33:01.068 --> 02:33:04.851
So, and so how lucky we
are to find the large

02:33:04.911 --> 02:33:12.071
cardinal axioms that instantiate
exactly this feature of increasing

02:33:12.171 --> 02:33:19.702
consistency strength, this unending and
extremely tall hierarchy of consistency

02:33:19.831 --> 02:33:23.552
strength of axioms. And it
exactly fulfills the prediction

02:33:23.612 --> 02:33:27.511
that Gödel's theorem
makes about that kind of

02:33:27.552 --> 02:33:31.542
thing. Except, it's the
axioms in the large cardinal

02:33:31.542 --> 02:33:34.761
hierarchy aren't, you know, metalogical

02:33:35.011 --> 02:33:38.472
self-referential statements of the
form that sometimes arise in the Gödel

02:33:38.552 --> 02:33:41.661
analysis, but rather they're professing

02:33:42.171 --> 02:33:46.732
existence of big infinities, these
large cardinal axioms. And so

02:33:47.692 --> 02:33:51.312
it's such a welcome
development, and yet it's

02:33:51.411 --> 02:33:54.712
also known that the
continuum hypothesis is

02:33:54.911 --> 02:33:59.612
independent of all of the known
large cardinal axioms. So

02:34:00.552 --> 02:34:04.452
none of the large cardinal
axioms we can prove, none

02:34:04.491 --> 02:34:08.271
of them can settle the continuum
hypothesis. So the independence

02:34:08.312 --> 02:34:11.722
phenomenon is still there for
things like the continuum

02:34:11.771 --> 02:34:17.042
hypothesis and the cardinal
combinatorics that I mentioned.

02:34:17.052 --> 02:34:19.962
- So you're building this
incredible hierarchy

02:34:21.312 --> 02:34:24.831
of axiomatic systems that are
more powerful than the ZFC.

02:34:24.841 --> 02:34:28.712
- More powerful than ZFC and then more powerful
than that, more powerful than that, and so on.

02:34:28.732 --> 02:34:32.802
It keeps going forever, and
it will never be finished.

02:34:32.831 --> 02:34:36.782
- And still, to this day, the
continuum hypothesis does not...

02:34:36.831 --> 02:34:39.911
- It's not settled by any of
the large cardinal axioms.

02:34:39.991 --> 02:34:43.431
- Wow. Wow.

02:34:44.032 --> 02:34:47.212
What does that mean? How does that make
you feel? Will it ever be settled?

02:34:47.232 --> 02:34:51.212
- Yeah, well, it's part of my
multiverse view, I guess. So which

02:34:51.232 --> 02:34:55.171
we started by, I was describing
the universe view, which

02:34:55.212 --> 02:34:59.091
is the view that, look, there are
facts of the matter about all

02:34:59.152 --> 02:35:02.812
of these questions and that it will
turn out, if you're a universe view

02:35:02.821 --> 02:35:06.452
person, which I'm not, but if
you are, then you will hold

02:35:06.652 --> 02:35:10.471
that there is a right answer to the
continuum hypothesis question, and there's a

02:35:10.511 --> 02:35:14.372
right answer to the
large cardinal questions

02:35:14.411 --> 02:35:18.122
and so on. And that what we should
be aiming to do is figure out this

02:35:18.212 --> 02:35:24.612
one true set theory, okay? In
contrast I take the developments

02:35:24.712 --> 02:35:31.632
of set theory over the past half century or
more as evidence that there isn't such a

02:35:31.732 --> 02:35:34.532
unique set theoretic reality. Rather,

02:35:35.532 --> 02:35:39.421
what we've been doing for decades
now is producing more and

02:35:39.491 --> 02:35:43.052
more alternative set theoretic
universes in which the

02:35:43.062 --> 02:35:47.042
fundamental truths are differing
from one to the other. And that

02:35:47.091 --> 02:35:52.812
is the answer to the continuum
hypothesis question. The fact that

02:35:53.632 --> 02:35:57.532
given any model of set theory, there's
a forcing extension where the continuum

02:35:57.552 --> 02:36:01.452
hypothesis is true, and another one
where it's false. You can sort of

02:36:01.511 --> 02:36:05.271
turn it on and off like a light switch.
And that's the fundamental nature of the

02:36:05.292 --> 02:36:09.081
continuum hypothesis is that you can have
it or you can have the negation as you like

02:36:10.591 --> 02:36:14.331
within a very closely
related set theoretic world.

02:36:14.372 --> 02:36:18.142
Wherever you happen to be living,
there's a closely related one where

02:36:18.192 --> 02:36:21.972
CH is true, where the continuum
hypothesis is true, and one

02:36:22.032 --> 02:36:25.652
where it's false. And that
itself is a kind of answer.

02:36:25.712 --> 02:36:29.571
It's not a singularist
answer, a universe view

02:36:29.632 --> 02:36:33.571
answer. It's a pluralist answer. And this

02:36:33.632 --> 02:36:37.071
led me to my views on the
multiverse view of set theory and

02:36:37.112 --> 02:36:41.091
pluralist truth, namely the fundamental
nature of set theoretic truth

02:36:41.892 --> 02:36:44.202
has this plural character in that

02:36:45.372 --> 02:36:49.091
there isn't a singular meaning
to the fundamental terms, but

02:36:49.152 --> 02:36:53.091
rather, there's this choice of
alternative set-theoretic universes

02:36:53.192 --> 02:36:54.501
that have different truths.

02:36:55.091 --> 02:36:58.712
- So, what does the multiverse view
of mathematics enable you to

02:36:58.751 --> 02:37:02.771
do? What does it empower you to
do and what are the limitations?

02:37:02.792 --> 02:37:06.591
What are the things it breaks
about mathematics as a field, as a

02:37:06.771 --> 02:37:10.792
space of knowledge, and
what does it enable?

02:37:10.851 --> 02:37:14.071
- First of all, I guess one should say
that these different philosophical

02:37:14.132 --> 02:37:17.931
positions that you might take in the
philosophy of set theory, like the multiverse

02:37:18.010 --> 02:37:21.940
view or the universe view,
we don't ever disagree about

02:37:21.940 --> 02:37:25.862
the mathematics. We're all
agreeing on what the theorems are.

02:37:25.911 --> 02:37:29.872
It's a question of philosophical
perspective on the underlying meaning

02:37:29.911 --> 02:37:35.952
or the context, or really what is a
philosophy of mathematics for, right?

02:37:36.491 --> 02:37:40.472
And I mean, if you look back
in history, for example, like

02:37:40.632 --> 02:37:43.511
to the time of calculus with
Newton and Leibniz, right?

02:37:44.632 --> 02:37:51.532
They famously developed the ideas of calculus
using their concepts of infinitesimals,

02:37:51.632 --> 02:37:55.431
and those foundations
were roundly mocked by

02:37:55.452 --> 02:37:59.042
Bishop Berkeley and so on who talked
about, you know, what are these

02:37:59.091 --> 02:38:02.892
same evanescent increments,
and shall we not call them the

02:38:02.931 --> 02:38:06.671
ghosts of departed quantities? But the

02:38:06.751 --> 02:38:10.552
foundations really were kind of
completely suspect, I think,

02:38:10.632 --> 02:38:14.392
at the time. And that foundation

02:38:14.452 --> 02:38:17.692
of infinitesimal calculus really
only became rigorous in the

02:38:17.732 --> 02:38:21.261
1950s or so with the development
of non-standard analysis and

02:38:21.292 --> 02:38:24.872
Robinson's work. Okay, so the point
I'm trying to make is that, do you

02:38:24.952 --> 02:38:32.392
need a robust, rigorous foundation of
mathematics to make enduring insights in

02:38:32.402 --> 02:38:39.671
mathematics? And the answer,
regrettably, is apparently not because

02:38:39.751 --> 02:38:46.991
in calculus, even with that lousy, creaky
foundation of infinitesimals not even

02:38:47.751 --> 02:38:51.491
well understood that Newton and
Leibniz had, they proved all the

02:38:51.552 --> 02:38:56.542
fundamental theorems of calculus and,
you know, they had all the main insights

02:38:57.571 --> 02:39:00.491
in those early days
with that extremely bad

02:39:00.532 --> 02:39:07.176
foundation. And so that shows you something
about the relevance of the kind of

02:39:07.236 --> 02:39:11.216
foundational views on mathematics
and how important they are for

02:39:11.256 --> 02:39:15.196
mathematical developments and progress
and insight. I mean, because I

02:39:15.316 --> 02:39:18.016
view those early mathematical
developments in calculus as

02:39:18.696 --> 02:39:22.356
genuinely mathematical
and extremely important

02:39:23.076 --> 02:39:26.936
and insightful, even though the
foundations weren't any good,

02:39:27.016 --> 02:39:30.176
from, you know, by contemporary
perspectives. Okay.

02:39:30.216 --> 02:39:34.006
So, rather... So when it comes to
the philosophy of set theory and

02:39:34.036 --> 02:39:40.976
the dispute between the universe view and
the pluralism, my view is that the choice

02:39:41.036 --> 02:39:44.676
of the philosophical perspective
doesn't actually have to do with the

02:39:44.716 --> 02:39:48.646
mathematical developments
directly at all. Rather, it

02:39:48.696 --> 02:39:52.586
tells us, "Where should
set theory go? What

02:39:52.696 --> 02:39:56.436
kind of set theory should we
be looking at? What kind of

02:39:56.496 --> 02:40:00.476
questions should we be
asking?" So if you have a

02:40:00.576 --> 02:40:04.516
universe mentality, the
universe view, then you're

02:40:04.556 --> 02:40:08.366
gonna be pushed to try to
find and articulate the

02:40:08.516 --> 02:40:11.986
nature of the one true
set-theoretic universe.

02:40:12.656 --> 02:40:16.556
And I think that remark is really well
borne out by the developments with

02:40:16.596 --> 02:40:20.146
Hugh Woodin, who's one of the
most prominent mathematicians

02:40:20.896 --> 02:40:24.416
and philosophers with the universe
view and his theory of ultimate

02:40:24.676 --> 02:40:26.916
L and so on. And he's really striving.

02:40:26.936 --> 02:40:27.976
- Who was also your advisor.

02:40:28.016 --> 02:40:30.576
- He was also my supervisor.
My graduate supervisor.

02:40:30.596 --> 02:40:32.796
- Which is a, a personal story as well.

02:40:32.806 --> 02:40:36.696
- This, this fundamental dispute,
yeah, on this question.

02:40:37.116 --> 02:40:41.016
he is uh, has a very strong and successful

02:40:41.056 --> 02:40:44.996
research program, sort
of trying to give legs

02:40:45.036 --> 02:40:48.756
to finding the nature of
the one true set theoretic

02:40:48.836 --> 02:40:52.316
universe. And it's driving the
questions that he's asking and the

02:40:52.356 --> 02:40:55.976
mathematical programs that he's
pursuing. Whereas if you have a

02:40:56.016 --> 02:40:59.716
pluralist view, as I do,
then you're gonna be led and

02:40:59.756 --> 02:41:03.216
attracted to questions that have
to do with the interaction of

02:41:03.296 --> 02:41:06.916
different set theoretic
universes. Or maybe you wanna

02:41:06.976 --> 02:41:10.966
understand the nature of how are the
models of set theory related to their

02:41:10.976 --> 02:41:14.165
forcing extensions and so on.
And so this led to things,

02:41:14.276 --> 02:41:18.156
um that I call, say, set theoretic potentialism,
where you think about a set theoretic

02:41:18.196 --> 02:41:22.165
universe in a potentialist way. Not in

02:41:22.176 --> 02:41:26.146
the sense of potential infinity directly,
because all of these universes have

02:41:26.196 --> 02:41:29.526
infinite sets inside them already.
But they're potentialist in the sense

02:41:29.556 --> 02:41:33.356
that we could have more sets.
The universe could be wider

02:41:33.416 --> 02:41:37.216
and taller and so on, you
know, by forcing or by

02:41:37.276 --> 02:41:41.186
extending upward. And so we
wanna understand the nature of

02:41:41.256 --> 02:41:45.136
this realm of set theoretic universes.

02:41:45.156 --> 02:41:48.896
And, and that's quite some
exciting work. And so with

02:41:48.916 --> 02:41:52.256
Benedikt Loewe and I, we proved
some theorems on the modal logic of

02:41:52.436 --> 02:41:56.316
forcing and set theoretic potentialism
under end extension. I've done a bunch

02:41:56.376 --> 02:42:00.336
of work on this topic. And, and also I

02:42:00.436 --> 02:42:04.156
I mounted together with Gunter Fuchs and Jonas Riets, who
was one of my own PhD students, the topic of set theoretic

02:42:04.196 --> 02:42:08.186
my own PhD students, the
topic of set theoretic

02:42:08.276 --> 02:42:12.176
geology, which is studying...
It's taking the metaphor of

02:42:12.256 --> 02:42:15.336
forcing. I mean, in forcing, you have
the ground model and the forcing

02:42:15.396 --> 02:42:18.796
extension. And when I was
first working with Jonas

02:42:20.316 --> 02:42:23.396
he said, "I wanna undo forcing. I wanna go

02:42:23.456 --> 02:42:27.436
backwards." And I at first said,
"But Jonas, it doesn't work

02:42:27.476 --> 02:42:31.436
that way. You start in the model, in the ground
model, and you go out, you go to the bigger one.

02:42:31.456 --> 02:42:35.116
bigger one. You know, that's how forcing
works." And he said, "No, no, I wanna go

02:42:35.136 --> 02:42:38.896
backwards." And, and so he was
quite persistent, actually.

02:42:38.976 --> 02:42:42.776
And um, and so finally, I said,
"Okay, let's, let's do it. Let's

02:42:42.796 --> 02:42:46.196
take it seriously." And so we
sat down and, and s- and started

02:42:46.236 --> 02:42:50.116
thinking, you know, more precisely and
carefully and deeply about the nature

02:42:50.176 --> 02:42:53.616
of taking a set theoretic universe
and seeing where did it come

02:42:53.676 --> 02:42:58.416
from by forcing, which was a new way
of thinking about forcing at the time.

02:42:58.456 --> 02:43:00.416
- Like reverse engineering the forcing?

02:43:00.436 --> 02:43:03.976
- Yeah, something like that. Forcing
is a way of producing a new

02:43:04.056 --> 02:43:08.036
universe. And so you could start somewhere and
go to that new universe, or you could look

02:43:08.076 --> 02:43:12.496
where you are and say, "Well, look, I got
here by doing that already in the past."

02:43:12.556 --> 02:43:16.396
So we defined models of the bedrock model

02:43:16.496 --> 02:43:20.336
and ground, you know, sort of
undoing the forcing. And, and

02:43:20.396 --> 02:43:24.336
really, it was quite fruitful. And I view
this as part of the sort of pluralist

02:43:24.416 --> 02:43:28.236
perspective, except the difference
is that set theoretic geology is

02:43:28.296 --> 02:43:32.256
amenable to the universe
view. So even though the work

02:43:32.296 --> 02:43:39.656
was inspired by this philosophical view
on the multiverse view, nevertheless, the

02:43:39.716 --> 02:43:43.636
central ideas of geology
have now been picked up

02:43:43.676 --> 02:43:47.626
by the people with the research program
in the universe view. Because it turns

02:43:47.676 --> 02:43:51.616
out that set theoretic geology
is helping them or us to

02:43:51.876 --> 02:43:55.616
discover the nature of the one
true universe relates to its

02:43:55.716 --> 02:43:59.696
mantle. There's this concept of the set
theoretic mantle that I had introduced in

02:43:59.736 --> 02:44:03.136
a way that is extremely
interesting. And so it's

02:44:03.196 --> 02:44:06.976
historically quite funny, I think,
because this research program

02:44:07.016 --> 02:44:10.596
that grew entirely out of
the pluralist point of

02:44:10.656 --> 02:44:14.396
view ended up being picked up by the

02:44:14.456 --> 02:44:20.496
universe point of view research program
in a, in a way that is quite important.

02:44:20.576 --> 02:44:27.766
- Can you prove something in the world
that you arrived at through forcing and

02:44:27.796 --> 02:44:30.436
then take some of that
back to the ground model?

02:44:30.476 --> 02:44:34.456
- Yeah, absolutely. And that's a really powerful
argument method, actually. People often

02:44:34.536 --> 02:44:38.256
want to do that. Suppose
you're in some set theoretic

02:44:38.316 --> 02:44:41.436
context. You know, you could think
about as living in a set theoretic

02:44:41.496 --> 02:44:45.126
universe, and you want to prove
something in that universe only.

02:44:45.136 --> 02:44:49.036
But maybe one way to do it is to first

02:44:49.476 --> 02:44:53.276
construct this forcing extension
and then use the features

02:44:53.336 --> 02:44:57.096
about this forcing extension to realize
that certain things must have already been

02:44:57.156 --> 02:45:01.296
true in the ground model. And then you throw
the forcing extensions away and you...

02:45:01.376 --> 02:45:01.596
- Oh, cool

02:45:01.716 --> 02:45:05.016
- ...yeah. So this can happen.
To pick a more elementary

02:45:05.096 --> 02:45:08.876
example, if you think about
the early days of people

02:45:08.976 --> 02:45:14.016
reasoning with the complex numbers
before they really understood them.

02:45:14.036 --> 02:45:16.456
So they would have these algebraic
equations that they're trying to

02:45:16.516 --> 02:45:20.482
solve, you know, and they would
have the tools and methods of

02:45:20.512 --> 02:45:24.452
doing it, but then in the course of, you know, so
they would have to do things to the polynomial

02:45:24.492 --> 02:45:28.472
and change the factors and so on, and
produce other polynomials and solve them and

02:45:28.492 --> 02:45:32.271
so on. And sometimes, they
could produce solutions.

02:45:33.692 --> 02:45:37.532
in the middle of their construction,
they were led to, like, the

02:45:37.612 --> 02:45:40.872
square root of minus five or
something, you know, in the

02:45:40.912 --> 02:45:44.832
construction. And they didn't have
any meaning for that, but they

02:45:44.872 --> 02:45:48.692
would just do it symbolically,
you know. And, and

02:45:48.912 --> 02:45:52.832
eventually, it would turn in, you know,
because of the methods that they had, they

02:45:52.851 --> 02:45:56.732
would combine and they would cancel and so on, and
all the complex parts would cancel out and they'd end

02:45:56.812 --> 02:46:00.442
up with this, you know, actual answer,
you know, three plus square root of

02:46:00.452 --> 02:46:04.362
17 or whatever. And, and they could
check it and it worked. It was

02:46:04.412 --> 02:46:07.952
a solution of the original
equation. And so it must have been

02:46:08.012 --> 02:46:11.992
bewildering to them because they
would start with this question purely

02:46:12.032 --> 02:46:15.512
in the real numbers, an algebraic
question, and they would

02:46:15.792 --> 02:46:19.542
march on their method and proceed
through the land of nonsense, you

02:46:19.592 --> 02:46:23.472
know, with these square roots of
negative numbers and then end up with

02:46:23.512 --> 02:46:29.312
an answer that was real again that
they could verify was correct.

02:46:29.332 --> 02:46:33.252
And so, I view this kind of forcing
argument that I was just describing

02:46:33.292 --> 02:46:37.112
in a similar way. You start
in set theory, and you go to

02:46:37.122 --> 02:46:41.101
this land of nonsense in the forcing
extension, this imaginary world.

02:46:41.192 --> 02:46:45.132
And you argue and you come back. I mean,
you make a consequence in the ground model,

02:46:45.152 --> 02:46:47.592
and it's such a beautiful way of arguing.

02:46:47.652 --> 02:46:51.532
- So, speaking of the land of nonsense, I
have to ask you about surreal numbers, but

02:46:51.592 --> 02:46:53.332
first, I need another bathroom break.

02:46:54.512 --> 02:46:57.812
All right, we're back, and
there's this aforementioned

02:46:58.552 --> 02:47:02.412
wonderful blog post on
the surreal numbers, and

02:47:04.192 --> 02:47:07.972
that there's quite a simple
surreal number generation

02:47:08.072 --> 02:47:10.832
process that can basically
construct all numbers.

02:47:11.752 --> 02:47:15.472
So, maybe this is a good spot to ask,

02:47:15.652 --> 02:47:20.452
what are surreal numbers and what is
the way we can generate all numbers?

02:47:20.532 --> 02:47:24.072
- So, the surreal number
system is an amazing,

02:47:24.132 --> 02:47:30.372
amazingly beautiful mathematical system
that was introduced by John Conway.

02:47:30.412 --> 02:47:33.122
- Rest in peace, one of the great
mathematicians ever on this earth.

02:47:33.172 --> 02:47:37.032
- Yes, absolutely. And I really admire his

02:47:37.132 --> 02:47:41.012
style of mathematical thinking and
working in mathematics, and the

02:47:41.032 --> 02:47:44.792
surreal number system is a good instance
of this. So, the way I think about the

02:47:44.812 --> 02:47:48.712
surreal numbers system is what
it's doing is providing us

02:47:48.851 --> 02:47:52.681
a number system that unifies all
the other number systems. So, it

02:47:52.912 --> 02:47:56.532
extends the real numbers.
Well, not only, it extends the

02:47:56.592 --> 02:47:59.892
integers, the natural numbers and the integers
and the rational numbers, and the real

02:47:59.931 --> 02:48:03.351
numbers, but also the ordinals and the

02:48:03.392 --> 02:48:09.271
infinitesimals. So, they're all sitting
there inside the surreal numbers, and

02:48:10.271 --> 02:48:13.992
it's this colossal system
of numbers. It's not a

02:48:14.072 --> 02:48:17.832
set even. It's a proper class, it
turns out, because it contains all

02:48:17.892 --> 02:48:23.351
the ordinal numbers. But
it's generated from nothing

02:48:23.832 --> 02:48:27.672
by a single rule, and
the rule is, so we're

02:48:27.692 --> 02:48:31.612
gonna generate the numbers in
stages, in transfinite sequence of

02:48:31.712 --> 02:48:35.552
stages. And at every stage,
we take the numbers that we

02:48:35.632 --> 02:48:39.282
have so far and in all possible
ways, we divide them into

02:48:39.392 --> 02:48:43.282
two sets, a lower set and an
upper set, or a left set and

02:48:43.312 --> 02:48:47.222
a right set. So we divide them
into these two sets, so that

02:48:47.271 --> 02:48:51.092
everything in the left set is less than
everything in the right set, and then at that

02:48:51.152 --> 02:48:56.392
moment, we create a new
number that fits in the gap

02:48:56.632 --> 02:49:03.672
between L and R. Okay? That's it. That's
all we do. So, let me say it again.

02:49:05.292 --> 02:49:08.312
The rule is, we proceed
in stages, and at any

02:49:08.431 --> 02:49:12.112
stage, then in all possible
ways, we divide the

02:49:12.152 --> 02:49:14.892
numbers we have into two collections,

02:49:16.012 --> 02:49:19.692
the left set and the right set, so that everything
in the left set is less than everything in the right

02:49:19.752 --> 02:49:27.252
set. And we create a new number, a new
surreal number that will fit in that gap.

02:49:27.332 --> 02:49:31.242
Okay. So, for example, we could start... At
the beginning, we don't have any numbers.

02:49:31.271 --> 02:49:35.072
We haven't created anything
yet, and so, well,

02:49:35.712 --> 02:49:39.452
we could take nothing, and we could
divide it into two sets, the empty lower

02:49:39.551 --> 02:49:43.212
set and the empty upper set.
I mean, the two empty sets.

02:49:43.892 --> 02:49:47.632
And everything in the empty set is less than
everything in the empty set because that's a vacuous

02:49:47.672 --> 02:49:51.552
statement. So we satisfy the conditions,

02:49:51.612 --> 02:49:55.572
and we apply the number generation
rule, which says we should create

02:49:55.632 --> 02:49:59.072
a new number. And this is
what I call the Big Bang of

02:49:59.192 --> 02:50:02.972
numbers, the surreal genesis
when the number zero is

02:50:03.012 --> 02:50:06.952
born. Zero is the firstborn
number that is bigger than

02:50:07.012 --> 02:50:09.632
everything in the empty set and
less than everything in the empty

02:50:09.752 --> 02:50:13.412
set. Okay, but now we have
this number zero, and so

02:50:13.472 --> 02:50:17.452
therefore, we now can define new gaps.

02:50:17.492 --> 02:50:21.392
Because if we put zero into
the left set and have an

02:50:21.452 --> 02:50:25.351
empty right set, then we should create
a new number that's bigger than

02:50:25.452 --> 02:50:29.372
zero and less than everything in the empty
set, and that number is called the number

02:50:29.492 --> 02:50:35.632
one. And similarly, at that same stage, we
could have put zero into the right set,

02:50:36.572 --> 02:50:40.052
and so that would be the firstborn number
that's less than zero, which is called

02:50:40.252 --> 02:50:43.812
minus one. So now we have
three numbers, minus one,

02:50:43.851 --> 02:50:47.771
zero and one, and they have four gaps
because there could be a number below

02:50:47.812 --> 02:50:51.332
minus one or between minus one
and zero or between zero and one

02:50:51.851 --> 02:50:55.492
or above one, and so we
create those four new

02:50:55.612 --> 02:50:59.512
numbers. The first number above one is called
two. The first number between zero and one

02:50:59.572 --> 02:51:03.392
is called 1/2, and then on the negative
side, we have minus 1/2 and minus

02:51:03.452 --> 02:51:07.351
two and so on. So now we have,
what is that, seven numbers?

02:51:07.412 --> 02:51:11.252
seven numbers. So there's eight
gaps between them. So at the next

02:51:11.532 --> 02:51:15.172
birthday, they call them, the next
stage will be born all the numbers

02:51:15.212 --> 02:51:18.592
between those gaps, and then between
those and between those and so

02:51:18.692 --> 02:51:21.922
on. And as the days progress,
we get more and more

02:51:21.931 --> 02:51:25.804
numbers, but those are just the finite
birthdays, because as I said, it's a

02:51:25.864 --> 02:51:29.744
transfinite process. So
at day omega, that's the

02:51:29.804 --> 02:51:33.444
first infinite day, we're
going to create a lot of

02:51:33.503 --> 02:51:37.294
new surreal numbers. So
every real number will

02:51:37.324 --> 02:51:41.104
be born at that stage because
every real number fills a

02:51:41.144 --> 02:51:44.884
gap in the previously born rational
numbers that we had just talked

02:51:44.944 --> 02:51:48.824
about. It's not all the rationals, because
actually the rational numbers that are born at the

02:51:48.864 --> 02:51:52.704
finite stages are just the rationals
whose denominator is a power of

02:51:52.884 --> 02:51:56.083
two, it turns out. Those are
called the dyadic rationals.

02:51:56.204 --> 02:51:59.784
So the real numbers are
all born on day omega,

02:51:59.844 --> 02:52:03.344
but also some other numbers
are born on day omega, namely,

02:52:04.583 --> 02:52:08.524
the ordinal omega itself is the firstborn
number that's bigger than all those

02:52:08.583 --> 02:52:12.364
finite numbers, and minus
omega is the firstborn number

02:52:12.424 --> 02:52:16.384
that's less than all those finite
numbers. But also, we have

02:52:16.424 --> 02:52:20.144
the number epsilon, which is the firstborn
number that's strictly bigger than

02:52:20.224 --> 02:52:23.864
zero and strictly less than
all the positive rational

02:52:24.044 --> 02:52:27.333
numbers. So that's going to be
an infinitesimal number in that

02:52:27.444 --> 02:52:31.264
gap, and so on. On day omega plus one, we

02:52:31.304 --> 02:52:35.194
get more numbers, and then omega plus two
and so on. And the numbers just keep coming

02:52:35.224 --> 02:52:38.414
forever. So, this is how you
build the surreal number

02:52:38.503 --> 02:52:42.304
system. And then it turns out
you can define the arithmetic

02:52:42.354 --> 02:52:46.344
operations of addition and
multiplication in a natural way that

02:52:46.424 --> 02:52:49.564
is engaging with this recursive
definition. So we have sort of

02:52:50.144 --> 02:52:53.864
recursive definitions of
plus and times for the

02:52:53.904 --> 02:52:57.244
surreal numbers. And it
turns out you can prove

02:52:57.284 --> 02:53:01.154
that they make the surreal numbers
into what's called an ordered

02:53:01.304 --> 02:53:05.124
field. So they satisfy the field axioms,
which means that you have distributivity

02:53:05.164 --> 02:53:09.114
and commutativity of
addition and multiplication.

02:53:09.144 --> 02:53:12.604
multiplication, and also
you have reciprocals for

02:53:12.614 --> 02:53:16.574
every non-zero number. You can
divide by the number. So you can add

02:53:16.604 --> 02:53:20.464
and multiply and divide and subtract.
And furthermore, you can take

02:53:20.484 --> 02:53:26.364
square roots. And furthermore, every
odd degree polynomial has a root,

02:53:27.404 --> 02:53:30.883
which is true in the real numbers, because
if you think about, say, a cubic or a

02:53:31.304 --> 02:53:35.024
fifth degree polynomial, then
you know it's going to cross the

02:53:35.144 --> 02:53:38.644
axis, because it has opposite
behaviors on the two

02:53:38.704 --> 02:53:42.613
infinities, because it's an odd degree
polynomial. So on the positive side,

02:53:42.644 --> 02:53:46.424
it's going to the positive infinity. On the
negative side, it would be going to minus infinity.

02:53:46.464 --> 02:53:49.664
So it has to cross. So we
know in the real numbers,

02:53:49.764 --> 02:53:53.664
every odd degree
polynomial has a root. And

02:53:53.724 --> 02:53:57.684
that's also true in the surreal numbers.
So that makes it what's called a

02:53:57.724 --> 02:54:01.664
real closed field, which is a
very nice mathematical theory.

02:54:02.184 --> 02:54:06.124
So it's really quite interesting
how we can find copies

02:54:06.164 --> 02:54:09.344
of all these other number systems
inside the surreal numbers.

02:54:09.384 --> 02:54:12.744
- But the surreal numbers are fundamentally
discontinuous as you're worried about.

02:54:12.784 --> 02:54:14.224
What are the consequences of this?

02:54:14.304 --> 02:54:18.083
- Right. So the surreal numbers
have a property that they form

02:54:18.304 --> 02:54:23.484
a non-standard model of the
real field, which means that

02:54:24.524 --> 02:54:28.024
they provide a notion of infinitesimality
that one can use to develop

02:54:28.104 --> 02:54:31.824
calculus on the grounds of Robinson's
non-standard theory that I had

02:54:31.864 --> 02:54:35.724
mentioned earlier. But they don't have

02:54:35.744 --> 02:54:39.604
the least upper bound property
for subcollections. There's

02:54:39.824 --> 02:54:43.804
no set of surreal numbers, no
non-trivial set of surreal numbers

02:54:43.864 --> 02:54:47.733
has at least upper bound, and there
are no convergent sequences in

02:54:47.764 --> 02:54:51.384
the surreal numbers. And so
for the sort of ordinary

02:54:51.464 --> 02:54:54.733
use in calculus based on limits and

02:54:54.824 --> 02:54:58.804
convergence, that method does
not work in the surreal numbers

02:54:58.824 --> 02:55:02.144
at all. So that's what I mean when I say
the surreal numbers are fundamentally

02:55:02.164 --> 02:55:05.664
discontinuous. They have a
fundamental discontinuity going

02:55:05.744 --> 02:55:09.124
on. But you can still do calculus
with them, because you have

02:55:09.164 --> 02:55:12.414
infinitesimals if you
use these non-standard

02:55:12.503 --> 02:55:16.444
methods, the infinitesimal-based
methods to calculus. And

02:55:16.484 --> 02:55:20.344
people do that. I once organized a

02:55:20.424 --> 02:55:24.344
conference in New York, and we had John Conway
as a speaker at that conference. And there

02:55:24.384 --> 02:55:28.274
was a question session, and
someone asked him, I mean,

02:55:28.304 --> 02:55:32.144
it's a bit rude, I think, but they

02:55:32.224 --> 02:55:36.044
asked it and the question
was, "What is your greatest

02:55:36.104 --> 02:55:40.023
disappointment in life?" I mean, I would never
ask a question like that at a conference

02:55:40.083 --> 02:55:43.664
in a very public setting. But
Conway was extremely graceful,

02:55:44.424 --> 02:55:46.544
and he answered by saying that,

02:55:47.404 --> 02:55:51.364
"The surreal numbers..." Not the
numbers themselves, but the reception

02:55:51.424 --> 02:55:55.304
of the surreal numbers, because
he had ambition that the

02:55:55.344 --> 02:55:59.144
surreal numbers would
become a fundamental number

02:55:59.244 --> 02:56:04.744
system used throughout mathematics and
science, because it was able to do

02:56:05.564 --> 02:56:09.444
non-set analysis, it was able to do calculus,
it unified the ordinals and so on. And it's

02:56:09.464 --> 02:56:13.364
such a unifying, amazing
structure, beautiful structure

02:56:13.844 --> 02:56:17.644
with elegant proofs and
sophisticated ideas all around

02:56:17.684 --> 02:56:25.364
it. And he was disappointed that it
never really achieved that unifying

02:56:25.424 --> 02:56:29.364
status that he had the
ambition for. And this,

02:56:29.424 --> 02:56:31.984
he mentioned as his
greatest disappointment.

02:56:32.024 --> 02:56:36.124
- Yeah, Donald Knuth tried to celebrate
it. It never quite took hold.

02:56:36.184 --> 02:56:40.083
- So I don't want to give the impression though
that the surreal numbers are not widely studied,

02:56:40.124 --> 02:56:41.794
because there are thousands
of people who are...

02:56:41.844 --> 02:56:41.984
- Sure

02:56:42.003 --> 02:56:45.964
- ...studying it. In fact, Philip Ehrlich,
who is one of the world experts on

02:56:45.984 --> 02:56:49.964
the surreal numbers, mentioned to
me once that Conway was his own

02:56:50.003 --> 02:56:53.083
worst enemy with regard to
that very issue, because

02:56:54.024 --> 02:56:57.644
in the Conway style,
everything is a game. And he

02:56:57.724 --> 02:57:00.503
treated the surreal numbers
as a kind of plaything, a

02:57:00.624 --> 02:57:04.364
toy, and maybe that makes people

02:57:04.384 --> 02:57:07.744
not take it seriously.
Although my view is that it is

02:57:07.804 --> 02:57:11.604
extremely serious, useful, and profound,

02:57:11.684 --> 02:57:15.624
and I've been writing a whole series
of essays on the surreal numbers for

02:57:15.664 --> 02:57:20.824
my Substack at Infinitely More. And
I just find the whole subject so

02:57:20.904 --> 02:57:24.508
fascinating and beautiful.
I mean, it's true. I'm not

02:57:24.548 --> 02:57:30.568
applying it in engineering, which maybe
was part of this Conway ambition.

02:57:30.648 --> 02:57:32.728
- And I just wanted to,
before I forget, mention

02:57:34.248 --> 02:57:38.168
the Conway, turning everything
into a game. It is a fascinating

02:57:38.208 --> 02:57:41.888
point that I didn't quite think about,
which I think the Game of Life is just an

02:57:41.928 --> 02:57:45.788
example of exploration of cellular automata.
I think cellular automata is one of the

02:57:45.828 --> 02:57:49.788
most incredible, complicated,
fascinating... It feels like an

02:57:49.888 --> 02:57:53.788
open door into a world we have not
quite yet explored. And it's such

02:57:53.908 --> 02:57:57.108
a beautiful illustration of that world,
the Game of Life, but calling it a

02:57:57.148 --> 02:58:01.088
game, maybe life balances it,
'cause that's your powerful word,

02:58:01.128 --> 02:58:04.328
but it's not quite a
game. It's a fascinating

02:58:04.408 --> 02:58:08.218
invitation to an incredibly complicated
and fascinating mathematical

02:58:08.268 --> 02:58:12.248
world. I think every time I see
cellular automata and the fact that

02:58:12.268 --> 02:58:16.188
we don't quite have mathematical
tools to make sense

02:58:16.208 --> 02:58:20.168
of that world, it fills me with awe.
Speaking of a thousand years from

02:58:20.228 --> 02:58:23.988
now, it feels like that is a world
we might make some progress on.

02:58:23.998 --> 02:58:27.567
- The Game of Life is a sort of
playground for computably undecidable

02:58:27.628 --> 02:58:31.528
questions because in fact,
you can prove that the

02:58:31.608 --> 02:58:35.568
question of whether a given
cell will ever become alive

02:58:36.548 --> 02:58:39.288
is computably undecidable. In other words,

02:58:39.348 --> 02:58:43.328
given a configuration and you ask,
"Will this particular cell ever

02:58:43.348 --> 02:58:49.618
you know, be alive?" "...in the
evolution?" And you can prove that that

02:58:49.708 --> 02:58:53.168
question is equivalent to the
Halting Problem. It's computably

02:58:53.208 --> 02:58:57.198
undecidable. It's semi-decidable
in the sense that if it will

02:58:57.248 --> 02:59:01.008
become alive, then you will know it at a
finite stage because you could just run the

02:59:01.688 --> 02:59:05.468
Game of Life algorithm and let
it run. And if it ever did come

02:59:05.508 --> 02:59:09.388
alive, you could say, "Yeah, it was alive."
But if you've run it for a thousand

02:59:09.468 --> 02:59:13.388
years and it hasn't come alive yet,
then you don't necessarily seem to

02:59:13.428 --> 02:59:16.988
have any basis for saying, "No, it won't
ever come alive" if the behavior was very

02:59:17.008 --> 02:59:18.048
complicated.

02:59:18.088 --> 02:59:21.968
Maybe if you have a complete understanding of
the evolution of the behavior, then you can say

02:59:22.008 --> 02:59:25.228
no, but you can prove you won't
always have that understanding-

02:59:25.238 --> 02:59:28.088
... precisely because the problem is
equivalent to the halting problem.

02:59:28.148 --> 02:59:31.808
- And nevertheless, when you sit back
and look and visualize the thing, some

02:59:31.848 --> 02:59:35.797
little mini cellular automata
civilizations are born and die quickly,

02:59:35.848 --> 02:59:39.758
and some are very predictable
and boring, but some have this

02:59:39.808 --> 02:59:43.428
rich incredible complexity. And maybe that

02:59:43.528 --> 02:59:48.858
speaks to a thing I wanted to ask on
the halting problem and decidability.

02:59:50.028 --> 02:59:53.948
You've mentioned this thing where if
you understand the program deeply, you

02:59:54.008 --> 02:59:57.788
might be able to say something. So
can we say something interesting

02:59:57.888 --> 03:00:01.648
about maybe once statistically
how many programs

03:00:02.648 --> 03:00:06.268
we know something about in terms of whether
they halt or not? Or what does it mean to

03:00:06.288 --> 03:00:11.248
understand a program deeply enough
to be able to make a prediction?

03:00:11.268 --> 03:00:15.308
- The main lesson of
computability theory in my view

03:00:16.708 --> 03:00:22.188
is that it's never the case
that you can have a thorough

03:00:22.268 --> 03:00:25.808
understanding of the behavior
of a program by looking at the

03:00:25.828 --> 03:00:29.778
program, and that the content
of what you learn from

03:00:29.788 --> 03:00:33.648
a program, I mean, in the most general
case, is always obtained just by

03:00:33.728 --> 03:00:37.368
running it and looking
at the behavior. And the

03:00:37.508 --> 03:00:41.408
proof of that is there's a theorem
called Rice's Theorem, which

03:00:41.468 --> 03:00:48.408
makes that idea completely robust. But I
want to just take a little detour towards

03:00:48.468 --> 03:00:51.768
another question riffing
on something that you just

03:00:51.808 --> 03:00:55.748
said. Namely, one can ask the question,

03:00:55.868 --> 03:00:59.858
What is the behavior of
a random program? So you

03:00:59.908 --> 03:01:03.898
have some formal computing language, you
know, and you want to, you know, look

03:01:03.928 --> 03:01:07.628
at the collection of all programs of a
certain size. Maybe there's only finitely

03:01:07.688 --> 03:01:09.188
many. And

03:01:10.108 --> 03:01:13.988
can you say something about the behavior
of a randomly chosen one, like with a

03:01:14.008 --> 03:01:17.978
certain likelihood it will have a certain
behavior? And the answer turns out

03:01:18.008 --> 03:01:21.628
to be extremely interesting.
Once years ago,

03:01:21.668 --> 03:01:25.308
Alexey Myasnikov asked me a
question. He had this concept of a

03:01:25.408 --> 03:01:28.388
decision problem with a black
hole, and what that means is

03:01:29.408 --> 03:01:32.968
it's a decision problem which is
possibly difficult in the worst

03:01:33.008 --> 03:01:36.788
case, but the difficulty
was concentrated in a very

03:01:36.848 --> 03:01:42.668
tiny region called the black hole. And
outside of that black hole, it was very easy.

03:01:42.677 --> 03:01:46.128
And so, for example, this kind of
problem is a terrible problem to use if

03:01:46.168 --> 03:01:50.118
you're basing your encryption
scheme, you know, you don't

03:01:50.128 --> 03:01:53.908
want to use a black hole problem
because if someone can rob the bank

03:01:54.128 --> 03:01:57.988
95% of the time, you know,
then that's not what you want,

03:01:58.008 --> 03:02:01.508
or even any non-trivial percent
of the time is too dangerous.

03:02:01.528 --> 03:02:08.088
So you don't want to use problems that
are, you know, almost every case is easily

03:02:08.388 --> 03:02:12.188
solved as the basis of your
encryption. And the question Alexey

03:02:12.228 --> 03:02:15.768
asked me was, "Does the
halting problem have a black

03:02:15.828 --> 03:02:19.668
hole?" You know? And so if we
take, say, the standard model of

03:02:19.688 --> 03:02:23.618
Turing machines, it's one-way
infinite tape with zeros

03:02:23.628 --> 03:02:27.468
and ones on the tape and so on, the head
moving back and forth, and you know, it

03:02:27.548 --> 03:02:31.448
stops when it gets into the
halt state, then it turns

03:02:31.548 --> 03:02:35.328
out we proved that there is
a black hole. And what that

03:02:35.368 --> 03:02:38.968
means is there's a computer
procedure that decides correctly

03:02:39.288 --> 03:02:43.008
almost every instance of the halting problem.
Even though the halting problem is not

03:02:43.068 --> 03:02:47.008
decidable, we can decide almost
every instance. So, more

03:02:47.028 --> 03:02:50.608
precisely, there's a collection
of Turing machine programs

03:02:51.608 --> 03:02:55.418
such that we can easily decide
whether a program's in that

03:02:55.488 --> 03:02:59.228
collection or not. And for the
programs in the collection,

03:02:59.328 --> 03:03:02.368
we can decide the halting
problem for those programs

03:03:02.568 --> 03:03:06.428
easily. And furthermore,
almost every program is

03:03:06.528 --> 03:03:10.458
in the collection in the sense that as
the number of states goes to, you know,

03:03:10.488 --> 03:03:17.988
becomes large, the proportion of
programs in the collection goes to 100%.

03:03:18.428 --> 03:03:23.028
So the asymptotic density
of the programs is one.

03:03:23.048 --> 03:03:26.908
And the proof was quite fascinating
because it's one of these situations where

03:03:26.948 --> 03:03:30.908
the theorem sounds really surprising, I
think, to many people when I first tell it,

03:03:30.928 --> 03:03:34.588
I mean, to computability
experts. Then it's sort of

03:03:34.648 --> 03:03:38.368
intriguing to think that you can solve
almost every instance of a halting

03:03:38.408 --> 03:03:42.048
problem. But then when
they hear the proof, it's

03:03:42.088 --> 03:03:47.908
completely a letdown. Unfortunately,
nobody likes the theorem after the proof.

03:03:47.948 --> 03:03:50.978
And so the proof is so simple,

03:03:50.978 --> 03:03:54.208
though. If you know how a Turing
machine operates, there's this infinite

03:03:54.288 --> 03:03:57.988
paper tape on which the machine writes
zeros and ones, and the head moves

03:03:58.028 --> 03:04:01.308
back and forth according to rigid
instructions. And the instructions are

03:04:01.368 --> 03:04:05.228
all of the form,

03:04:05.967 --> 03:04:09.908
if the machine is in such and such a state
and it's reading such and such symbol

03:04:09.967 --> 03:04:13.887
on the tape, then it should write
this symbol on the tape and it should

03:04:13.948 --> 03:04:17.908
change to this new state specified, and
it should either move left or right

03:04:17.967 --> 03:04:24.608
as specified. So a program consists of
instructions like that. If you look at,

03:04:25.448 --> 03:04:29.268
If you look at a program, you know, one of
the states is the halt state and that's

03:04:29.308 --> 03:04:34.428
when the program halts. But you
can calculate how many programs

03:04:35.808 --> 03:04:38.848
don't have any instruction
that transitions to the halt

03:04:38.967 --> 03:04:42.848
state. You can easily
calculate the proportion. And

03:04:42.887 --> 03:04:46.848
in the limit, it goes to 1
over E squared, 13 and a half

03:04:46.868 --> 03:04:50.387
percent. If you calculate the limit, the

03:04:50.428 --> 03:04:54.228
proportion of programs
with end states that don't

03:04:54.308 --> 03:04:58.368
ever halt because they don't have
any instruction saying halt.

03:04:58.788 --> 03:05:02.467
Those programs obviously never halt because
they can't halt. They don't have any

03:05:02.478 --> 03:05:03.948
instruction that says halt.

03:05:04.008 --> 03:05:06.648
- So 13% of programs, you could say,

03:05:06.668 --> 03:05:10.048
- 13%, you can say they don't halt, because you
just look at them and you can understand them.

03:05:10.348 --> 03:05:11.258
- There's no halt state.

03:05:11.258 --> 03:05:13.887
- There's no... They never change to
the halt state, so they can't halt.

03:05:13.928 --> 03:05:17.188
- I mean, that nevertheless
is beautiful to know.

03:05:17.228 --> 03:05:21.028
- So that's a kind of trivial
reason for non-halting, you know.

03:05:21.048 --> 03:05:24.328
And when I first made that observation,
I thought, "Okay, this is the proof

03:05:24.408 --> 03:05:28.338
strategy." Because we wanted...
I wanted to say at first the

03:05:28.408 --> 03:05:32.248
goal was, look, that's a stupid
reason for a program not to

03:05:32.288 --> 03:05:37.198
halt. And I just want to pile up as many
stupid reasons as I can think of...

03:05:37.198 --> 03:05:43.458
...until it gets more than
50%, and then I can say most.

03:05:43.608 --> 03:05:43.798
- That was brilliant.

03:05:43.798 --> 03:05:44.368
- Yeah. That was my goal.

03:05:44.408 --> 03:05:45.048
- I love this.

03:05:45.108 --> 03:05:48.517
- Yeah. So we thought more about
it, though, and we hit the

03:05:48.608 --> 03:05:52.508
jackpot because we found one
gigantic stupid reason that

03:05:52.568 --> 03:06:00.288
converged to 100%. I mean, in the
limit. And so, the stupid reason for a

03:06:00.308 --> 03:06:04.048
program not to halt is that,
well, if you think about

03:06:04.387 --> 03:06:07.808
the behavior, see, the head is sitting
there. It's on the leftmost cell of the

03:06:07.848 --> 03:06:10.648
tape at the very beginning.
It's in the start

03:06:10.748 --> 03:06:14.528
state, and the head is following an
instruction. And the instruction says,

03:06:14.988 --> 03:06:18.788
"When you're in the start state," which it is,
"and you're reading something on the tape,

03:06:18.868 --> 03:06:22.768
then you should write something and you should
change to a new state, and you should either move

03:06:22.808 --> 03:06:26.748
left or right." But
half of them move left.

03:06:27.988 --> 03:06:31.088
But if you move left and you are
already at the end, then the head falls

03:06:31.208 --> 03:06:35.748
off. And so the computation stops
because the head fell off the tape.

03:06:37.168 --> 03:06:40.628
That's a pretty stupid reason. Okay, but
that's half of them already just like

03:06:40.688 --> 03:06:44.148
that. Okay, and then some of them
went right, and they changed to a new

03:06:44.308 --> 03:06:48.238
state. And amongst those, you know, the new
state, half of those ones are going left and

03:06:48.288 --> 03:06:52.268
half are going right from that
place, and then most of those are

03:06:52.308 --> 03:06:56.028
changing to a new state. When there's a lot of
states, it's very likely that the next state that you

03:06:56.048 --> 03:06:59.837
transition to is new. And so you get this

03:06:59.887 --> 03:07:03.668
random walk behavior, if you know what that
means, where half go left and half go right at

03:07:03.728 --> 03:07:07.508
each step. And there's a
theorem due to Pólya which is

03:07:07.548 --> 03:07:11.508
called the Pólya recurrence
theorem, which says when you have

03:07:11.548 --> 03:07:15.028
a random walk, a one-dimensional
random walk, then it's very

03:07:15.108 --> 03:07:18.848
likely to come back to where you
started. And when that happens for

03:07:18.908 --> 03:07:22.318
us, then half of them from that
place fall off on the next step.

03:07:23.728 --> 03:07:27.628
And so you can show using
this kind of analysis that

03:07:28.248 --> 03:07:32.088
the probability one behavior
of a random Turing machine is

03:07:32.148 --> 03:07:35.488
that the head falls off the
tape before it repeats a

03:07:35.568 --> 03:07:39.518
state. And that is the stupid proof that

03:07:39.548 --> 03:07:42.688
shows how to solve the halting problem. Because when
that happens, we can answer the halting problem

03:07:42.768 --> 03:07:46.688
saying, "No, the computation stopped
because the machine crashed, not because

03:07:46.728 --> 03:07:50.458
it halted, so therefore it
doesn't count as halting on some

03:07:50.528 --> 03:07:54.288
accounts." Or, you know, if you want to
define that as halting, crashing as halting,

03:07:54.308 --> 03:07:58.288
then... But in any case, however it is
that you set up your formalism, you're

03:07:58.308 --> 03:08:01.217
going to be able to answer the
question for the behavior of the

03:08:01.217 --> 03:08:03.887
machine when the head falls off.

03:08:03.967 --> 03:08:08.208
- So statistically, in the limit,
you solve the halting problem.

03:08:08.268 --> 03:08:11.578
- Yes, exactly. Computably solve it. Yeah.

03:08:11.928 --> 03:08:15.308
- What do we take from that? Because
you didn't solve the halting problem.

03:08:15.408 --> 03:08:17.688
- No, it's impossible to fully solve...

03:08:17.698 --> 03:08:19.818
...the halting problem
correctly in all cases.

03:08:20.088 --> 03:08:22.217
- That's pretty cool. That's kind of...
I mean, I don't know. This is...

03:08:22.217 --> 03:08:26.188
- It's a probabilistic way... I mean,
it's probabilistic in the sense that

03:08:26.228 --> 03:08:28.868
we're solving almost all instances...

03:08:28.878 --> 03:08:32.788
...computably. There are versions of
this that are maybe more interesting

03:08:32.828 --> 03:08:36.128
from the point of view of complexity theory
and actually useful. I mean, there's the whole

03:08:36.268 --> 03:08:39.868
P-NP problem and so on. And
there's this genre of NP-complete

03:08:39.967 --> 03:08:42.858
problems, which are problems that are

03:08:42.908 --> 03:08:46.898
infeasible. They would take
exponential time to solve them in

03:08:46.948 --> 03:08:50.878
the ordinary way. And they're not
known to be polynomial time solvable,

03:08:50.948 --> 03:08:54.438
although in these cases it's an open
question whether there is a polynomial time

03:08:54.628 --> 03:09:01.328
algorithm, a feasible algorithm. And
for most for most of the NP-complete

03:09:01.338 --> 03:09:04.788
problems, you can prove that there's a

03:09:04.848 --> 03:09:08.998
polynomial time approximation that
solves almost all instances...

03:09:09.008 --> 03:09:12.768
...in a feasible amount of time. So
like the knapsack problem, you know,

03:09:12.828 --> 03:09:16.168
packing problems, and so on, other kinds
of problems, satisfaction problems,

03:09:16.248 --> 03:09:20.008
when... Depending on how you set
up the formalism, you can prove,

03:09:20.048 --> 03:09:23.948
and I've proven many
instances of this but also I

03:09:23.988 --> 03:09:27.708
think it's widespread for
almost all the NP-complete

03:09:27.788 --> 03:09:31.568
problems, the difficult problems, and these
are important problems for industrial

03:09:31.608 --> 03:09:36.708
application when these are problems that
we actually want to solve. We can have

03:09:37.408 --> 03:09:41.528
feasible algorithms that solve
almost every instance of them.

03:09:42.003 --> 03:09:45.964
- The amount of fields and topics
you've worked on is truly

03:09:45.983 --> 03:09:49.964
incredible. I have to ask about P
versus NP. This is one of the big

03:09:50.044 --> 03:09:53.764
open problems in complexity theory. So for
people who don't know, it's about the relation

03:09:53.823 --> 03:09:57.223
between computation time and problem
complexity. Do you think it will ever be

03:09:57.284 --> 03:10:02.624
solved? And is there any chance
the weird counterintuitive

03:10:03.663 --> 03:10:06.223
thing might be true that P equals NP?

03:10:06.264 --> 03:10:09.903
- Yeah, that's an interesting question.
Sometimes people ask about whether it could be

03:10:09.983 --> 03:10:14.903
independent, which I think is... ...An
interesting question for logicians.

03:10:15.024 --> 03:10:18.983
And of course, well, one has
to say if you're entertaining

03:10:19.003 --> 03:10:22.933
the idea of independence, you
know, over which theory? Because

03:10:23.003 --> 03:10:26.243
every statement is going to be
independent over an extremely weak

03:10:26.303 --> 03:10:29.854
theory. So that's, you know, it doesn't
make sense to say it's independent all by

03:10:29.864 --> 03:10:33.764
itself. You're only independent relative
to a theory, right? So the way I think

03:10:33.823 --> 03:10:39.733
about P-NP is that... I mean, of course
it's a theoretical question about

03:10:40.663 --> 03:10:44.524
the asymptotic behavior of
these problems. I mean, for a

03:10:44.563 --> 03:10:48.524
problem to be in P means that there,
you know, there is a computable

03:10:48.563 --> 03:10:52.284
decision procedure that
runs in time bounded by

03:10:52.364 --> 03:10:55.083
some polynomial. But the coefficients
on that polynomial could be

03:10:55.143 --> 03:11:02.684
enormous, and the degree could be
incredibly high. And so for small values of

03:11:02.723 --> 03:11:06.524
inputs, then it doesn't make sense
to talk about this polynomial

03:11:06.583 --> 03:11:10.544
time feasibility with respect to, say,
the range of problem inputs that we will

03:11:10.643 --> 03:11:14.614
ever give it in our lifetime or in

03:11:14.643 --> 03:11:18.384
the span of human civilization or
whatever. I mean, because it's an

03:11:18.444 --> 03:11:22.223
asymptotic property, it's
really in the limit as the

03:11:22.264 --> 03:11:26.104
size of the inputs goes to infinity,
that's the only time that polynomial

03:11:26.143 --> 03:11:29.934
or NP becomes relevant. And so maybe it's

03:11:29.964 --> 03:11:32.204
important to keep that in
mind when. Sometimes you find

03:11:33.223 --> 03:11:37.163
kind of overblown remarks
made about, you know, if P

03:11:37.204 --> 03:11:41.163
equals NP, then this will be incredibly
important for human civilization

03:11:41.204 --> 03:11:44.954
because it means that we'll have feasible
algorithms for solving these incredibly important-

03:11:45.444 --> 03:11:49.163
... problems in NP. You
know, that it would

03:11:49.243 --> 03:11:52.983
cause immense wealth for human
societies and so on because we

03:11:53.024 --> 03:11:56.934
would be able to solve these
otherwise intractable problems, and

03:11:56.964 --> 03:12:00.864
that would be the basis of new
technology and industry and so forth. I

03:12:00.903 --> 03:12:03.424
mean, people make these
kind of remarks, but-

03:12:03.444 --> 03:12:03.764
- Of course

03:12:04.083 --> 03:12:07.764
- ... you have to temper those
remarks by the realization

03:12:07.844 --> 03:12:11.733
that P and P equal NP
or P not equal NP are

03:12:11.784 --> 03:12:15.313
not about these practical things
at all because of the asymptotic

03:12:15.344 --> 03:12:19.134
nature of the question itself.

03:12:19.184 --> 03:12:22.503
Okay, that's on the one hand. But on
the second hand, we already have the

03:12:22.563 --> 03:12:26.464
algorithm, so we could use it already,
except it's a terrible algorithm because

03:12:26.544 --> 03:12:30.044
it involves all this incredible
amount of coding and so on.

03:12:30.083 --> 03:12:33.844
- And on the third hand, like you said, we
already have approximation algorithms

03:12:33.924 --> 03:12:34.604
that-

03:12:34.643 --> 03:12:34.844
- Yes

03:12:34.983 --> 03:12:38.143
- ... that from a pragmatic
perspective, solve

03:12:38.803 --> 03:12:42.634
all the actual real engineering
problems of human civilization.

03:12:42.663 --> 03:12:46.374
- Like the SAT solvers work amazingly
well, you know, in lots and lots of

03:12:46.384 --> 03:12:50.364
cases, even though we can prove we don't expect...
If P is not equal to NP, then there won't

03:12:50.444 --> 03:12:55.403
be a polynomial time SAT solver.
But the actually the SAT solver

03:12:55.424 --> 03:12:58.453
approximations, you know,
are really quite amazing.

03:12:59.124 --> 03:13:02.813
- Sorry to ask the ridiculous question,
but who is the greatest mathematician...

03:13:02.813 --> 03:13:06.624
... of all time? Who are the
possible candidates? Euler,

03:13:06.663 --> 03:13:10.184
Gauss, Newton, Ramanujan, Hilbert. We

03:13:10.223 --> 03:13:14.672
mentioned Gödel, Turing, if
you throw him into the bucket.

03:13:14.723 --> 03:13:18.384
- So this is, I think, an
incredibly difficult question to

03:13:19.143 --> 03:13:22.924
answer. Personally, I don't
really think this way

03:13:23.003 --> 03:13:28.003
about ranking the
mathematicians by greatness.

03:13:28.024 --> 03:13:31.663
- So you don't have, like... You know, some people
have a Taylor Swift poster in their dorm room.

03:13:31.704 --> 03:13:32.983
You don't have it.

03:13:33.024 --> 03:13:37.534
- I mean, if you forced me to pick someone,
it would probably be Archimedes because-

03:13:37.534 --> 03:13:41.983
... he had such incredible
achievements in such an early

03:13:43.024 --> 03:13:49.604
era, which totally transcended the
work of the other people in his era.

03:13:49.614 --> 03:13:53.063
But I also have the view
that I want to learn

03:13:53.124 --> 03:13:56.983
mathematics and gain mathematical
insight from whoever can

03:13:57.044 --> 03:14:00.893
provide it and wherever I can
find it. And this isn't always

03:14:00.964 --> 03:14:04.864
just coming from the greats. And
sometimes the greats are doing things

03:14:05.104 --> 03:14:08.903
that are just first and not... You
know, somebody else could have easily

03:14:08.944 --> 03:14:12.884
been first. And so there's a kind of
luck aspect to it when you go back and

03:14:12.944 --> 03:14:16.624
look at, you know, the achievements.
And because of this progress

03:14:16.723 --> 03:14:20.473
issue in mathematics that we talked about
earlier, namely, we really do understand things

03:14:20.544 --> 03:14:24.124
much better now than they used
to. And when you look back at the

03:14:24.184 --> 03:14:27.864
achievements that had been made, then
maybe you can imagine, you know,

03:14:27.903 --> 03:14:31.743
thinking, "Well, you know, somebody
else could've, could've had

03:14:31.823 --> 03:14:35.663
that insight also." And maybe they

03:14:35.944 --> 03:14:39.924
would have. It's already a known
phenomenon that disparate mathematicians

03:14:40.044 --> 03:14:43.924
end up proving essentially similar
results at approximately the

03:14:43.983 --> 03:14:48.764
same time. But okay, the person who did
it first is getting the credit and so on.

03:14:48.803 --> 03:14:52.653
- What do you make of that? Because I see
that sometimes when mathematicians...

03:14:52.704 --> 03:14:56.413
This also applies in physics and
science, where completely separately,

03:14:57.544 --> 03:15:01.403
discoveries are made... ...Maybe at a
very similar time. What does that mean?

03:15:01.483 --> 03:15:05.063
- It's relatively common. I
mean, I think it's certain

03:15:05.163 --> 03:15:10.323
ideas are in the air and being thought
about but not fully articulated, and so

03:15:11.384 --> 03:15:13.643
this is the nature of growth in knowledge.

03:15:13.864 --> 03:15:15.924
- Do you understand where ideas come from?

03:15:16.044 --> 03:15:16.663
- Not really.

03:15:17.243 --> 03:15:21.983
- I mean, what's your own process when
you're thinking through a problem?

03:15:22.024 --> 03:15:25.444
- Yeah, that's another difficult
question. I suppose it has to do

03:15:25.483 --> 03:15:30.563
with... I mean, my mathematical style,
my style as a mathematician, is that

03:15:32.663 --> 03:15:36.524
I don't really like difficult mathematics.

03:15:37.583 --> 03:15:45.454
What I love is simple, clear,
easy-to-understand arguments that

03:15:45.583 --> 03:15:48.003
prove a surprising result.
That's my favorite

03:15:48.063 --> 03:15:51.992
situation. And actually, so the
question of whether it's a new result

03:15:52.011 --> 03:15:55.882
or not is somehow less important to
me. And so that has to do with this

03:15:55.912 --> 03:15:59.812
question of the greats and so on, whoever does
it first. Because I think, for example, if

03:15:59.851 --> 03:16:05.511
you prove a new result with a bad
argument or complicated argument,

03:16:07.011 --> 03:16:10.632
that's great because you proved
something new. But I still

03:16:10.732 --> 03:16:17.152
want to see the beautiful simple because
that's what I can understand. Also,

03:16:18.552 --> 03:16:21.891
I mean, I'm kind of naturally
skeptical about any

03:16:22.032 --> 03:16:26.052
complicated argument because
it might be wrong. And-

03:16:26.431 --> 03:16:30.011
...if I can't really understand
it fully, like every single

03:16:30.091 --> 03:16:34.032
step all at once in my head,
then I'm just worried maybe it's

03:16:34.052 --> 03:16:37.732
wrong. And so these different
styles, sometimes mathematicians get

03:16:37.771 --> 03:16:41.591
involved with these enormous
research projects that involve

03:16:41.992 --> 03:16:44.322
huge numbers of working parts and-

03:16:44.322 --> 03:16:48.232
...different technology coming together. I
mean, mathematical technology, not physical

03:16:48.271 --> 03:16:48.792
technology.

03:16:48.832 --> 03:16:52.792
- And sometimes it actually involves now more
and more something like the Lean programming

03:16:52.851 --> 03:16:54.862
language where some parts are
automated, so you have this gigantic-

03:16:54.912 --> 03:16:58.392
- Yeah, yeah, I see. Well, that's another
issue because maybe those things are, you

03:16:58.412 --> 03:17:02.122
know, less subject to
skepticism when it's validated-

03:17:02.122 --> 03:17:06.072
...by Lean. But I'm thinking about
the case where the arguments

03:17:06.112 --> 03:17:10.062
are just extremely complicated,
and so I sort of worry whether

03:17:10.072 --> 03:17:13.632
it's right or not, whereas you
know, I like the simple thing. And

03:17:13.672 --> 03:17:17.632
so, so I tend to have often
worked on things that are

03:17:17.692 --> 03:17:21.372
a little bit off the beaten
path from what other people are

03:17:21.412 --> 03:17:23.172
working on from that point of view.

03:17:23.212 --> 03:17:25.302
- Your curiosity draws
you towards simplicity.

03:17:25.332 --> 03:17:29.122
- Yeah. I wanna work on the things that
I can understand and that are s-

03:17:29.122 --> 03:17:36.511
And luckily, I've found that I've
been able to make contributions

03:17:36.692 --> 03:17:40.552
that other people seem to
like, you know, in this way,

03:17:40.612 --> 03:17:44.091
in this style. And so I've been kind
of fortunate from that point of view.

03:17:44.851 --> 03:17:50.242
I mean, my process always, though, and I've
recommended this always to my students,

03:17:51.872 --> 03:17:55.742
is just a kind of playful
curiosity. So whenever I have...

03:17:55.752 --> 03:18:03.452
whenever there's an idea or a topic,
then I just play around with it and

03:18:03.511 --> 03:18:07.422
change little things or
understand a basic case and then

03:18:07.452 --> 03:18:11.172
make it more complicated or press
things a little bit on this

03:18:11.232 --> 03:18:17.832
side or apply the idea to my favorite
example, you know, that's relevant or,

03:18:17.872 --> 03:18:21.282
and see what happens, or you just
play around with ideas, and this

03:18:21.372 --> 03:18:24.572
often leads to insights that then lead to

03:18:24.612 --> 03:18:28.382
more methods or more, you know,
then pretty soon you're making

03:18:28.392 --> 03:18:32.222
progress on the problem.
And so this is basically my

03:18:32.271 --> 03:18:36.261
method, is I just, you know, fool
around with the ideas until I can

03:18:36.431 --> 03:18:40.961
see a path through towards
something interesting.

03:18:41.372 --> 03:18:45.271
And then prove that, and that's
worked extremely well for me.

03:18:45.332 --> 03:18:47.712
So I'm pretty pleased with that method.

03:18:47.752 --> 03:18:51.572
- You do like thought experiments where you
anthropomorphize, like you mentioned?

03:18:51.612 --> 03:18:55.591
- Yeah, yeah. So this is a basic tool. I mean,
I use this all the time. You know, you

03:18:55.672 --> 03:19:00.011
imagine a set-theoretic
model, a model of ZFC as like

03:19:00.912 --> 03:19:04.712
a place where you're living, and you
might travel to distant lands by

03:19:04.792 --> 03:19:08.472
forcing, and this is a kind of metaphor for
what's going on. Of course, you know, the actual

03:19:08.552 --> 03:19:09.552
arguments aren't anything

03:19:10.392 --> 03:19:13.492
like that because there's not land, and
you're not traveling and you're not...

03:19:13.511 --> 03:19:16.021
- But you allow your mind to visualize that
kind of thing, in the natural real world.

03:19:16.032 --> 03:19:19.851
- And it helps you to understand, particularly
when there's parts of the argument that are in

03:19:19.872 --> 03:19:23.732
tension with one another, then you can
imagine that people are fighting or

03:19:23.771 --> 03:19:27.652
something. And those kind of metaphors,
you know, or you imagine it in

03:19:27.672 --> 03:19:31.632
terms of a game-theoretic, you know, two
players trying to win. So that's kind of

03:19:31.712 --> 03:19:35.681
tension. And those kind of metaphorical
ways of understanding a mathematical

03:19:35.752 --> 03:19:38.882
problem often are extremely
helpful in realizing,

03:19:38.952 --> 03:19:42.712
aha, the enemy is going to
pick this thing to be like

03:19:42.771 --> 03:19:46.702
that because, you know, it makes
it more continuous or whatever,

03:19:46.732 --> 03:19:50.542
and then we should do this other
thing in order to... So it

03:19:50.832 --> 03:19:54.351
makes you realize mathematical
strategies for finding the

03:19:54.452 --> 03:19:57.952
answer and proving the theorem that
you want to prove because of the

03:19:57.961 --> 03:20:01.832
ideas that come out of
that anthropomorphization.

03:20:01.841 --> 03:20:05.752
- What do you think of somebody like
Andrew Wiles, who spent seven years

03:20:05.812 --> 03:20:09.761
grinding at one of the hardest problems
in the history of mathematics? And

03:20:09.792 --> 03:20:13.431
maybe contrasting that a little bit with
somebody who's also brilliant, Terence

03:20:13.472 --> 03:20:17.332
Tao, who basically says
if he hits a wall, he

03:20:17.402 --> 03:20:21.011
just switches to a different problem
and he comes back and so on. So it's

03:20:21.792 --> 03:20:24.931
less of a focused grind
for many years without

03:20:25.091 --> 03:20:30.492
any guarantee that you'll get there,
which is what Andrew Wiles went through.

03:20:30.511 --> 03:20:32.612
Maybe Grigori Perelman did the same.

03:20:32.652 --> 03:20:36.542
- I mean, Wiles proved an amazing theorem,
the Fermat's Last Theorem result is

03:20:36.591 --> 03:20:40.232
incredible. This is a totally
different style than my own

03:20:40.392 --> 03:20:44.271
practice, though, of working
in isolation. I mean, for me,

03:20:44.332 --> 03:20:48.252
mathematics is often a kind
of social activity. I have-

03:20:48.351 --> 03:20:53.392
I counted, I mean, it's pushing towards
a hundred collaborators, co-authors on

03:20:53.472 --> 03:20:57.452
various papers and so on. And, you
know, anybody has an idea they

03:20:57.472 --> 03:21:01.132
want to talk about with me, if I'm
interested in it, then I'm gonna wanna

03:21:01.172 --> 03:21:04.882
collaborate with them and we might solve
the problem and have a joint paper or

03:21:04.892 --> 03:21:06.511
whatever. You wanna have
a joint paper? Let me-

03:21:06.532 --> 03:21:08.011
- Yeah, exactly. Let's go.

03:21:08.672 --> 03:21:12.132
- So my approach to, like,
making mathematical progress

03:21:12.732 --> 03:21:16.591
tends to involve working with other people
quite a lot rather than just working on

03:21:16.632 --> 03:21:20.892
my- ...own, and I enjoy that
aspect very much. So I,

03:21:20.952 --> 03:21:24.851
personally, I couldn't ever do what Wiles
did. Maybe I'm missing out. Maybe if

03:21:24.912 --> 03:21:28.312
I locked myself, you know, in the bedroom
and just worked on whatever, then,

03:21:29.112 --> 03:21:33.072
uh, I would solve it. But I tend
to think that no, actually, like

03:21:33.292 --> 03:21:37.271
being on MathOverflow so
much and I've gotten so

03:21:37.351 --> 03:21:41.232
many ideas, so many papers have
grown out of the MathOverflow

03:21:41.292 --> 03:21:45.082
conversations and back and forth. Someone
posts an, you know, someone posts a

03:21:45.112 --> 03:21:49.011
question and I post an answer on part of it, and
then someone else has an idea and it turns into a

03:21:49.052 --> 03:21:52.892
full solution, and then we have a three-way
paper coming out of that. That's happened

03:21:52.952 --> 03:21:56.876
many times. And so for
me, it's... I enjoy this

03:21:56.916 --> 03:22:00.776
kind of social aspect to it.
And it's not just the social

03:22:00.975 --> 03:22:06.555
part. Rather, that's the nature of
mathematical investigation as I see it, is

03:22:08.116 --> 03:22:11.836
putting forth mathematical
ideas to other people and they

03:22:12.356 --> 03:22:15.936
respond to it in a way that
helps me learn, helps them

03:22:16.016 --> 03:22:20.696
learn, and I think that's a very
productive way of undertaking mathematics.

03:22:20.776 --> 03:22:24.635
- I think it's when you work
solo on mathematics, from my

03:22:24.715 --> 03:22:28.635
outsider perspective, it
seems terrifyingly lonely.

03:22:28.655 --> 03:22:32.076
And because you're, especially
if you do stick to a single

03:22:32.215 --> 03:22:36.196
problem, especially if that
problem has broken many brilliant

03:22:36.235 --> 03:22:40.176
mathematicians in the past, that
you're really putting all your chips

03:22:40.276 --> 03:22:41.876
in. And just the torment-

03:22:41.885 --> 03:22:45.546
...the rollercoaster of day to...
that day. Because I imagine

03:22:47.395 --> 03:22:51.856
you have these moments of hopeful
break, mini breakthroughs, and then

03:22:52.916 --> 03:22:56.776
you have to deal with the
occasional realization

03:22:56.796 --> 03:23:00.696
that, no, it was not a breakthrough,
and that disappointment.

03:23:00.735 --> 03:23:04.715
And then you have to go,
like, a weekly, maybe daily

03:23:05.135 --> 03:23:08.776
disappointment where you hit a wall,
and you have no other person to

03:23:09.916 --> 03:23:16.126
brainstorm with. You have no
other avenue to pursue. And it's

03:23:17.016 --> 03:23:20.956
I don't know. The mental fortitude it
takes to go through that. But every-

03:23:20.996 --> 03:23:23.876
Everybody's different. Some
people are recluse and just

03:23:24.155 --> 03:23:32.126
really find solace in that lone
grind. I have to ask about

03:23:32.235 --> 03:23:36.155
Grisha Grigori Perelman. What
do you think of him famously

03:23:36.196 --> 03:23:38.956
declining the Fields Medal
and the Millennial Prize?

03:23:39.936 --> 03:23:43.876
So he stated, "I'm not interested
in money or fame. The prize is

03:23:43.916 --> 03:23:47.555
completely irrelevant to me. If
the proof is correct, then no

03:23:47.776 --> 03:23:52.496
other recognition is needed." What do
you think of him turning down the prize?

03:23:52.555 --> 03:23:56.315
- I guess what I think is that
mathematics is full of a

03:23:56.395 --> 03:23:59.676
lot of different kinds of
people. And my attitude is that,

03:24:00.096 --> 03:24:03.996
hey, it doesn't matter. Maybe they have
a good math idea, and so I want to

03:24:04.036 --> 03:24:07.876
talk to them and interact with
them. And so I think the Perelman

03:24:07.975 --> 03:24:14.336
case, you know, is maybe an
instance where, you know, he's

03:24:15.616 --> 03:24:19.565
such a brilliant mind and he
solved this extremely famous and

03:24:19.696 --> 03:24:23.436
difficult problem, and that
is a huge achievement.

03:24:23.536 --> 03:24:27.326
But he also had these
views about, you know,

03:24:27.376 --> 03:24:32.506
prizes and somehow, I don't really fully
understand why he would turn it down.

03:24:33.016 --> 03:24:36.616
- I do think I have a similar
thing, just observing Olympic

03:24:36.756 --> 03:24:40.715
athletes that, in many cases,
don't get paid very much,

03:24:40.735 --> 03:24:42.305
and they nevertheless dedicate their
entire lives for the pursuit...

03:24:42.305 --> 03:24:47.055
...of the gold medal. I think his case
is a reminder that some of the greatest

03:24:47.135 --> 03:24:51.096
mathematicians, some of the greatest
scientists and human beings do the thing

03:24:51.135 --> 03:24:54.475
they do, take on these
problems for the love

03:24:55.555 --> 03:24:59.135
of it, not for the prizes or
the money or any of that.

03:24:59.176 --> 03:25:02.895
Now, as you're saying, if the
money comes, you could use it for

03:25:02.956 --> 03:25:06.155
stuff. If the prizes come, and the
fame, and so on, that might be

03:25:06.235 --> 03:25:12.786
useful. But the reason fundamentally the
greats do it is because of the art itself.

03:25:13.235 --> 03:25:16.936
- Sure, I totally agree with that.
I mean, I share the view. That's,

03:25:16.975 --> 03:25:20.836
you know, that's why I'm a mathematician

03:25:20.936 --> 03:25:24.876
is because I find the question so
compelling and I've spent my whole life

03:25:24.916 --> 03:25:31.735
thinking about these problems.
But, you know, if I won an award -

03:25:32.356 --> 03:25:35.856
- Yeah, it's great. It's great. I mean,
I'm pretty sure you don't contribute to

03:25:35.895 --> 03:25:43.846
MathOverflow for the wealth,
and the power. That you gain.

03:25:43.856 --> 03:25:46.395
I mean, it's genuine curiosity.

03:25:46.436 --> 03:25:50.256
- Well, you asked who the
greatest mathematician is, and

03:25:50.266 --> 03:25:53.686
of course, if we want to be truly objective
about it, we would need a kind of an

03:25:53.696 --> 03:25:55.016
objective criteria.

03:25:55.025 --> 03:25:55.126
- Criteria, yeah.

03:25:55.126 --> 03:25:58.715
- About how to evaluate the
relative strength and the

03:25:58.756 --> 03:26:02.536
reputation of various mathematicians.
And so, of course, we should use

03:26:02.576 --> 03:26:04.846
MathOverflow score. ...Because -

03:26:06.155 --> 03:26:10.116
- That you're definitively. I mean, nobody's
objectively the greatest mathematician of

03:26:10.135 --> 03:26:10.676
all time.

03:26:10.686 --> 03:26:14.576
- Yes, that's true. I've also argued
that tenure and promotion decisions

03:26:14.616 --> 03:26:15.275
should be based...

03:26:15.296 --> 03:26:16.126
- Based on MathOverflow.

03:26:16.296 --> 03:26:20.876
- ...Yeah. So my daughter
introduced me to her boyfriend.

03:26:20.936 --> 03:26:25.846
and told me that she had
a boyfriend. And I, um-

03:26:25.916 --> 03:26:26.385
- asked him what his MathOverflow...

03:26:26.395 --> 03:26:30.196
- I wanted to know, first of
all, what is his chess rating,

03:26:30.235 --> 03:26:33.956
and secondly, what is
his MathOverflow score?

03:26:34.235 --> 03:26:38.135
- Oh, man. Well, that's the only way to
judge a person, I think. That's, I

03:26:38.235 --> 03:26:40.106
think, objectively correct. Yeah.

03:26:41.576 --> 03:26:45.496
I mean, since you bring up chess, I've got
to ask you about infinite chess. I can't let

03:26:45.555 --> 03:26:49.036
you go. You've, I mean, you worked on a
million things, but infinite chess is one of

03:26:49.076 --> 03:26:54.016
them. Somebody asked on MathOverflow,
the mathematical definition of chess.

03:26:54.076 --> 03:26:54.426
- Right.

03:26:54.456 --> 03:26:58.416
- So can we talk about the math of chess
and the math of infinite chess? What

03:26:58.436 --> 03:26:59.176
is infinite chess?

03:26:59.215 --> 03:27:03.086
- Oh, yeah, absolutely. Infinite chess
is fantastic. Chess ordinarily is

03:27:03.096 --> 03:27:07.076
played on this tiny, tiny board. It's
an eight by eight board, right? So

03:27:07.116 --> 03:27:10.796
when you play chess, normally it's on the
eight by eight board. But we want to play

03:27:10.876 --> 03:27:14.836
infinite chess, so on the, on the

03:27:15.055 --> 03:27:18.936
integer board. It's infinite
in all four directions, you

03:27:18.996 --> 03:27:22.856
know, but it still has the chessboard pattern,
and maybe there's pieces on this board,

03:27:22.895 --> 03:27:26.866
maybe infinitely many pieces we
allow. But one difference from

03:27:26.895 --> 03:27:33.055
finite ordinary chess, in infinite chess,
we don't play from a standard starting

03:27:33.076 --> 03:27:37.055
position. Rather, you... The

03:27:37.116 --> 03:27:40.965
interesting situation is that you present
a position where there's a lot of

03:27:40.975 --> 03:27:44.876
pieces already on the board in a complicated
way, and you say, "What would it

03:27:44.895 --> 03:27:48.536
be like to start from this position or
from that one?" You know, and we want to

03:27:48.555 --> 03:27:51.795
produce positions that have
interesting features, meaning

03:27:51.876 --> 03:27:56.715
mathematically interesting
features. And so I can tell you for

03:27:56.756 --> 03:28:04.712
example, probably a lot of people
are familiar with, say, the

03:28:04.832 --> 03:28:07.342
mate in two genre of chess problem.

03:28:07.352 --> 03:28:11.112
You know, you have a chess problem and it's
white to mate in two, which means that

03:28:11.392 --> 03:28:15.192
white is going to make two moves, but the
second move is going to be a checkmate.

03:28:15.252 --> 03:28:19.152
Or maybe mate in three or mate in
five or whatever. We can have mate in

03:28:19.392 --> 03:28:25.852
N positions for any N. I mean, in
infinite chess, you can create a position

03:28:26.692 --> 03:28:31.752
which is not mate in N for any N, but

03:28:33.632 --> 03:28:39.652
white has a winning strategy that will win
infinitely many moves. So in other words,

03:28:39.752 --> 03:28:43.312
let me say it again. There are
positions in infinite chess that

03:28:43.792 --> 03:28:47.672
white can definitely win.
Infinitely many moves, white is

03:28:47.692 --> 03:28:51.512
going to make checkmate.
But there's no particular N

03:28:51.572 --> 03:28:56.232
for which white can
guarantee to win in N moves.

03:28:56.292 --> 03:28:57.212
- There's no N?

03:28:57.252 --> 03:29:01.012
- No N. So it's not mate in N
for any N, but it's a white

03:29:01.092 --> 03:29:04.512
win, infinitely many. The
way to think about it is,

03:29:05.092 --> 03:29:09.532
white is going to win, but black
controls how long it takes.

03:29:09.592 --> 03:29:10.872
- Ah, got it.

03:29:10.932 --> 03:29:14.902
- But it's doomed. Black can say, "Well, I know
you're gonna win, but this time it's gonna...

03:29:14.912 --> 03:29:17.032
you're gonna take a
thousand moves at least."

03:29:17.072 --> 03:29:21.012
Or maybe in a different way of playing, black can say,
"Well, I know you're gonna win, but this time you're

03:29:21.032 --> 03:29:25.012
gonna have to take a million moves." For
any number, black can say that. So it's

03:29:25.052 --> 03:29:28.972
these really interesting positions.
There's a position in my first

03:29:29.032 --> 03:29:33.712
infinite chess paper. So it's black
to play in this position, and

03:29:34.692 --> 03:29:37.572
if black doesn't move that rook there,

03:29:38.692 --> 03:29:41.372
then white is gonna
checkmate pretty quickly.

03:29:41.392 --> 03:29:44.072
- By the way, can we describe
the rules of infinite chess?

03:29:44.792 --> 03:29:48.752
- Right. So the rules of infinite chess
are there's just the ordinary pieces,

03:29:48.792 --> 03:29:52.692
and they move on this infinite board, which
is just a chessboard, but extended in

03:29:52.732 --> 03:29:56.592
all directions- infinitely, with
no edge. So there's no boundary.

03:29:57.612 --> 03:30:01.532
But the pieces move just like you'd expect.
So the knights move just the same and the

03:30:02.052 --> 03:30:05.972
rooks move, you know, on the ranks and files,
and the bishops move on the same color

03:30:06.052 --> 03:30:09.972
diagonals and, just like you would expect,
except they can move as far as they

03:30:10.032 --> 03:30:12.702
want, you know, if there's no
intervening piece in the way.

03:30:13.772 --> 03:30:17.632
The one thing is that, okay,
so the white pawns always

03:30:17.752 --> 03:30:21.232
move upwards and the black pawns always
move downwards, but when they're

03:30:21.272 --> 03:30:25.132
capturing, the pawns, you know,
capture on the diagonal. So I

03:30:25.172 --> 03:30:28.892
think the piece movement is
pretty clear. There's a couple

03:30:28.972 --> 03:30:32.652
of differences that you have to pay
attention to from ordinary chess. For

03:30:32.672 --> 03:30:36.292
example, there's this threefold repetition

03:30:36.412 --> 03:30:40.252
rule in ordinary chess, but we
just get rid of this for infinite

03:30:40.272 --> 03:30:44.072
chess because, of course, threefold
repetition is just a proxy for infinite

03:30:44.192 --> 03:30:47.772
play. The real rule is
infinite play is a draw, not

03:30:47.832 --> 03:30:51.492
threefold repetition is a draw.
That's just a kind of convenient

03:30:51.652 --> 03:30:55.632
approximation to the, what I view
as the actual rule, which is that

03:30:55.712 --> 03:30:59.692
infinite play is a draw. So the only
way to win is to make checkmate on

03:30:59.732 --> 03:31:03.472
the board at a finite stage of play.
And if you play infinitely, you

03:31:03.512 --> 03:31:05.272
haven't done that, and so it's a draw.

03:31:05.312 --> 03:31:06.392
- And the pawns can't be converted into-

03:31:06.432 --> 03:31:10.172
- And there's no promotion 'cause
there's no edge. Right, exactly. And

03:31:10.372 --> 03:31:14.132
this position that we were just talking about
is a position with game value omega, which

03:31:14.192 --> 03:31:18.182
means that because it has
an ordinal value, white is

03:31:18.212 --> 03:31:21.712
going to win, but black can play as though

03:31:21.832 --> 03:31:25.492
counting down from omega. What is
the nature of counting down from

03:31:25.552 --> 03:31:29.512
omega? If you're black and you need
to count down from omega, then

03:31:30.592 --> 03:31:32.832
you have to say a finite number,

03:31:33.152 --> 03:31:36.792
and then after that, it's gonna
be at most that many numbers

03:31:36.892 --> 03:31:40.482
afterwards to count down, right? So the
nature of counting down from omega is

03:31:40.512 --> 03:31:44.412
that you take this giant
step on the first count,

03:31:44.952 --> 03:31:48.692
and then after that, you subtract one
each time. You can't subtract one from

03:31:48.732 --> 03:31:52.652
omega because that's not an ordinal. So
if you count down from omega, you have

03:31:52.692 --> 03:31:56.501
to go to some finite number, and then if
you just subtract one each time, then

03:31:56.532 --> 03:31:58.552
that's how many more moves you get.

03:31:58.592 --> 03:32:02.412
So that's the sense in which black
can make it take as long as he wants

03:32:02.452 --> 03:32:05.622
because he can pick his initial
number to be whatever he wants.

03:32:05.672 --> 03:32:09.662
- By the way, I just noticed that you were citing
a MathOverflow question, which is really

03:32:09.692 --> 03:32:10.402
cool.

03:32:10.452 --> 03:32:14.352
- That's right, yeah. My interest in infinite chess
was born on MathOverflow 'cause someone asked

03:32:14.392 --> 03:32:15.732
this question.

03:32:15.812 --> 03:32:19.691
- Noam Elkies asked this question. That's
so cool to see a MathOverflow citation

03:32:19.751 --> 03:32:26.362
in an arXiv paper. That's cool.
How do you construct the position-

03:32:28.052 --> 03:32:28.122
- Right

03:32:28.152 --> 03:32:31.752
- the position that satisfies this? Is
there an algorithm for construction?

03:32:31.772 --> 03:32:35.612
- No. This is an act of mathematical
creativity, really, to come up

03:32:35.672 --> 03:32:38.772
with... I had a co-author, my
co-author, Corey Evans. He's a

03:32:38.852 --> 03:32:42.672
US national master chess player.

03:32:42.692 --> 03:32:49.872
A very strong chess player. He's
also a philosophy professor of law.

03:32:49.932 --> 03:32:53.252
- Your collaborations are
wonderful. That's great.

03:32:53.292 --> 03:32:56.962
- So I met him because he was a grad student
at CUNY where I was at the time in New York.

03:32:57.032 --> 03:33:01.902
And also he was my son's chess
coach for when my son was

03:33:01.902 --> 03:33:05.232
playing chess competitively
in elementary school.

03:33:05.272 --> 03:33:08.792
Then Corey was the coach.
And so we knew him that

03:33:08.852 --> 03:33:12.472
way. And that was right around the
time when I was getting interested in

03:33:12.512 --> 03:33:19.282
infinite chess, and I knew I needed
a chess-knowledgeable partner. And

03:33:19.352 --> 03:33:23.492
so Corey was invaluable
for the paper because

03:33:25.112 --> 03:33:28.772
the proofs in infinite chess are extremely

03:33:28.852 --> 03:33:32.822
finicky because you
create these positions,

03:33:32.892 --> 03:33:36.712
but the details of the argument
have to do with kind of chess

03:33:36.772 --> 03:33:40.692
reasoning, you know? My chess reasoning

03:33:40.792 --> 03:33:44.732
wasn't quite up to it
because I would create

03:33:44.752 --> 03:33:48.672
the positions. Almost all the
positions are ones that I made,

03:33:48.712 --> 03:33:50.942
but this is like after many generations,

03:33:50.942 --> 03:33:54.872
of being corrected by Corey because Corey
would come and say, "Hey, you know, this pawn

03:33:54.932 --> 03:33:57.322
is hanging, and it breaks
your argument, and"

03:33:57.322 --> 03:34:03.374
"or, or, you know, this bishop can leak
out" "of the cage," or whatever. And so...

03:34:03.374 --> 03:34:07.024
the process was I knew kind of

03:34:07.384 --> 03:34:10.694
in terms of these ordinals
what we needed to create with

03:34:10.724 --> 03:34:14.684
the position, and I would struggle to
do it and create something that sort

03:34:14.724 --> 03:34:18.503
of had the features that I wanted, and then
I would show it to Corey and he would say,

03:34:18.524 --> 03:34:22.424
"Look, it doesn't work because of this and
that," and so on. And so this kind of back and

03:34:22.524 --> 03:34:26.003
forth was extremely helpful to me, and
eventually we, you know, converged

03:34:26.144 --> 03:34:29.984
on arguments that were correct.

03:34:30.044 --> 03:34:33.824
So it's... yeah, it's quite
interesting. Also, maybe

03:34:33.864 --> 03:34:37.454
another thing to say is the follow-up
paper to this one was a three-way

03:34:37.564 --> 03:34:41.244
paper with also Corey and myself and my

03:34:41.284 --> 03:34:44.913
PhD student, Norman Perlmutter,
in which we improved the bound.

03:34:44.984 --> 03:34:48.744
So we were aiming to produce more and more chess
positions with higher and higher ordinal values.

03:34:48.984 --> 03:34:52.464
chess positions with higher
and higher ordinal values.

03:34:52.524 --> 03:34:56.464
So the initial position was value omega, and then we
made omega-squared and omega-cubed in the first paper,

03:34:56.503 --> 03:35:00.473
omega-squared and omega-cubed in the first paper, and then
in this three-way collaboration, we made omega to the 4th.

03:35:00.503 --> 03:35:03.764
then in this three-way collaboration,
we made omega to the 4th.

03:35:03.824 --> 03:35:07.364
- The title of the paper: The Position
in Infinite Chess with Game Value

03:35:07.384 --> 03:35:09.044
Omega to the 4th.

03:35:09.444 --> 03:35:13.424
- Right. And so, at the time,
this was the best-known result,

03:35:13.744 --> 03:35:17.524
the sort of state of the art, but
since that time, it's been improved

03:35:17.583 --> 03:35:22.583
now dramatically. And, in fact, we
know now that every countable ordinal

03:35:22.594 --> 03:35:28.874
arises as the game value of a position in
infinite chess, so it's a fantastic result.

03:35:28.904 --> 03:35:36.503
- Before I forget, let me ask about your
views on AI and LLMs that are getting

03:35:37.564 --> 03:35:41.304
better and better in mathematics. We've spoken
about collaborators, and you have so many

03:35:41.364 --> 03:35:47.824
collaborators. Do you see AI as a
potential great collaborator to you as a

03:35:47.864 --> 03:35:50.854
mathematician, and what do you
think the future role of those-

03:35:50.854 --> 03:35:51.984
kinds of AI systems is?

03:35:52.583 --> 03:35:56.464
- I guess I would draw a distinction
between what we have currently

03:35:56.624 --> 03:36:03.003
and what might come in future years. I've
played around with it and I've tried

03:36:03.604 --> 03:36:07.324
experimenting, but I haven't
found it helpful at all,

03:36:07.484 --> 03:36:10.384
basically zero. It's not helpful to me.

03:36:10.583 --> 03:36:14.484
helpful to me. And, you know, I've
used various systems and so on, the

03:36:14.524 --> 03:36:22.344
paid models and so on. My typical
experience is interacting with AI on a

03:36:22.384 --> 03:36:26.364
mathematical question is
that it gives me garbage

03:36:26.544 --> 03:36:30.204
answers that are not
mathematically correct.

03:36:30.304 --> 03:36:36.134
And so I find that not
helpful and also frustrating.

03:36:36.144 --> 03:36:40.083
Like, if I was interacting
with a person, the frustrating

03:36:40.124 --> 03:36:44.104
thing is when you have to argue
about whether or not, you know, the

03:36:44.264 --> 03:36:47.344
argument that they gave you is right,
and you point out exactly the error,

03:36:47.354 --> 03:36:50.704
in the AI saying, "Oh,
it's totally fine." And,

03:36:52.564 --> 03:36:56.524
you know, if I were having such an
experience with a person, I would simply

03:36:56.564 --> 03:36:58.594
refuse to talk to that person again.

03:36:58.604 --> 03:37:02.003
But okay, one has to overlook
these kind of flaws.

03:37:02.024 --> 03:37:09.464
And so I tend to be a kind of skeptic about
the value of the current AI systems as

03:37:09.503 --> 03:37:13.484
far as mathematical reasoning
is concerned. It seems not

03:37:13.524 --> 03:37:17.384
reliable. Okay, but I know for a

03:37:17.503 --> 03:37:21.244
fact that many, that there are several
prominent mathematicians whom I have

03:37:21.284 --> 03:37:27.374
enormous respect for, who are saying
that they are using it in a way

03:37:27.374 --> 03:37:31.163
that's helpful, and I'm often
very surprised to hear that

03:37:31.484 --> 03:37:36.524
based on my own experience, which
is quite the opposite. And so

03:37:37.663 --> 03:37:41.413
maybe my process isn't any good,
although, you know, I use it for other

03:37:41.424 --> 03:37:44.764
things, like, you know,
for programming things or

03:37:44.864 --> 03:37:48.594
for image generation and
so on. It's amazingly

03:37:48.644 --> 03:37:52.604
powerful and helpful. But
for mathematical arguments,

03:37:52.704 --> 03:37:59.003
I haven't found it helpful, and maybe I'm
not interacting with it in the right way.

03:37:59.184 --> 03:38:02.904
Yet, or it could be. And so
maybe I just need to improve my

03:38:03.024 --> 03:38:10.244
skill. But also maybe I wonder,
like, these examples that

03:38:10.264 --> 03:38:13.844
are provided by other people maybe
involved quite a huge amount of

03:38:13.884 --> 03:38:17.764
interaction, and so I wonder
if maybe the mathematical

03:38:17.824 --> 03:38:21.304
ideas are really coming from the person,
you know, these great mathematicians

03:38:21.314 --> 03:38:27.684
who are doing it rather than the AI. And
so so I tend to be kind of skeptical. But

03:38:27.764 --> 03:38:31.964
also, I'm skeptical for
another reason, and that is

03:38:34.163 --> 03:38:37.784
because of the nature of the
large language model approach

03:38:38.324 --> 03:38:48.503
to AI doing mathematics. Um, I recognize
that the AI is trying to give me

03:38:48.564 --> 03:38:52.184
an argument that sounds
like a proof rather than an

03:38:52.324 --> 03:38:59.864
argument that is a proof. The
motivation is misplaced. And so I

03:38:59.964 --> 03:39:03.744
worry that this is a very
dangerous source of error

03:39:03.864 --> 03:39:07.764
because it often happens in
mathematics that, I mean, if I

03:39:07.804 --> 03:39:11.663
think back to when I was an undergrad,
you know, here at Caltech, and I

03:39:11.704 --> 03:39:15.594
was a math major eventually, and at that

03:39:15.644 --> 03:39:19.594
time, LaTeX was a pretty new thing,
and I was learning LaTeX, and

03:39:19.624 --> 03:39:24.694
so I was typing up my homeworks in
LaTeX and they looked beautiful.

03:39:24.724 --> 03:39:28.134
Actually, they looked like garbage.
From my current standards,

03:39:28.134 --> 03:39:29.644
I'm sure it was terrible.

03:39:29.663 --> 03:39:33.024
Except at the time, you know, I didn't
know anything. I was an undergrad,

03:39:33.224 --> 03:39:37.054
and LaTeX was sort of unheard of.

03:39:37.304 --> 03:39:40.294
And so I was producing these
beautifully typeset, you know,

03:39:40.294 --> 03:39:44.234
problem sets, solutions, and so on. And

03:39:44.324 --> 03:39:47.704
I would print it up and submit it and
so on, and the grades would come back,

03:39:47.784 --> 03:39:52.094
terrible grades. And I
realized what was happening

03:39:52.094 --> 03:39:57.764
is that the, you know,
the copy was so beautiful

03:39:58.083 --> 03:40:01.884
mathematically typeset in this way. It looked
like the kind of mathematics you find in a

03:40:01.944 --> 03:40:02.644
book, you know?

03:40:02.654 --> 03:40:06.284
Because basically that's the only time you saw
that kind of mathematical typesetting was in

03:40:06.344 --> 03:40:10.324
a, in a professional, you
know, published book.

03:40:10.333 --> 03:40:13.672
And those me- that mathematics
was almost always correct-

03:40:13.672 --> 03:40:20.024
... in a book, right? And so I
had somehow, you know, lost my-

03:40:20.872 --> 03:40:24.852
... because it was so beautiful, and I'm
used to only seeing that kind of type

03:40:24.892 --> 03:40:27.942
setting when an argument was,
you know, totally right-

03:40:27.942 --> 03:40:31.032
... I wasn't critical enough, and
making these sort of bonehead

03:40:31.072 --> 03:40:36.292
mistakes in the proofs. And, and so,
okay, so I, I corrected this, of course.

03:40:36.312 --> 03:40:40.122
- But this kind of effect is very much real
with the modern LLM system. That's right.

03:40:40.122 --> 03:40:44.032
- And so I think that the chat programs

03:40:44.072 --> 03:40:46.692
and so on are producing
these arguments that look

03:40:46.772 --> 03:40:50.672
really, they look like a... that's
what they're striving to do,

03:40:50.692 --> 03:40:54.532
that it's what they're designed
to do. They're not designed to

03:40:54.552 --> 03:40:58.272
make a logically correct argument.
They're designed to make something that

03:40:58.412 --> 03:41:01.992
looks like a logically correct
argument. And it's easy to get

03:41:02.072 --> 03:41:05.732
fooled if you're not skeptical. And
so that's why I worry a bit when

03:41:05.772 --> 03:41:09.692
people rely on AI for
mathematical arguments.

03:41:10.332 --> 03:41:13.892
I mean, using... tying them
to Lean in the formal proof,

03:41:13.992 --> 03:41:17.562
um verification systems and so
on, this is a totally different

03:41:17.632 --> 03:41:20.992
way of operating. But for the sort of
ordinary person sitting down and using

03:41:21.052 --> 03:41:23.712
chat to come up with a mathematical

03:41:23.792 --> 03:41:27.662
argument, I think it's a dangerous
source of error if you're

03:41:27.732 --> 03:41:31.202
not especially attuned
to this very issue that

03:41:31.712 --> 03:41:35.612
the AI is going to produce
something that's not grounded in

03:41:35.652 --> 03:41:39.572
mathematical understanding, but
rather something that is trying

03:41:39.612 --> 03:41:41.942
to look like something that is grounded

03:41:41.942 --> 03:41:45.602
in mathematical understanding. And those
are not the same thing at all. And

03:41:46.572 --> 03:41:50.092
furthermore, I really wonder if
one can make a kind of system for

03:41:50.192 --> 03:41:56.272
producing genuine mathematical insight
that isn't based in what I would view as

03:41:56.812 --> 03:42:00.782
mathematical understanding
as opposed to the text

03:42:00.852 --> 03:42:04.732
generation systems. The methods
that are used, you know, they

03:42:04.772 --> 03:42:08.732
don't seem close enough grounded in
understanding of the underlying mathematical

03:42:08.792 --> 03:42:12.732
concepts, but rather grounded in

03:42:12.792 --> 03:42:16.452
the way words appear on a page in
arguments about those concepts, which are

03:42:16.492 --> 03:42:17.832
not the same.

03:42:17.872 --> 03:42:22.012
- So there's a couple of things to say there.
So one, I think there is a real skill in

03:42:23.132 --> 03:42:29.112
providing the LLM system with enough
information to be a good collaborator.

03:42:29.132 --> 03:42:33.112
Because you really are dealing with a different...
It's not a human being. You really have to load

03:42:33.212 --> 03:42:37.152
in everything you possibly
can from your body of

03:42:37.252 --> 03:42:40.992
work, from the way you're thinking,
and that's a real skill. And then the

03:42:41.032 --> 03:42:44.932
other thing is, you know, for
me, if it's at all anything

03:42:44.992 --> 03:42:48.862
like programming, because I have a
lot of colleagues and friends who

03:42:48.892 --> 03:42:55.812
are programmers who kind of feel
similarly to you. And for me, I've

03:42:55.872 --> 03:42:59.732
gotten better and better and
better at giving as much

03:42:59.792 --> 03:43:03.672
information as possible to the systems
in a really structured way, maybe

03:43:03.692 --> 03:43:07.612
because I just like natural
language as a way to express

03:43:07.652 --> 03:43:11.592
my thinking. And then the
benefit comes from the

03:43:11.652 --> 03:43:15.432
inspiration that the system
can provide by its ability to

03:43:16.872 --> 03:43:20.392
know a lot of things and
make connections between

03:43:20.432 --> 03:43:25.492
disparate fields and between disparate
concepts. And in that way, it provides

03:43:26.352 --> 03:43:29.392
not the answer but the inspiration, the

03:43:29.472 --> 03:43:33.432
handholding, the camaraderie
that helps me get to the

03:43:33.492 --> 03:43:41.352
answer, because it does know a lot more
than me. Know, like knowledge. And if you

03:43:41.472 --> 03:43:47.232
give it a lot of information and ask the
broader questions, it can make some really

03:43:47.252 --> 03:43:51.012
beautiful connections. But
I do find that I have to be

03:43:51.052 --> 03:43:53.272
extremely patient, like you said.

03:43:53.292 --> 03:43:57.152
The, the amount of times
I'll do something dumb where

03:43:57.232 --> 03:44:01.152
I feel like, "Uh, you don't get this at
all, do you?" That's a source of a lot

03:44:01.172 --> 03:44:04.882
of frustration for us humans.
Like, "This... Wait, this

03:44:04.912 --> 03:44:08.812
thing doesn't understand at all." If
you can have the patience to look past

03:44:08.892 --> 03:44:15.932
that, there might be some brilliant
little insights that it can provide.

03:44:16.012 --> 03:44:16.482
- Right.

03:44:16.482 --> 03:44:20.172
- At least for me in the realm
of programming. I should say

03:44:20.212 --> 03:44:23.232
programming, there's just so much
training data. There's so much

03:44:23.252 --> 03:44:27.112
there. And at least I see

03:44:27.352 --> 03:44:31.262
the light at the end of the
tunnel of promising possibilities

03:44:31.292 --> 03:44:33.412
of it being a good
collaborator, versus like

03:44:35.032 --> 03:44:38.902
something that gives you really
true genius-level insights.

03:44:39.251 --> 03:44:43.212
- Right. It's probably true. Uh,
I also find it likely that a

03:44:43.232 --> 03:44:47.332
lot of the... As far as mathematical
training data is concerned,

03:44:48.552 --> 03:44:52.802
I just have to assume that math overflow
answers are part of the training data.

03:44:52.892 --> 03:44:53.252
- Yes, of course.

03:44:53.392 --> 03:44:54.712
- It's so...

03:44:54.722 --> 03:44:56.092
- And you're...

03:44:56.172 --> 03:44:56.232
- So-

03:44:56.252 --> 03:44:57.872
- I mean, you're talking to
yourself, essentially.

03:44:57.892 --> 03:45:00.412
- Yeah, maybe.

03:45:00.632 --> 03:45:05.792
- Sorry for the ridiculously big
question, but what idea in mathematics

03:45:06.772 --> 03:45:09.922
is most beautiful to you?
We've talked about so many.

03:45:10.672 --> 03:45:14.382
- The most beautiful idea
in mathematics is the

03:45:14.382 --> 03:45:17.912
transfinite ordinals. These
were the number system

03:45:17.972 --> 03:45:21.472
invented by Georg Cantor
about counting beyond

03:45:21.512 --> 03:45:23.962
infinity, just the idea of
counting beyond infinity.

03:45:24.992 --> 03:45:28.692
I mean, you count through the ordinary
numbers, the natural numbers: zero, one, two,

03:45:28.712 --> 03:45:35.282
three, and so on. And then you're not done
because after that comes omega, and then

03:45:35.332 --> 03:45:39.252
omega plus one, and omega plus
two, and so on. And you can always

03:45:39.292 --> 03:45:43.222
add one. And so of course
after you count through

03:45:43.292 --> 03:45:46.872
all those numbers of the form
omega plus N, then you get to

03:45:47.572 --> 03:45:51.372
omega plus omega, the first
number after all those. And

03:45:51.452 --> 03:45:55.122
then comes omega plus omega plus
one, and so on. You can always add

03:45:55.212 --> 03:45:58.612
one. And so you can just keep counting
through the ordinals. It never

03:45:58.692 --> 03:46:02.232
ends. Eventually, you get to
omega times three, omega times

03:46:02.292 --> 03:46:06.262
four, and so on. And then the limit of
those numbers, the first number that

03:46:06.292 --> 03:46:09.992
comes after all those numbers
will be omega squared.

03:46:10.052 --> 03:46:13.492
And this one is the first
compound limit ordinal

03:46:13.532 --> 03:46:16.812
because it's a limit ordinal,
is one of these numbers, an

03:46:16.892 --> 03:46:20.872
ordinal that doesn't have an
immediate predecessor like omega and

03:46:20.932 --> 03:46:24.472
omega times two, omega times three.
Those are all limit ordinals.

03:46:24.542 --> 03:46:28.440
But omega squared is a limit
ordinal, but it's also a

03:46:28.640 --> 03:46:32.410
limit of limit ordinals
because the omega times three,

03:46:32.520 --> 03:46:36.180
omega times four, and so on, those are
all limit ordinals that limit up to omega

03:46:36.280 --> 03:46:40.160
squared. And then, of course, you
form omega squared plus one, and

03:46:40.200 --> 03:46:44.020
then omega squared plus two, and so
on, and it never stops. And it's

03:46:44.080 --> 03:46:47.160
just absolutely beautiful and amazing, and

03:46:47.720 --> 03:46:51.140
furthermore, forms the
foundation for these

03:46:51.160 --> 03:46:54.940
transfinite recursive constructions
that came later. I mean

03:46:55.000 --> 03:47:02.730
starting with the Cantor-Bendixson theorem
that I mentioned. And continuing with,

03:47:02.840 --> 03:47:06.720
the construction of the V hierarchy

03:47:06.820 --> 03:47:10.580
and Gödel's constructible
universe is built this way,

03:47:10.640 --> 03:47:14.440
and Zermelo's proof of the
well-order principle using the

03:47:14.480 --> 03:47:18.360
axiom of choice is a transfinite
recursive construction. And,

03:47:18.420 --> 03:47:22.220
and so the idea of just
counting past infinity

03:47:22.300 --> 03:47:27.660
is so simple and elegant, and has led
to so much fascinating mathematics.

03:47:27.720 --> 03:47:30.520
- Yeah, the infinity's not
the end. And what about

03:47:30.600 --> 03:47:34.680
philosophy? What to you is the
most beautiful idea in philosophy?

03:47:35.560 --> 03:47:39.640
- So I have a foot in both fields:
philosophy and mathematics, and

03:47:41.120 --> 03:47:47.510
in some contexts I seem to be required to
choose whether I'm a mathematician or a

03:47:47.520 --> 03:47:50.920
philosopher. I mean, my training is in
mathematics. My PhD, all my degrees are

03:47:50.960 --> 03:47:54.900
mathematics. But somehow I turned
myself into a philosopher over

03:47:54.920 --> 03:47:58.600
the years because my mathematical work
was engaging with these philosophical

03:47:58.700 --> 03:48:02.470
issues. And so when I went... In New

03:48:02.520 --> 03:48:06.240
York, I had appointments first in
mathematics only, but then eventually I was

03:48:06.280 --> 03:48:09.820
also joining the philosophy
faculty at the graduate

03:48:09.920 --> 03:48:13.580
center. And when I went to Oxford for the
first time, my main appointment was in

03:48:13.620 --> 03:48:15.540
philosophy, and that's also true now

03:48:16.480 --> 03:48:20.100
at Notre Dame although I'm
also a concurrent professor in

03:48:20.140 --> 03:48:25.320
mathematics. And I have math PhD students
still and philosophy PhD students. And so

03:48:26.160 --> 03:48:32.300
I don't really care to decide whether
I'm a mathematician or a philosopher.

03:48:32.340 --> 03:48:35.560
And my work is engaging
with mathematics and with

03:48:35.600 --> 03:48:38.940
philosophical issues in
mathematics and with plain

03:48:38.980 --> 03:48:42.840
philosophy, and there's
this ample region between

03:48:42.900 --> 03:48:46.100
these re- between these two
subjects. So it's not necessary to

03:48:46.200 --> 03:48:49.390
choose. I remember when I first
went to Oxford and I told my

03:48:49.440 --> 03:48:53.400
daughter that I was going to become
professor of philosophy in Oxford,

03:48:54.260 --> 03:48:58.190
And she looked at me
plaintively and said, "Uh,

03:48:59.260 --> 03:49:03.060
but, but Papa, you're not a
philosopher. Because in her

03:49:03.160 --> 03:49:07.000
mind, you know, her father was the
mathematician and her mother was the

03:49:07.040 --> 03:49:10.120
philosopher 'cause my wife, Barbara, is a

03:49:10.340 --> 03:49:17.489
philosopher. Now also at Notre Dame.
We're together there. And okay, but

03:49:17.820 --> 03:49:21.720
fortunately, I don't really have
to choose between them. So you

03:49:21.730 --> 03:49:25.700
ask about the most beautiful idea in
philosophy, and I would have to say

03:49:25.780 --> 03:49:32.880
that I think it's the distinction between
truth and proof, the one that we discussed

03:49:33.000 --> 03:49:39.700
already. Um, it's, it's so profound and

03:49:40.620 --> 03:49:44.600
gets at the heart of so many
philosophical issues. I

03:49:44.620 --> 03:49:48.610
mean, of course this is a distinction
that's maybe born in mathematics

03:49:48.640 --> 03:49:52.380
or mathematical logic, but that's
already philosophical to a

03:49:52.400 --> 03:49:59.580
degree, and it's ph- you know, fundamentally
a philosophical distinction. The

03:49:59.640 --> 03:50:01.700
truth is about the,

03:50:03.040 --> 03:50:06.500
nature of the world and the way
things are. It's about objective

03:50:06.560 --> 03:50:10.520
reality in a sense.
Whereas proof is about our

03:50:10.580 --> 03:50:14.560
understanding of the world
and about how we come

03:50:14.620 --> 03:50:18.900
to know the things that
we know about the world.

03:50:18.940 --> 03:50:25.200
And so to focus on proof is to focus
on the interaction that we have with

03:50:26.020 --> 03:50:29.989
the objective reality. And, okay,
I'm talking about the reality

03:50:30.000 --> 03:50:33.940
of mathematics, not the physical world, because,
as I said, I live in the Platonic realm

03:50:33.960 --> 03:50:37.660
and I interact with
mathematical reality, and so

03:50:37.800 --> 03:50:41.720
proof is about the interaction
and how we come to know the

03:50:41.760 --> 03:50:45.000
facts that are true in this mathematical

03:50:45.040 --> 03:50:48.860
reality, whereas truth is
about what's really the case,

03:50:48.920 --> 03:50:56.400
sort of apart from our knowledge of
it. And this is, I think, such a

03:50:56.440 --> 03:51:00.380
core way that I have of
understanding the world

03:51:00.420 --> 03:51:03.500
and the nature of logic and reasonings.

03:51:03.560 --> 03:51:06.900
- And the gap between the
two is full of fascinating

03:51:06.940 --> 03:51:10.740
mysteries, both in the Platonic
realm, but also in the

03:51:10.780 --> 03:51:14.760
physics realm, and I would
even say in the human

03:51:15.260 --> 03:51:18.740
psychology, sociology,
politics, geopolitics, all of

03:51:18.820 --> 03:51:22.680
it, if you think about proof more
generally, which is the process

03:51:22.720 --> 03:51:30.960
of discovery versus the truth itself.
And that's our journey whatever

03:51:31.000 --> 03:51:37.300
field we're in. Well, I
for one, am grateful for

03:51:37.310 --> 03:51:40.880
how marvelous of a philosopher,
mathematician, and human being you

03:51:40.960 --> 03:51:43.450
are. It's truly an honor
to speak with you today.

03:51:43.460 --> 03:51:47.340
- Well, thank you so much. It's such a pleasure
to be here, and thank you for inviting me.

03:51:47.400 --> 03:51:51.040
- Thanks for listening to this
conversation with Joel David Hamkins.

